<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-01 00:15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Eric Lindros May Return to Flyers  </HEADLINE>
By ROB MAADDI
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHILADELPHIA (AP) -- Eric Lindros waited until the final hours to
let the team that stripped him of his captain's job and made him an
outcast know if he would return.
</P>
<P>
   After a tumultuous season marked by a feud with general manager
Bob Clarke and four concussions in five months, Lindros was
expected to sign the Philadelphia Flyers' $8.5 million qualifying
offer.
</P>
<P>
   He had until 12:01 a.m. Tuesday to sign the offer sheet. Team
officials said Monday that Lindros had yet to sign, and they were
not sure when they would receive the fax.
</P>
<P>
   However, the team's offices closed at 9:30 p.m., so a signed
copy of the offer sheet could have been sitting in the tray of a
fax machine in an empty room.
</P>
<P>
   ''We've got lots of time left today,'' Lindros said Monday
before participating in a charity golf tournament in Ontario.
</P>
<P>
   ''I can't comment on anything at this point,'' Carl Lindros,
Eric's father and agent, said late Monday night.
</P>
<P>
   The qualifying offer included a two-way contract that would
allow the Flyers to send Lindros to their AHL affiliate, the
Philadelphia Phantoms, and pay him a minor league salary of
$85,000.
</P>
<P>
   If Lindros signed the offer sheet, it doesn't guarantee he will
wear a Flyers uniform.
</P>
<P>
   Lindros, still recovering from his sixth concussion, was
examined recently by Dr. James Kelly, a neurologist in Chicago, and
an independent doctor in Montreal.
</P>
<P>
   ''They both had similar timelines as far as December, January as
far as coming back playing,'' Lindros said. ''I'm going to continue
with my therapy and be ready when I'm ready. If I was to jump in at
the start of the year, I'd be playing with fire.''
</P>
<P>
   That could lead to further trouble with the Flyers because
Clarke has already said that the team's physicians believe Lindros
will be healthy enough to start the season.
</P>
<P>
   Lindros has a $20 million insurance policy that covers him this
season. If he doesn't play 20 games, the 27-year-old star center
will receive the full premium tax-free.
</P>
<P>
   When he submitted the qualifying offer, Clarke seemed to reach
out to Lindros, and call for a truce.
</P>
<P>
   ''On a personal level, I greatly regret the extent to which the
relationship between myself and Eric and his family has
deteriorated,'' Clarke said. ''I intend to do whatever I can to try
to move this relationship onto a better course.''
</P>
<P>
   Two weeks later Clarke urged Lindros to look past their
contentious relationship.
</P>
<P>
   ''It'd be nice if we got along, but it's not necessary in my
opinion,'' Clarke said. ''You're a hockey player, you play for your
coach and your teammates. Lots of players don't like their
managers, but you still play for your teammates and that's what we
encourage him to look at.''
</P>
<P>
   Lindros had 28 goals and 32 assists in 57 games last season,
including four periods of the playoffs. He has made six All-Star
teams and won an MVP award in 1995, but the Flyers lost in their
only Stanley Cup final with him.
</P>
<P>
   Lindros came to Philadelphia in 1992 following a trade with
Quebec that included six players, two first-round draft choices and
$15 million.
</P>
<P>
   Lindros' relationship with Clarke, his childhood hero,
deteriorated to a point last season where the two men didn't speak
for months.
</P>
<P>
   The boiling point came after Lindros criticized the team's
medical staff for failing to diagnose his second concussion of the
season on March 4.
</P>
<P>
   Clarke then stripped Lindros of his captaincy, and the star was
ostracized from the team until he returned for Games 6 and 7 of the
Eastern Conference finals against New Jersey.
</P>
<P>
   Clarke had an even bigger problem with Lindros' parents. He
accused Carl and Bonnie Lindros of meddling in team matters and
running their son's life.
</P>
<P>
   ''We don't want his mom and dad. We've had enough of them,''
Clarke said after the season.
</P>
<P>
   The relationship between the Lindros family and the Flyers
soured further after Lindros suffered a collapsed lung on April 1,
1999, in Nashville.
</P>
<P>
   The potentially life-threatening injury was diagnosed the
following day. After the injury, Lindros and his family had little
confidence in the team's medical staff.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
