<HEADLINE> AP Top News at Midnight EDT  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 Monday, July 31, 2000
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Republicans Open 37th National Convention
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   PHILADELPHIA (AP) -- Determined to send George W. Bush to the White House,
Republicans opened their 37th national convention Monday with a meticulously
scripted appeal to voters in the political middle. Colin Powell praised the
Texas governor's ''passion for inclusion,'' and bluntly challenged the GOP to
follow his lead. Bush knows ''that the party of Lincoln has not always carried
the mantle of Lincoln,'' Powell told delegates and a nationwide television
audience. ''He wants the Republican Party to wear that mantle again.''
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Co. To Start Web-Based Gene Project
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   SAN JOSE, Calif. (AP) -- DNA Sciences Inc. is banking on the Internet's vast
reach to give it a strategic edge in the crowded field of genetic research. On
Tuesday, the Mountain View-based company launched a large-scale gene research
project that uses the Internet to collect medical information from any willing
donors, healthy and ill, in the United States. Using this information, DNA
Sciences will determine which donors fit into various patient profiles for 20
common diseases the company wishes to study. Blood samples will be taken from
these donors, and the samples will be used to determine gene variations that
could lead to better drugs and medical treatments for the diseases.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Countries Accused In S.Leone War
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   UNITED NATIONS (AP) -- The United States and Britain publicly accused Liberia
and Burkina Faso on Monday of fueling the war in Sierra Leone by helping its
notorious rebels sell diamonds and buy arms. ''The United States intends to
support measures against both Burkina Faso and Liberia unless they cease their
support for the war in Sierra Leone,'' U.S. Ambassador Richard Holbrooke warned.
U.S. officials said the measures under consideration include freezing the
foreign assets of both countries and visa restrictions on senior officials.
Washington is also prepared to reexamine U.S. assistance, the officials said.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Power Outage at Sydney Airport
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   SYDNEY, Australia (AP) -- Sydney Airport's control tower had its second power
outage in less than a month Tuesday, grounding aircraft for an hour and leaving
passengers facing lengthy delays. The brief power outage again set alarm bells
ringing with less than 50 days to go before the Olympic Games and the airport's
busiest weeks ever. The Olympics begin Sept. 15 in Sydney.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Rebel Leader Charged, Probe Goes On
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   SUVA, Fiji (AP) -- Rebel leader George Speight has been charged with crimes
related to a wave of civil unrest in Fiji that followed his coup in May, police
said Tuesday. The charges -- against Speight and a small group of key advisers
-- did not include treason, although an investigation into that charge was still
underway, assistant Police Commissioner Moses Driver said. The charges also fell
outside an amnesty period granted between the time rebel gunmen led by Speight
stormed parliament on May 19 and the date that the last of their dozens of
hostages were released on July 13, Driver said.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Deadly Floods Kill Eight in Brazil
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   RIO DE JANEIRO, Brazil (AP) -- Mudslides triggered by heavy rains plowed
through homes in a town in northeastern Brazil on Monday, killing eight people,
local media reported. All eight were killed when hillsides gave away, sending
avalanches of mud onto the homes in the city of Recife, 1,160 miles northeast of
Rio, Estado news agency reported. There were at least 39 different mudslides
Monday in different parts of the city.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
CanWest Buying 13 Newspapers
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   TORONTO (AP) -- A new multimedia colossus was created Monday as Canada's
second-largest private broadcaster converged with its biggest newspaper group in
a deal that promises to knock down the walls between print, broadcast and online
information. The $1.8 billion blockbuster deal has CanWest Global Communications
Corp., controlled by Winnipeg entrepreneur Izzy Asper, taking over all the major
Canadian newspapers held by Conrad Black's Hollinger Inc. The deal -- by far the
largest of its kind in Canada -- instantly crowns CanWest as the largest
newspaper owner in the country.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Japanese Stocks Rise
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   TOKYO (AP) -- Japanese stocks rose in trading Tuesday following gains on Wall
Street. The Nikkei rose 255.52 points to 15,983.01 in early trading. In New
York, the Nasdaq rose 103.99 to 3,766.99 on Monday after dropping more than 10
percent last week. The Dow gained 10.81 to 10,521.98.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Reds Beat Mets 6-0
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- Scott Williamson pitched six strong innings and Dante
Bichette drove in three runs as the Cincinnati Reds snapped the New York Mets'
six-game winning streak with a 6-0 victory Monday night. Barry Larkin, in his
first game at Shea Stadium since rejecting a trade to the Mets on July 23, went
1-for-4 with an RBI and walk as the Reds won their fourth straight.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
AP NewsBrief by MARIA CODER
</SUBHEAD>
</TEXT>
