<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-01 00:30 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Countries Accused In S.Leone War  </HEADLINE>
By EDITH M. LEDERER
<TEXT>
<P>
   UNITED NATIONS (AP) -- The United States and Britain publicly
accused Liberia and Burkina Faso on Monday of fueling the war in
Sierra Leone by helping its notorious rebels sell diamonds and buy
arms.
</P>
<P>
   ''The United States intends to support measures against both
Burkina Faso and Liberia unless they cease their support for the
war in Sierra Leone,'' U.S. Ambassador Richard Holbrooke warned.
</P>
<P>
   U.S. officials said the measures under consideration include
freezing the foreign assets of both countries and visa restrictions
on senior officials. Washington is also prepared to reexamine U.S.
assistance, the officials said.
</P>
<P>
   Liberian Foreign Minister Monie Captan demanded that the Western
powers present ''concrete evidence'' of the allegations that could
be examined by a panel of eminent persons. Burkina Faso's U.N.
Ambassador Michel Kafando also called for proof, but said his
government is also ''ready and willing'' to receive investigators
from the United Nations or any other source.
</P>
<P>
   In early July, the Security Council imposed a ban on the
purchase of Sierra Leone diamonds that don't have a government
certificate. It is a bid to strangle the ability of the rebel
Revolutionary United Front to finance the 9-year civil war that has
killed and maimed tens of thousands in the West African nation.
</P>
<P>
   The council's resolution referred to illegal diamonds being
shipped through neighboring Liberia but didn't mention Burkina
Faso.
</P>
<P>
   At Monday's town hall-style hearing by the Security Council
committee that monitors sanctions on Sierra Leone, the United
States and Britain went much further in pinpointing responsibility.
</P>
<P>
   ''The governments of Liberia and Burkina Faso, including through
the actions of their presidents, are fueling the war in Sierra
Leone and profiting from the diamond trade,'' Holbrooke said.
</P>
<P>
   ''I appeal to them to end their support for the Revolutionary
United Front and to put a permanent halt to their involvement in
the diamonds for arms trade,'' he told the open meeting which
included representatives from governments, the diamond industry and
voluntary organizations.
</P>
<P>
   U.S. officials said Undersecretary of State Thomas Pickering
delivered a similar message to Liberian President Charles Taylor
during a visit to West Africa in mid-July. Taylor reacted
defensively and took ''sharp issue'' with the evidence, the
officials said.
</P>
<P>
   Liberia's diamond production in recent years is estimated at
between 100,000 and 150,000 carats, worth less than $10 million,
but it has exported 6 million carats of RUF diamonds worth $300
million, Holbrooke said.
</P>
<P>
   About 90 percent of Sierra Leone's diamond mines remain in rebel
hands and the United States estimates the RUF earns $30-50 million,
and perhaps as much as $125 million a year, from illicit diamond
sales, he said.
</P>
<P>
   The diamonds are being purchased by unidentified middlemen, many
Lebanese, who resell them to Belgian, South African, Israeli,
Indian, Russian and other buyers, Holbrooke said.
</P>
<P>
   While most of the diamond trade moves through Liberia, in the
late 1990s about 40 percent of smuggled Sierra Leone diamonds went
through Guinea, he said. Subsequently, significant quantities moved
through the Ivory Coast and Burkina Faso, probably for sale to
South African and European buyers, he said.
</P>
<P>
   The money earned by the rebels is being used to buy more
sophisticated weapons.
</P>
<P>
   ''A year ago, the RUF were ... drug-crazed, machete-wielding
thugs. They are now acquiring machine guns, shoulder-fired
surface-to-air missiles and the means to shoot down aircraft,''
Holbrooke said. ''This is extraordinarily dangerous not only for
the region but for the United Nations,'' which has 13,000
peacekeepers in Sierra Leone.
</P>
<P>
   Stephen Pattison, head of the United Nations Department in the
British Foreign Office, gave details of recent meetings between RUF
rebels and presidents Charles Taylor of Liberia and Blaise Compaore
of Burkina Faso.
</P>
<P>
   Three rebels -- one carrying diamonds to pay for Burkina Faso
''material support'' -- traveled with Taylor to a June 5 meeting
with Compaore in the Burkina Faso capital of Ouagadougou, he said.
On June 10, the same rebel leader flew to the Liberian capital,
Monrovia, to meet Taylor, carrying more diamonds to buy equipment,
he said.
</P>
<P>
   Taylor has arranged transport of arms, munition, food, fuel and
soldiers for the rebels and produced a plan to fortify the diamond
producing areas around Kono which the RUF implemented in June and
July, Pattison said.
</P>
<P>
   In an attempt to tighten his control of diamond production,
Taylor in June authorized establishment of a cover company in
Liberia -- the Liberian Investment Corporation -- with a subsidiary
in Burkina Faso to hide RUF mining operations in Sierra Leone, he
said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-08-01-00 0030 </TRAILER>
