<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-01 00:31 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Study: Convention Coverage Down  </HEADLINE>
By FRAZIER MOORE
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- During half-time on ''ABC Monday Night
Football,'' play-by-play man Al Michaels squeezed in a 90-second
interview with ABC News' Peter Jennings in Philadelphia. Something
about a convention.
</P>
<P>
   Then it was on with the half-time hoopla at the Hall of Fame
Game.
</P>
<P>
   This is the year that coverage of political conventions became a
specialty item.
</P>
<P>
   At convention time in election years past, ABC, CBS and NBC went
wall-to-wall and head-to-head. But in covering Monday's opening of
the Republican National Convention, the broadcast networks devoted
less than two hours total in prime time.
</P>
<P>
   ABC's Jennings was back for an hour special when the football
game was over at 10 p.m. Eastern.
</P>
<P>
   So was CBS, with Dan Rather anchoring. But CBS' coverage had to
share the slot with ''48 Hours.'' The newsmagazine began with an
unrelated story that bumped the live address by prospective first
lady Laura Bush. Then the broadcast joined retired Gen. Colin
Powell's speech eight minutes late.
</P>
<P>
   To its credit, CBS stuck with Powell. ABC cut away five minutes
early as Jennings grandly referred to ABC News' 24-hour coverage
(on Web site ABC.com, that is).
</P>
<P>
   NBC News, which offered no broadcast coverage in prime time, had
the night's biggest (and arguably only) scoop. Interviewed on cable
network MSNBC, former President George Bush told correspondent
Jamie Gangel that if President Clinton doesn't knock off the
insults about his son George W. inside a month, ''I'm gonna tell
the nation what I think about him as a human being and a person.''
</P>
<P>
   Monday, the three broadcast networks met competitively at the
convention during just one 30-minute period: their regular nightly
newscasts.
</P>
<P>
   But signing off for ''NBC Nightly News,'' anchor Tom Brokaw told
viewers they could find him and more coverage by clicking on the
NBC News Web site.
</P>
<P>
   ''There's a dramatic new dimension to covering the convention
this time,'' he said. ''This truly is the first 'e-convention.'''
</P>
<P>
   Earlier, Robert Lichter had described this new dimension in less
rosy terms.
</P>
<P>
   ''The 'big three' networks have handed off much of the campaign
coverage to the 24-hour cable news networks and Internet sites,''
said Lichter, president of the Center for Media and Public Affairs,
a nonpartisan research and educational organization that studies
news and entertainment media.
</P>
<P>
   ''America is on the verge of having a subscription democracy,''
he said.
</P>
<P>
   Diminished airtime for political conventions by the broadcast
networks isn't anything new. But the three major television
networks this year have cut by a third the time devoted to the
presidential campaign as compared with 1996, according to a study
by the center released Monday.
</P>
<P>
   The study examined news coverage by ABC, CBS and NBC from Jan. 1
to July 26, and found that evening news shows devoted 21 hours, 33
minutes to the presidential race this year.
</P>
<P>
   That compares to 32 hours, 18 minutes during the previous
presidential election year, meaning that more than a minute of
political coverage was shaved from each network show per night, the
study said.
</P>
<P>
   Up to now in this election season, CBS has had the steepest
decline, cutting coverage 43 percent from the 1996 election cycle,
the study said. ABC's coverage declined 38 percent and NBC's
coverage was down 16 percent.
</P>
<P>
   ''If you're not wired in,'' Lichter said, ''you're disconnected
from the political process.''
</P>
<P>
   Not quite. During the convention, PBS is providing extensive
over-the-air coverage through the auspices of ''The NewsHour With
Jim Lehrer.''
</P>
<P>
   Even so, it seemed that with three all-news cable networks (up
from two in 1996), plus the supplemental Web sites of the broadcast
networks, this week's proceedings hadn't just been certified as an
e-convention. They were also transformed into a niche product for a
specialized audience.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, the broadcast networks remained free to go on with
their customary mission -- feeding the larger appetite for
entertainment fare such as football, ''Big Brother'' or a ''Law &AMP;
Order'' rerun.
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   On the Net:
</P>
<P>
   Center for Media and Public Affairs: http://www.cmpa.com
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-08-01-00 0031 </TRAILER>
