<HEADLINE> Blasts Kill Two in S. Philippines  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   MANILA, Philippines (AP) -- At least two people were killed and
17 others injured in explosions at a carnival and a Roman Catholic
cathedral in the southern Philippines, officials said Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   One explosion ripped through a town festival in Monkayo, 580
miles southeast of Manila on the island of Mindanao late Monday,
killing two men and injuring 16 others, police said. Investigators
could not conclude who was responsible, said regional police
spokesman Hermelino Bermoy.
</P>
<P>
   Also late Monday, a grenade exploded near the cathedral in the
Muslim-dominated town of Jolo, 250 miles southwest of Monkayo,
injuring one man, the military's Southern Command said.
</P>
<P>
   It was the third grenade blast in less than two weeks in the
town on Jolo island, where Muslim extremists are holding 29
hostages, including 15 foreigners.
</P>
<P>
   Muslim separatist rebels have been blamed for other recent
bombings in the southern Philippines, but some explosions have been
triggered by quarrels among local residents.
</P>
