<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-01 01:04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Peres' Defeat a Familiar Role  </HEADLINE>
By DINA KRAFT
<TEXT>
<P>
   JERUSALEM (AP) -- The color drained from Shimon Peres' face as
the tally of votes was read aloud. Once again, he had lost an
election.
</P>
<P>
   The Nobel peace laureate and former Israeli prime minister --
celebrated more abroad than in his own country -- found himself cast
in the familiar role of loser, defeated in Monday's poll of the
Knesset's 120 legislators by a relative unknown in the election for
the presidency.
</P>
<P>
   The eloquent elder statesmen and master politician, thought a
shoo-in for the ceremonial post, gained only 57 votes. The other 63
went to Moshe Katsav, an underwhelming legislator from the hawkish
Likud Party.
</P>
<P>
   Peres may have the most impressive resume in Israel's
parliament. His career spans the country's 52 year history -- from
the man responsible for developing Israel's nuclear capacity in the
1950s, to an architect of the Israeli-Palestinian peace process.
</P>
<P>
   He has served in each of the top four posts: defense minister,
finance minister, foreign minister, prime minister.
</P>
<P>
   Persuading elected officials to hire him was never a problem.
Getting elected himself was.
</P>
<P>
   He lost four elections for prime minister, and tied for one in
1984. That led to a ''rotation'' agreement with the other
candidate, Yitzhak Shamir; Peres served from 1984-86.
</P>
<P>
   In November 1995 he took office for a second time after the
assassination of Yitzhak Rabin. He served until May 1996, when he
was narrowly defeated by hard-liner Benjamin Netanyahu.
</P>
<P>
   An architect of the breakthrough Oslo Accords, launching the
peace process with the Palestinians, Peres shared the 1994 Nobel
Peace Prize with Rabin and Yasser Arafat. Although he is revered
abroad as a statesman, hawks at home say he is too conciliatory to
Israel's Arab neighbors.
</P>
<P>
   Legislator Eli Goldschmidt of Peres' One Israel faction said it
was hard to watch Peres lose another race.
</P>
<P>
   ''Apparently, a person's greatness does not necessarily
translate into an ability to win elections,'' Goldschmidt said.
</P>
<P>
   Prime Minister Ehud Barak also was caught off-guard by the
defeat -- until Sunday, media counts said 65 legislators were with
Peres, only 45 were with Katsav and 10 were undecided.
</P>
<P>
   ''My heart today is with Shimon Peres who has contributed his
entire life to the security and peace of Israel,'' Barak told the
parliament.
</P>
<P>
   Ultimately it was the powerful ultra-Orthodox Shas party that
turned the tide.
</P>
<P>
   Party officials said all 17 Shas legislators voted for Katsav
after their spiritual leader Rabbi Yitzhak Kadouri had a vision
that Katsav -- an observant Jew -- was favored by the heavens.
</P>
<P>
   Peres' fellow lawmakers blamed ethnic politics. Shas has built a
following decrying discrimination of Sephardic Jews of Middle
Eastern by the country's elite of Ashkenazi Jews of European
descent.
</P>
<P>
   Despite his many years in government, the Iranian-born Katsav
campaigned as the underdog who rose from humble origins.
</P>
<P>
   ''It was not a proper vote, it was an ethnic vote,'' said Labor
lawmaker Colette Avital.
</P>
<P>
   Peres was welcomed back to his home north of Tel Aviv Monday
night by a drum-beating crowd of supporters, chanting ''Peres, the
nation is with you.''
</P>
<P>
   ''We will continue to work for peace and won't give up,'' Peres
called out in response.
</P>
<P>
   In an interview with Israel Television, Peres' daughter said the
religious legislators missed the mark when they failed to choose
the man whose career was marked first by securing the Jewish
state's capacity to defend itself -- and then by securing its
peaceful existence.
</P>
<P>
   ''I hear they say Katsav keeps the (biblical) commandments -- but
my father actually fulfills them,'' said Tsvia Valdan.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-08-01-00 0104 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000801.0018 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-01 01:05 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Book Helps ID Bosnia War Victims  </HEADLINE>
By AIDA CERKEZ-ROBINSON
<TEXT>
<P>
   SARAJEVO, Bosnia-Herzegovina (AP) -- A book containing pictures
of personal belongings found on bodies discovered near Srebrenica
has helped dozens of families identify relatives missing from
nearly five years ago in the worst massacre of the Bosnian war.
</P>
<P>
   Between 7,000 and 10,000 Muslim men were believed to have been
systematically killed when Serb forces overrun the eastern enclave
of Srebenica in 1995. Thousands were buried in mass graves around
the town. Others were left unburied.
</P>
<P>
   Since June 19, the International Committee of the Red Cross has
been showing the book containing photographs of torn clothes,
boots, socks and other personal items found on about 300 recovered
remains to people whose relatives are among the missing.
</P>
<P>
   As a result, dozens of victims have been identified, according
to Amor Masovic, head of the Muslim Commission for Missing Persons
in Sarajevo.
</P>
<P>
   ''Every day, families call saying they recognized in the book
the clothes of their beloved and we then combine the clothes with
the body,'' he said Monday.
</P>
<P>
   So far 4,000 bodies have been found and are being stored in a
morgue in Tuzla in northern Bosnia. Only a few have been identified
because of the advanced state of decomposition and lack of
sufficient dental and other records.
</P>
<P>
   The book offers the best chance of bringing closure to at least
some of the victims' families, officials said.
</P>
<P>
   ''We absolutely hit the nail on the head with this book,''
Masovic said.
</P>
<P>
   Nine specially trained Red Cross teams carefully go through the
book with family members, trying to help them find an item by which
they can recognize a victim.
</P>
<P>
   Of tens of thousands of pictures taken, only those that would
cause the least pain were printed in 500 copies of the book:
various jackets, underwear, a sweat shirt emblazoned with ''Los
Angeles,'' snapshots of laughing children at birthday parties or of
smiling men carrying a case of beer.
</P>
<P>
   The items testify to the victims' lives and last moments.
</P>
<P>
   For five years already, families of the victims have been
demanding to know the fate of their sons, brothers, fathers and
husbands. Without recognizing a body and giving it a decent burial,
some families fill their days and nights with expectations that
maybe someday, somewhere, by some miracle, their dearest will be
found alive.
</P>
<P>
   The success achieved with the book made the Muslim commission
and the Red Cross consider widening the project and printing books
with items found on bodies in other mass graves in Bosnia and maybe
in the region of Serbia and Croatia too, Masovic said.
</P>
<P>
   ''We have millions of photos from exhumations and turning them
into books means getting good results for minimum investment,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   Asked whether any plans were made for a common book with
pictures of items found on Muslim, Serb and Croat victims of the
war could be published, Masovic said his Serb and Croat colleagues
do not have the same problem.
</P>
<P>
   Since the end of the Bosnian 1992-95 war, the Serb Commission
for Missing Persons exhumed about 1,500 Serb bodies and the Croat
Commission about 450.
</P>
<P>
   ''So, they have more time to do the identification,'' Masovic
said. ''We have exhumed 8,704 bodies so far, of which 4,000 only
around Srebrenica.''
</P>
<P>
   More than 80 percent of the bodies found elsewhere by the Muslim
Commission were identified. But from the 4,000 Srebrenica bodies,
only 76 were identified before the book came out.
</P>
<P>
   ''We should have done this book in 1996,'' Masovic said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-08-01-00 0105 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
