<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-01 01:16 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Ex-President Bush Sharing a Salute  </HEADLINE>
By WALTER R. MEARS
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHILADELPHIA (AP) -- Politics has been the family calling for
three generations, yet George W. Bush dismisses talk of a dynasty.
Still, his legacy is on the ticket and in his shadow Cabinet as he
seeks to reclaim the White House his father lost eight years ago.
</P>
<P>
   George W. would not be where he is without the family name.
Taking that advantage without overplaying it is not an easy course.
</P>
<P>
   Former President Bush and his wife, Barbara, drew an opening
ovation when they appeared in the VIP gallery at the Republican
National Convention Monday night. ''We are so proud of you, the
entire Bush family,'' Rep. Henry Bonilla of Texas told them.
</P>
<P>
   George Bush, former President Gerald R. Ford, and Nancy Reagan
take the convention's salute Tuesday night. But the role of the
elder Bush is a limited one. No prime time speech as when Ronald
Reagan played to the cheers of the 1988 convention, urging
Republicans to ''win one more for the Gipper'' by helping Bush
succeed him.
</P>
<P>
   Too much George Bush at this convention could play into the
Democrats' contention that George W. is trying to win a replay
presidency.
</P>
<P>
   There is no denying the father's impact, and Bush doesn't
pretend otherwise. ''After all, it wasn't but two years after he
left the presidency that two of his sons ran for governor,'' Bush
said in an interview with USA Today. George W. won his first Texas
term in 1994; brother Jeb lost that year but now is governor of
Florida.
</P>
<P>
   Their grandfather was a winning politician, too, Sen. Prescott
Bush of Connecticut.
</P>
<P>
   On his way to the presidential nomination, George W. Bush called
the father-son impact ''the John Adams and John Q. factor.'' They
were the only father and son ever elected presidents, six terms
apart in 1796 and 1824.
</P>
<P>
   Bush seeks to succeed the man who beat his father eight years
ago. President Clinton is campaigning for his designated political
heir, Vice President Al Gore, and taunting Bush as he does so.
</P>
<P>
   ''Nearest I can tell, the message of the Bush campaign is 'How
bad could I be? I've been governor of Texas. My daddy was
president. I own a baseball team. They like me down there.' ''
</P>
<P>
   George Bush's place in the campaign of George W. became a
sensitive point with the Republican nominee when critics said that
the former president had pushed his son to choose Dick Cheney for
vice president, implying that the younger Bush was not making his
own decisions. Cheney was President Bush's secretary of defense.
</P>
<P>
   Gov. Bush said that they talked about the choice and that it was
no sign of weakness for a man to get advice from his father. But he
said the decision was based on his own work with Cheney as a
campaign adviser and was his alone.
</P>
<P>
   Colin Powell, the general George Bush made chairman of the joint
chiefs of staff, and Condoleezza Rice, a national security adviser
in the Bush White House, surely would be major figures in a George
W. Bush administration. Bush has hinted that Powell might be his
secretary of state. Ms. Rice, Bush's chief adviser on foreign
policy, could play the same role in the White House.
</P>
<P>
   Both are black, both had prime time speech slots at the
Republican National Convention. Introducing Powell via satellite TV
Monday night, Bush said ''I hope his greatest service to America
might still lie ahead.''
</P>
<P>
   There surely would be other Bush veterans in a new Bush
government, hardly surprising because it fits the pattern of both
parties. The officials of one administration are the logical
recruits for another.
</P>
<P>
   Connections and comparisons of father and son are constant and
inevitable, as when George W. not only pledged no new taxes but
promised cuts.
</P>
<P>
   ''Read my lips, no new taxes,'' George Bush vowed from every
platform in his 1988 campaign, but reneged on the pledge as
president. George W. said after his father's defeat that it was a
self-inflicted wound.
</P>
<P>
   ''Breaking his pledge cost him credibility and weakened his
base,'' George W. said.
</P>
<P>
   He is on record with a comparable pledge. ''This is not only no
new taxes,'' he said in a campaign debate on Jan. 16. ''This is tax
cuts, so help me God.''
</P>
<P>
   The elder Bush made only a handful of campaign appearances for
his son during the primaries, campaigning for a day in Iowa, for an
afternoon in New Hampshire, the latter event marked by an inadroit
phrase.
</P>
<P>
   ''This boy, this son of ours, is not going to let you down,''
the former president said. With critics then, and still, trying to
make inexperience an issue against Bush, ''boy'' was not the image
his campaign wanted left with voters.
</P>
<P>
   Nor is the idea of a Bush dynasty. George W. counters that
suggestion by saying that he isn't trying to win on an inheritance,
but by earning trust and votes.
</P>
<P>
   Bush favors the description of his political heritage Powell
offered in urging his election.
</P>
<P>
   ''He is a man who comes from a family with a generations-long
tradition of public service,'' Powell said.
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   EDITOR'S NOTE -- Walter R. Mears has reported on national
political conventions for The Associated Press since 1964.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-08-01-00 0116 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000801.0023 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-01 01:18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Bush Eager To Tell U.S. His Plans  </HEADLINE>
By LAURIE KELLMAN
<TEXT>
<P>
   COLUMBUS, Ohio (AP) -- George W. Bush is eager to tell the
country about his plans to ''use these good times for great
purposes.''
</P>
<P>
   The GOP nominee-to-be is working his way to the Republican
National Convention by stumping through battleground states won by
Democrats in 1996 and 1992, including Arkansas, Missouri, Kentucky
and Ohio.
</P>
<P>
   ''But not this time, not this year,'' Bush said Monday in a
satellite remarks to the gathering in Philadelphia after his wife's
prime-time convention speech.
</P>
<P>
   ''We've seen thousands of people. The crowds have been big and
the enthusiasm even bigger,'' he said from a classroom at
Westerville South High School. ''And I cannot wait to stand before
you Thursday night and tell America how I want to use these good
times for great purposes.''
</P>
<P>
   Bush arrives in Philadelphia on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   The Texas governor watched his wife with a group of honor
students while waiting to go on camera himself.
</P>
<P>
   Seated in a school chair, he grinned proudly as she took the
stage. ''She looks great,'' he said. Then, as Laura Bush said she
was ''honored to open this convention that will nominate my husband
for president of the United States,'' Bush joked, ''I wrote that
line for her.''
</P>
<P>
   In his convention remarks, Bush recalled his premarital pledge
to Laura -- the one about her never having to deliver a political
speech.
</P>
<P>
   ''I know you're as glad as I am that she didn't hold me to that
promise,'' he told the delegates.
</P>
<P>
   Aides said Bush will deliver more broad-themed, short speeches
described as practice runs for the 3,900-word address that he
delivers Thursday night to accept the Republican nomination for
president.
</P>
<P>
   The Bushes practiced their speeches separately, but in front of
about a dozen friends and staff members Sunday night.
</P>
<P>
   ''I wanted to see her speech on first delivery,'' Bush said.
''Nor did she help me practice mine.''
</P>
<P>
   Earlier Monday, Bush attended rallies at the University of
Dayton, a private Catholic college, and in the Senate atrium of
Ohio's state Capitol in Columbus. In both places, he sounded many
of the themes he is expected to raise in his convention speech.
</P>
<P>
   ''We've got a lot of work to do, and I'm ready to do the work,''
he told the Columbus audience. He said Americans were ''sick and
tired of the politics of tearing people down.''
</P>
<P>
   Democrats held a competing rally a few blocks away.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier in Dayton, Bush proclaimed, ''Ours is not the politics
of personal destruction'' and pledged to wage ''a campaign of
hopefulness.'' He also promised to ''keep the peace'' and
strengthen America's military.
</P>
<P>
   As with most recent Bush rallies, only those with invitations
were allowed up front. Still, a group of about two dozen people
with Gore signs chanted ''Al Gore'' on the edge of the rally.
</P>
<P>
   Bush ignored the group, but Sen. Mike DeWine, R-Ohio, turned to
them and said, ''The First Amendment is alive and well. We welcome
our friends.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
