<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Mrs. Bush Launches Convention  </HEADLINE>
By KALPANA SRINIVASAN
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHILADELPHIA (AP) -- Out from behind her husband's shadow, Laura
Bush is carving her own path in the campaign that could lead her to
the East Wing of the White House.
</P>
<P>
   She charmed delegates Monday night with her rousing kickoff
speech at the GOP convention. An increasingly valuable asset in
Gov. George W. Bush's presidential bid, she planned to return to
his side on the campaign trail Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   She comes back here later this week to show off yet another
facet of her campaign role at a major fund-raiser.
</P>
<P>
   At the convention, the delegates greeted the Texas first lady
exuberantly, amid a shower of metallic streamers and red, white and
blue confetti. She drew a standing ovation when she suggested that
voters want to return respect to the presidency.
</P>
<P>
   America wants a leader who reflects ''its heart and its values
and its leadership in the world,'' Mrs. Bush said. ''They will be
looking for someone to uphold that honor and that trust.''
</P>
<P>
   She said the Texas governor would fulfill those dreams.
</P>
<P>
   ''He shares credit and doesn't cast blame,'' she said. ''He sets
a tone that's positive and constructive, a tone that's very
different from the bitterness and division that too often
characterize Washington, D.C.''
</P>
<P>
   The former librarian and schoolteacher walked on stage to the
Jackson Five classic ''ABC,'' setting the tone for a speech framed
around her experience and interest in education.
</P>
<P>
   She pledged that if her husband is elected, she will focus her
attention on the issues she has championed in Texas, such as early
childhood development and reading and learning.
</P>
<P>
   Twenty students from a Houston charter school sat in desks
behind her. They recited multiplication charts and chanted, ''There
are no shortcuts'' before Mrs. Bush took center stage.
</P>
<P>
   Referring not-so-indirectly to Vice President Al Gore, Mrs. Bush
noted that her husband's opponent sometimes spends a night at a
teacher's home before visiting a school.
</P>
<P>
   ''George spends every night with a teacher,'' said Mrs. Bush,
53, to a round of cheers. The pair wed in 1977 in Midland, Tex.,
where they both grew up.
</P>
<P>
   Standing next to her state's delegation in the center of the
convention hall, Minnesota Secretary of State Mary Kiffmeyer said
she ''loved that line ... There's a quality about Laura Bush, a
genuineness, a sensitivity, and I think the American people are
looking for that kind of First lady,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. Bush credited her husband for working to make education
more accessible to young adults, recounting how the couple used to
read Dr. Seuss stories to their daughters.
</P>
<P>
   ''One of the major reasons George is running for president is to
make sure every child in America has that same opportunity to grow
up reading,'' said Mrs. Bush.
</P>
<P>
   She looked out at more than a few friendly faces. The Bushes'
twin daughters, Jenna and Barbara, sat beside the candidate's
parents -- former President and Barbara Bush. Laura Bush's mother,
Jenna Welch also watched from the audience.
</P>
<P>
   The governor caught his wife's address from an Ohio high school,
where he stood with a group of honor students. Grinning proudly as
she took the stage, he said, ''She looks great.''
</P>
<P>
   Afterward, he told the delegates via satellite: ''You heard from
the best speaker in the family.''
</P>
<P>
   ''Watching her speak tonight, seeing her grace and strength
reminded me just how much I love her,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. Bush said she can attest to the candidate's unswerving
principles, having sat beside him during his ups and downs in
politics and in baseball, referring to his time as a managing
partner with the Texas Rangers.
</P>
<P>
   ''His core principles will not change with the winds of polls or
politics or fame or fortune or misfortune,'' Mrs. Bush said.
</P>
<P>
   She is certain that her husband will one day ''be a fabulous
grandfather. In the meantime he'll make a great president,'' she
quipped.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
