<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-01 01:22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Spotlight Is Fleeting for Doles  </HEADLINE>
By TED ANTHONY
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHILADELPHIA (AP) -- They claim center stage once more Tuesday
night, surrounded by admirers, warmed by effusive praise, carrying
the GOP's message with the same fervor. But this time, for Bob and
Elizabeth Dole, the spotlight is fleeting and a bit less bright.
</P>
<P>
   He returns as an elder statesman -- the 20th-century war hero,
the gentleman legislator from Kansas, the totem to be treated with
deference. Her role is now dual -- the would-be first lady of 1996
and, more recently, the presidential candidate who could have made
Bob Dole America's first first man. And yet both are saddled with
campaign-season failures.
</P>
<P>
   It's an unusual situation that creates an unusual dilemma for
Republicans: What role should these GOP stalwarts play at the 2000
convention of the self-described party of the future?
</P>
<P>
   ''She's without a doubt the top woman in the party. He
represents patriotism and people who have served their country
selflessly,'' says Roger Hartley, a public affairs specialist at
Roanoke College in Virginia. ''They're still very important to the
Republican Party.''
</P>
<P>
   Certainly neither Dole is absent here, either physically or in
spirit.
</P>
<P>
   The senator, in addition to addressing the convention Tuesday
night, is ''working'' as a ''correspondent'' for Comedy Central,
trading on the dry wit he has untethered of late and generally
being a ''senior something'' -- the way he described himself last
month. He doesn't seem at all, well, doleful.
</P>
<P>
   ''We had a good ticket and we did our best and we didn't win. We
accept responsibility for that,'' a relaxed Dole said Monday night
on CNN's ''Larry King Live.'' ''But it looks good this year.''
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. Dole, also scheduled to speak in prime time Tuesday,
promised when she withdrew from the presidential race in October
that she was ''a long way from twilight.'' On Monday, at a fete
sponsored by the Lifetime Network honoring her accomplishments as
Cabinet member, Red Cross chief and successful woman, Florida Rep.
Tillie Fowler predicted an even brighter future.
</P>
<P>
   ''I don't know what mountain Elizabeth Dole will climb next,''
Fowler said. ''But I do know this: She has always been ahead of her
time.''
</P>
<P>
   Finding a place for vanquished candidates can be a thorny issue.
The Democrats waited years to offer group hugs to the defeated
George McGovern (1972) and Walter Mondale (1984). Michael Dukakis
(1988) is still waiting. On the Republican side, it took years
before Richard Nixon overcame the stigma of resignation and was
welcomed home.
</P>
<P>
   President Bush, who lost to Bill Clinton in 1992, is a different
story. First off, he actually served as president; second, with
Ronald Reagan ailing and unavailable, he offers a convenient bridge
between the adored Reagan years and the Republicans' anticipated
administration of George W. Bush.
</P>
<P>
   That leaves Bob and Elizabeth Dole somewhere in the middle --
associated with good eras and accomplishments but hobbled a bit by
recent defeats. Yet some say name recognition alone can carry the
day for them -- especially him.
</P>
<P>
   ''A lot of it depends on how you've been beaten, whether you
were gracious in defeat and the overall tenor of the campaign,''
says Rick Hardy, a University of Missouri political scientist who
worked on Republican Fred Thompson's aborted 1996 presidential run.
Dole, he says, is ''a man that didn't shame the Republican Party,
even in defeat.''
</P>
<P>
   Senate Majority Leader Trent Lott, R-Miss., says Dole's ''deep
reservoir of support'' and longtime presence in the GOP would
''make it kind of strange not to have him around.'' Former national
Republican Chairman Haley Barbour speaks of the ''affection and
nostalgia'' people hold for Dole.
</P>
<P>
   And Kansas Gov. Bill Graves, chairman of his state's delegation,
expects Dole to be welcomed throughout the week; people, Graves
said, remember him as ''the total package as a public servant.''
</P>
<P>
   ''Bob Dole,'' says Graves, ''is still one of the bright stars of
the Republican Party.''
</P>
<P>
   And so the Doles step forward again, not the center of attention
but proving that two intersecting, incredibly circuitous political
careers have a few more twists and turns left.
</P>
<P>
   ''I kind of like people rediscovering Bob Dole,'' says Alfred
Eckes, former executive director of the Republican Caucus of the
House of Representatives and now an Ohio University history
professor.
</P>
<P>
   ''He's not a 24-hour meteor. His public life demonstrated
extraordinary ability and bravery. Who better to recognize? Who
else do they have around? I'm sure they'll trot out Gerry Ford, but
how far can they go with that?''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
