<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-01 01:24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Huggins Turns Down Clippers Job  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   CINCINNATI (AP) -- Bob Huggins turned down an offer to coach the
Los Angeles Clippers on Monday night, preferring to stay at the
University of Cincinnati.
</P>
<P>
   Huggins' decision left the NBA's worst team still in search of a
coach. Huggins turned down a four-year contract believed to be
worth a total of $8 million.
</P>
<P>
   ''We received a call from coach Huggins Monday evening notifying
us of his latest position,'' said Joe Safety, the Clippers' vice
president of communications. ''We wish him well.''
</P>
<P>
   Huggins was tempted by the chance to coach in the NBA, but
decided against taking over one of its least successful teams.
</P>
<P>
   ''To have the opportunity to be a head coach in the NBA and to
coach the greatest basketball players in the world is without a
doubt a goal of mine,'' Huggins said in a statement. ''I'm hoping
someday I will have the opportunity again. But for now, I have made
commitments to players, families and the community that I would
like to see through.''
</P>
<P>
   Huggins met with the Clippers and got their offer on Friday. He
was in Michigan recruiting when he informed the team and the
university of his decision.
</P>
<P>
   ''I still have the burning desire to make a run at the national
championship and there's no better place for me to do it than
here,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   During his 11 seasons at Cincinnati, Huggins has taken the
Bearcats to one Final Four and made them a consistent Top 25 team.
The school gave him a $54,000 raise last spring, keeping his
contract among the most lucrative in Conference USA.
</P>
<P>
   The Clippers were 15-67 last season, the NBA's worst record, but
improved their roster on draft day with a series of moves.
</P>
<P>
   Huggins has had an interest in coaching in the NBA for some
time.
</P>
<P>
   He withdrew as a candidate for the Miami Heat's head coaching
job in June 1995. Miami was interested in hiring Huggins, then
halted negotiations when Pat Riley resigned from the New York
Knicks. Huggins signed a 10-year extension at Cincinnati, and the
Heat hired Riley.
</P>
<P>
   Huggins has been mentioned in connection with several NBA
vacancies the last few months. He denied a report this month that
Clippers owner Donald Sterling had discussed the job with him.
</P>
<P>
   Huggins' best team provided one of his biggest disappointments
last season. A team ranked No. 1 most of the season came apart
after center Kenyon Martin -- the top pick in June's NBA draft --
broke his leg in the Conference USA tournament. The Bearcats then
lost in the second round of the NCAA tournament for the fourth
consecutive year.
</P>
<P>
   Cincinnati enters the upcoming season without five of its top
players from last year's team -- Martin, forwards Pete Mickeal, Ryan
Fletcher and Jermaine Tate and guard DerMarr Johnson.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
