<HEADLINE> Athletics 6, Blue Jays 1  </HEADLINE>
By ANNE M. PETERSON
<TEXT>
<P>
   OAKLAND, Calif. (AP) -- David Wells lost on the road for the
first time this season as Tim Hudson pitched the Oakland Athletics
over the Toronto Blue Jays 6-1 Monday night.
</P>
<P>
   Wells (16-4), who leads the majors in victories, had been 10-0
on the road this year. Overall, he had won 13 in a row away from
SkyDome since Sept. 7, 1999, when he lost at Seattle.
</P>
<P>
   Miguel Tejada and Adam Piatt homered as Oakland won its third
straight game. Jason Giambi put the A's ahead to stay with an RBI
double in the fifth inning.
</P>
<P>
   Hudson (12-3) went eight innings, allowing one run on just three
hits. He walked walked one and struck out five.
</P>
<P>
   Hudson has won 11 of his last 12 decisions.
</P>
<P>
   Wells pitched eight innings, giving up five earned runs and 12
hits. He walked two, and has walked only 24 this season.
</P>
<P>
   The Blue Jays have won 19 of Wells' 22 starts this year. Their
last loss with Wells on the mound was July 15 against Philadelphia.
</P>
<P>
   Jim Mecir, acquired by the A's from Tampa Bay on Friday, made
his first appearance for Oakland and pitched a scoreless ninth.
</P>
<P>
   With the score tied at 1 in the fifth, Wells walked Ryan
Christenson walked with one out. An out later, Giambi's double
sailed to the fence in left-center, scoring Christenson easily.
</P>
<P>
   The A's loaded the bases with one out in the seventh inning
against Wells. But Olmedo Saenz grounded to short and then stumbled
and fell while running to first as the Blue Jays turned a double
play.
</P>
<P>
   Saenz had to be helped off the field with a strained left
hamstring.
</P>
<P>
   With one out in the eighth, Ben Grieve singled and Tejada hit
his 24th home run. Terrence Long followed with a double and scored
on Eric Chavez's double. Chavez later scored on Christenson's
suicide squeeze.
</P>
<P>
   Brad Fullmer hit a solo home run off Hudson in the second. It
was 22nd homer.
</P>
<P>
   The A's tied it at the bottom of the inning on Piatt's solo
homer off Wells. All four of his home runs this season have come
against left-handed pitchers.
Notes: A's starters have pitched at least seven innings in the
last five games. ... The Athletics traded Triple-A Sacramento
catcher Danny Ardoin to Triple-A Salt Lake for first baseman Mario
Valdez. ... Toronto second baseman Homer Bush was in the original
lineup, but pulled before the game and replaced by Craig Grebeck.
Bush was hit by a pitch on Sunday, and although X-rays were
negative, he was not available to play. ... Right-hander Steve
Traschel, acquired by the Blue Jays in a trade from Tampa Bay, will
join the team in Toronto on Thursday and enter the rotation.
</P>
</TEXT>
