<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Verizon Unions Negotiate Jobs  </HEADLINE>
By ANJETTA McQUEEN
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- More than 85,000 employees of Verizon
Communications are negotiating for a bigger share of the telephone
giant's growing wireless operation.
</P>
<P>
   The Communications Workers of America and International
Brotherhood of Electrical Workers unions, armed with authority to
call a strike, headed for a second day of talks Tuesday with
Verizon, which was created by the June merger of Bell Atlantic and
GTE. The union's contract with Verizon expires this weekend.
</P>
<P>
   On Monday, neither side would characterize the talks, nor even
pinpoint where they are being held in Washington. The unions and
the company agreed the going could be tough.
</P>
<P>
   ''I expect they will grow more intense,'' CWA spokeswoman
Candace Johnson said Monday.
</P>
<P>
   In 1998, CWA struck Bell Atlantic and IBEW honored the picket
lines, affecting service in 13 Eastern states and the District of
Columbia. A 1989 strike by both unions against Nynex, which later
merged with Bell Atlantic, lasted four months.
</P>
<P>
   The authority to strike this time came during regional talks in
New York and Philadelphia last week. An impasse at 12:01 a.m.
Sunday could send operators and technicians to the picket lines and
leave 25 million homes and businesses from Maine to Virginia
without help setting up phone services, repairing or installing
lines, and figuring out their telephone bills.
</P>
<P>
   Union leaders say they are seeking better benefits, wages and
working conditions and concessions to create more union-represented
jobs in the wireless division.
</P>
<P>
   A fraction of workers in the Verizon wireless division are
unionized, while most of the company's local phone operation
workers are union members. Armed with data on wages and employee
productivity, the sides are at odds over what kind of access the
unions should have to wireless jobs, among the fastest-growing
sectors in the industry.
</P>
<P>
   ''Our members have made Verizon a success,'' Johnson said. Union
officials say Verizon's wireless operation uses new job categories,
profit-sharing options and temporary workers to shut out the
unions.
</P>
<P>
   ''The union right now is free to conduct an organizing campaign,
if it so wishes,'' because the wireless division is a separate
company responsible for its own labor relations, said Verizon
spokesman Steven Marcus.
</P>
<P>
   The company's traditional ''wire-line'' operations just happen
to have a strong union tradition, he said. In wireless services,
''for the most part there is no tradition of union
representation,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   He noted that Verizon Wireless already has a small bargaining
unit.
</P>
<P>
   Johnson said those roughly 50 jobs -- out of 32,000 in the
company -- were grandfathered in from Bell Atlantic's merger with
Nynex mobile communications company. Wire-line workers would lose
their union benefits if they were to seek wireless jobs.
</P>
<P>
   The Communications Workers of America, bargaining separately
from the electrical workers, adds excessive stress and forced
overtime as major issues. Workers at call centers, who market
products to and solve problems for phone customers, are not given
proper training, and employees are forced to work overtime, cancel
vacations and stay on shifts despite family emergencies, the union
says.
</P>
<P>
   Marcus said the company has increased union wire-line jobs in
the last year.
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   On the Net: The Communications Workers of America:
http://www.cwa-union.org/
</P>
<P>
   International Brotherhood of Electrical Workers:
http://www.ibew.org
</P>
<P>
   Verizon Communications: http://www.verizon.com/home.html
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-08-01-00 0131 </TRAILER>
