<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Cheney Joins Hastert in Quest  </HEADLINE>
By JEANNINE AVERSA
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHILADELPHIA (AP) -- Dick Cheney is teaming up with House Speaker
Dennis Hastert to not only help Republicans capture the White House
but also to keep them in control of Congress.
</P>
<P>
   Cheney -- George W. Bush's vice presidential ticket mate and a
five-term member of the House -- is kicking off Day Two of the
Republican National Convention Tuesday by taking part in a luncheon
for the Illinois lawmaker.
</P>
<P>
   Cheney's appearance ''serves to energize our troops,'' said John
McGovern, a spokesman for Hastert, whose entered Congress while
Cheney was there representing Wyoming.
</P>
<P>
   ''Dick Cheney is a veteran of the House and appreciates the
importance of keeping a majority,'' McGovern said. Cheney's support
''reinforces the partnership we are building between the
presidential campaign and the congressional campaign.''
</P>
<P>
   Hastert, meanwhile, said he wasn't ruffled by the relative
absence of congressional candidates as speakers in the convention
lineup. ''We're doing this district by district-- the old-fashioned
way,'' Hastert said. ''We have the best candidates. They're going
to have the money to get their message out.''
</P>
<P>
   Later in the day, Cheney will spend time on the convention floor
rehearsing his speech, which will be delivered Wednesday night.
</P>
<P>
   Aides say he has completed the text but continues to tinker with
certain passages. They wouldn't reveal the themes Cheney will
discuss.
</P>
<P>
   Speech writing experts said Cheney may face some challenges as
he steps back into public life after being in the private sector
for the last five years as a globe-trotting executive at
Halliburton Co., a giant oil-service firm.
</P>
<P>
   Giving a corporate speech and a political speech are ''hugely
different,'' said Robert Orben, a speech writer for President Ford.
</P>
<P>
   ''The essence of a business speaker is to be a serious person,''
Orben said. ''One of the things you learn in the world of
international business, is that you better go easy on jokes, humor
doesn't always translate. But in politics humor is a real asset''
</P>
<P>
   On Monday, Cheney -- calm, collected, even appearing a bit
distant at times -- quietly worked the opening day of the convention
as Democrats launched a new line of attack on his record.
</P>
<P>
   Specifically, they went after his student and then fatherhood
draft deferments during the Vietnam War.
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Tom Harkin, D-Iowa, a Vietnam veteran and
sometimes-mentioned possible running mate for Al Gore, said Cheney
''had other priorities in the '60s. So did a lot of other young men
who went over there and didn't come back.''
</P>
<P>
   Bush campaign spokesman Ari Fleischer said Democrats ''have
fallen into a full panic about this Republican ticket,'' and
questioned why Harkin hasn't criticized President Clinton, who also
avoided the draft.
</P>
<P>
   ''It's interesting that Harkin would discuss his feelings about
Cheney and never say a word about Clinton,'' Fleischer said.
</P>
<P>
   At the convention, Cheney, often accompanied by his wife, Lynne,
was welcomed with rousing applause and chants.
</P>
<P>
   ''We're so proud of you,'' one supporter yelled to Cheney Monday
evening as he listened to speeches by Bush's wife, Laura, and
retired Gen. Colin Powell. Cheney, in an uncharacteristic move,
responded by giving a thumbs up and flashing a wide smile.
</P>
<P>
   ''He will be a superb vice president,'' Powell said of his
former colleague during the speech. Powell was chairman of the
Joint Chiefs of Staff while Cheney was secretary of Defense during
the administration of Bush's father.
</P>
<P>
   The hoopla was a far cry from Cheney's days as a private
citizen.
</P>
<P>
   In his trademark low-key style, Cheney described his transition
into the whirlwind Republican campaign as little more than a
''change of pace.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
