<HEADLINE> Indonesia's President Meets Rivals  </HEADLINE>
By DANIEL COONEY
<TEXT>
<P>
   YOGYAKARTA, Indonesia (AP) -- Indonesia's embattled president met
his main political rivals in this ancient city Tuesday, hoping to
ease tensions imperiling his grip on power along with the nation's
fragile economy and fledgling democracy.
</P>
<P>
   The meeting is hosted by the city's revered sultan behind the
whitewashed walls of his sprawling palace. It comes six days before
President Abdurrahman Wahid faces pressure at an annual meeting of
the People's Consultative Assembly, Indonesia's highest legislative
body.
</P>
<P>
   Wahid's, whose patchy record and unpredictable style has
infuriated lawmakers, met with assembly chairman Amien Rais,
parliamentary Speaker Akbar Tandjung and Vice President Megawati
Sukarnoputri.
</P>
<P>
   Infighting among the four, who head different political parties,
has led to fears of a deepening rift within Wahid's coalition
government, formed 10 months ago after decades of authoritarian
rule.
</P>
<P>
   Sultan Hamengku Buwono X invited the group for reconciliation
talks after a similar meeting was canceled last month when Megawati
failed to attend. Her party was angered by Wahid's decision to fire
one of its top officials from the Cabinet and his refusal to tell
the parliament why.
</P>
<P>
   Wahid and Megawati made no comment when they arrived at the
palace.
</P>
<P>
   ''The controversy in the political situation is quite high,''
said Tandjung, who heads the Golkar Party. ''We want the
controversy to become low.''
</P>
<P>
   Rais also hoped progress could be made.
</P>
<P>
   Wahid has been increasingly criticized for his inability to end
a long-running separatist war in the country's west and an ongoing
bloody religious conflict in the east, and failure to fix the
ailing economy.
</P>
<P>
   Disgruntled senior lawmakers have promised not to launch
impeachment proceedings during the assembly, but said Wahid should
be removed if his performance does not improve soon.
</P>
<P>
   Indonesia's currency, the rupiah, hit a 21-month low earlier
this month, on fears of greater political instability and a
possible outbreak of violence during the assembly's session.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
