<HEADLINE> Change Seen in GOP Rhetoric  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHILADELPHIA (AP) -- Ray Dearin has noticed a change in how
Republicans talk.
</P>
<P>
   ''The vocabulary's different. We're hearing a lot more terms of
empathic understanding, of people and their feelings,'' said
Dearin, an Iowa delegate who happens to be a communications
professor at Iowa State University. ''We're hearing less hard-edged
rhetoric.''
</P>
<P>
   Dearin, 58, should know. He's been involved in the last six GOP
conventions and was a delegate in 1980, 1984 and 1996. He has also
studied the acceptance speech of every Republican presidential
nominee since Wendell Wilkie in 1940.
</P>
<P>
   His academic specialty is political rhetoric. His hobby is
politics.
</P>
<P>
   And Dearin said his professional standing with colleagues has
never been threatened by his longtime Republican roots. In 1972 he
was Iowa chairman of Educators for Nixon.
</P>
<P>
   ''I don't think they think of me as a Republican scholar, but as
a scholar who happens to be a Republican,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   Fellow Republicans are in awe that a guy named George Wallace is
now on their team. At this week's GOP convention, Wallace Jr. gets
stopped repeatedly to sign an autograph, shake a hand, or spin a
tale about events he barely recalls.
</P>
<P>
   Without question, Wallace is the celebrity Alabama delegate, and
it's not for being such an effective public service commissioner.
</P>
<P>
   Wallace's father was the longtime Democratic governor remembered
for demanding segregation in the 1960s, although he later preached
inclusion in the 1980s.
</P>
<P>
   The younger Wallace wants to make one thing clear: His family
didn't change its political views. The political parties changed
theirs.
</P>
<P>
   ''I feel very comfortable here,'' Wallace said of the party.
''This is where I belong, but I do realize the strength of the name
has got me quite a bit more attention.''
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   It's been a difficult year for rancher Marie Ingalls. Her son
was shot and killed last summer at age 42 by his stepson, and
Ingalls recently underwent treatment at the Mayo Clinic in
Rochester, Minn., for a brain tumor.
</P>
<P>
   Yet the former state legislator from Mud Butte, S.D., is
determined to live life as fully as she can. She recently took a
European vacation with her husband and this week she is fulfilling
a lifelong dream of attending a national convention as a delegate.
</P>
<P>
   ''It's something I always wanted to do,'' Ingalls said. ''It's
exciting for us to be here. I got kind of choked up on the floor
this morning.''
</P>
<P>
   ''I think she is just a testament to South Dakota toughness and
resiliency,'' said state Rep. Bill Peterson of Sioux Falls.
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   Mormon members of Utah's contingent at the GOP convention are
used to spending Monday nights in faith-promoting ''Family Home
Evenings.''
</P>
<P>
   This week, instead, they talked about national politics and
listened to Laura Bush and Gen. Colin Powell extoll the virtues of
education and diversity.
</P>
<P>
   Congressional candidate Derek Smith and his wife, Genine, left
their three children with grandparents in Utah. ''We're getting a
little bit of time together,'' Smith said.
</P>
<P>
   Several delegates and alternates brought their children along to
share the experience. Tom and Nathan Draschil, father and son from
Provo, are both delegates.
</P>
<P>
   Family Home Evening is encouraged by Mormon leaders as a way to
ensure that parents and children spend time together at least one
night a week. It can focus on religious study and reflection or
secular fun.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
