<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-01 02:13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> McCain Gets Chance To Mend Fences  </HEADLINE>
By MATT KELLEY
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHILADELPHIA (AP) -- This time around, John McCain says, speaking
to the Republican convention won't be particularly prestigious.
</P>
<P>
   ''That's something that's usually accorded to losers,'' McCain
said.
</P>
<P>
   The Arizona senator spent several hours Monday preparing for
Tuesday night's address, which he said will focus on his support
for primary rival George W. Bush and the greatness and promise he
sees in America's future.
</P>
<P>
   For McCain personally, the speech offers a chance to mend fences
with the Republican officials he alienated during a sometimes
bitter campaign against the Texas governor. He also gets a chance
to appear graceful in defeat.
</P>
<P>
   ''The American people,'' McCain said repeatedly this week,
''don't like sore losers.'' But he also got laughs by repeating an
old quote from the late football coach Vince Lombardi: ''Show me a
good loser and I'll show you a loser.''
</P>
<P>
   McCain says this speech is not as nerve-racking as the one he
gave in 1996 nominating Bob Dole for president because this time
only his own reputation is on the line.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile on Monday McCain worked to bring the young and
independent voters who supported his presidential bid into the
Republican fold, making his case on MTV and planning congressional
campaign trips to both coasts.
</P>
<P>
   ''If you want those old geezers to be interested in your
issues,'' get involved, vote in congressional races, he said at an
MTV-sponsored event at the Hard Rock Cafe.
</P>
<P>
   If enough voters ages 18-26 cast ballots this fall, they could
swing the election, McCain said on a stage in front of a
stained-glass portrait of Elvis.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
