<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-01 02:17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Punk Rocker, Kasich Cross Paths  </HEADLINE>
By DAVID BAUDER
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHILADELPHIA (AP) -- Just a couple of guys hanging out at the
bar: Ohio Rep. John Kasich and punk rock rebel Johnny Rotten.
</P>
<P>
   The two crossed paths at a reception Monday at Finnegan's Wake
Pub, Rotten wearing a luminescent yellow shirt and spiked red hair,
Kasich in a dark business suit.
</P>
<P>
   The Ohio Republican, perhaps confusing the Sex Pistols with the
Rolling Stones, told Rotten he should support George W. Bush
because he's a ''street fighting man.''
</P>
<P>
   Rotten was in Philadelphia working on his VH1 variety show. He
was constantly interrupted from enjoying his Murphy's Stout beer by
college-aged Republicans who wanted to pose for a picture with him.
</P>
<P>
   When one young man couldn't figure out how to use the camera,
Rotten urged him to ''go get a slave to do it for you.''
</P>
<P>
   After a brief chat about delivering music through the Internet,
Kasich got the Rotten thumbs-up.
</P>
<P>
   ''He's a nice chap,'' Rotten said. ''I like him. If he runs for
the president's job, I'd vote for him.''
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   Philadelphia's most famous mythical boxer was a no-show, but
light-heavyweight champion Roy Jones Jr. tried to put some fight in
the Republican Senate candidates.
</P>
<P>
   Jones flew from Pensacola, Fla., Monday night to be the featured
guest at a fund-raiser for GOP Senate candidates.
</P>
<P>
   In a soft voice, the boxer promoted an upcoming fight and urged
high-rollers and senators -- including the ''Louisville slugger''
Sen. Mitch McConnell of Kentucky -- not to forget children.
</P>
<P>
   ''Stand up for people who can't help themselves -- the kids in
our society,'' Jones said.
</P>
<P>
   Former heavyweight boxer Michael Spinks was also in attendance,
as a huge portrait of his brother Leon towered above him. Two
heavyweight champs with roots in the Philadelphia region, Joe
Frazier and Larry Holmes, weren't around.
</P>
<P>
   And although his theme music played, neither was ''Rocky.''
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   A brief shudder of fear spread through the Hard Rock Cafe when
Arizona Sen. John McCain started speaking at a reception designed
to promote MTV's get-out-the-vote campaign.
</P>
<P>
   ''I think I'll spend 40 minutes talking about the North Korean
nuclear buildup,'' McCain said.
</P>
<P>
   Just a joke, folks. McCain instead told dozens of college
students that politicians often ignore their interests because too
many young people don't register to vote.
</P>
<P>
   One 19-year-old, Elizabeth Hess, said she was inspired to
register -- not necessarily by McCain, but because her mother
dragged her to the Hard Rock Cafe with her boyfriend.
</P>
<P>
   While McCain spoke, a newly minted member of the media filmed
him from behind. It was his wife Cindy, who was given a camera by
ABC's ''Good Morning America'' and asked to keep a video diary of
her week.
</P>
<P>
   ''Let's make sure you get on national television,'' McCain told
his audience. ''When I say three, shout 'Good Morning America.'''
</P>
<P>
   No dissenters from the ''Today'' show were heard.
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   Elizabeth Dole is known for her stroll while making a speech at
the 1996 Republican convention. She has another fond memory of the
campaign four years ago: a ''Tonight'' show appearance with Jay
Leno.
</P>
<P>
   Dole wore a black leather jacket and rode on a motorcycle with
Leno, making a few fancy moves with a stunt double's help.
</P>
<P>
   She smiled watching a tape of that moment Monday afternoon at a
testimonial luncheon sponsored by Lifetime Television.
</P>
<P>
   ''Many people thought that was the highlight of the campaign,''
said her husband, losing presidential candidate Bob Dole. ''I can't
remember any highlights of the campaign.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
