<DOCNO> APW20000801.0056 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-01 02:29 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> W. Va. Rejoins South in GOP Region  </HEADLINE>
By RALPH SIEGEL
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHILADELPHIA (AP) -- West Virginia broke away from the South 137
years ago. Now, Republicans have voted it back.
</P>
<P>
   The vote Monday was just technical, and few delegates even paid
attention when the Republican National Convention passed a
resolution allowing West Virginia to join the GOP's Southern
region.
</P>
<P>
   ''West Virginia is going to be back with the South,'' GOP state
chairman David Tyson said. ''This vote is a moment of history, I do
believe it.''
</P>
<P>
   But some of his fellow West Virginians, when asked, didn't seem
to know what he was talking about.
</P>
<P>
   ''I do seem to remember David mentioning something about it to
me,'' was the response from Gov. Cecil Underwood, chairman of the
delegation.
</P>
<P>
   Ever since the Civil War, Republican Party organizations have
grouped West Virginia for purposes of some regional meetings with
Ohio, Minnesota, the Dakotas and other Midwestern states.
</P>
<P>
   ''We have nothing in common with those people on issues, so we
feel we are better aligned with the South,'' Tyson said.
</P>
<P>
   Tyson said West Virginia has always had economic and social ties
with Virginia, Kentucky and the other Southern states. And they
have been together in all of the more modern economic councils and
collegiate sports conferences.
</P>
<P>
   West Virginia separated from Virginia to become the 35th state
in a move engineered by President Lincoln in 1863 at the height of
the Civil War. No sooner had that been done than the Army of
Northern Virginia marched through the new state en route to
disaster at Gettysburg, Pa., where the men of the 7th West Virginia
regiment fixed bayonets against them.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-08-01-00 0229 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000801.0057 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-01 02:31 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Labor Cozies Up to Republicans  </HEADLINE>
By JONATHAN D. SALANT
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHILADELPHIA (AP) -- Among the corporations, trade groups and
other special interests feting Republicans this week are
organizations not normally aligned with the GOP: organized labor.
</P>
<P>
   Some of the nation's biggest labor unions are holding receptions
in honor of friendly congressional Republicans. And the Republican
National Committee saluted Teamsters President James Hoffa on
Monday night with the kind of reception usually reserved for big
donors.
</P>
<P>
   ''It's a really positive sign, both for the Republican Party and
the labor movement,'' said Rep. Jack Quinn, R-N.Y., one of three
GOP lawmakers to be honored by 16 unions on Wednesday. ''It shows
we can reach out to other people and other factions, and it's very
positive for the labor movement because they know some Republicans
are willing to help them.''
</P>
<P>
   When Republicans captured the House in 1994, the GOP leadership
pushed legislation to restrict how unions spend their dues money,
supported a bill allowing employers to give comp time rather than
overtime and attacked ''union bosses.''
</P>
<P>
   But labor leaders are seeing the wisdom of reaching out to
supporters in both parties instead of pitching their tent firmly in
the Democratic camp.
</P>
<P>
   ''Every time we've accomplished everything, it has been a
bipartisan vote in the end,'' said Mary Elizabeth Teasley, director
of government relations for the National Education Association, or
NEA, the nation's largest labor union. ''We're going to build a
bipartisan majority, not a specific-party majority.''
</P>
<P>
   The RNC bash for Hoffa was the highest-profile evidence of
improving relations between the GOP and the Teamsters. Hoffa has
delighted Republicans by withholding a presidential endorsement by
his union until after Labor Day.
</P>
<P>
   While many in the room sought a formal endorsement of George W.
Bush, most were realistic and hoped to achieve a lesser goal of
blocking the union from endorsing Gore.
</P>
<P>
   ''I don't think there's enough time to grow the relationship to
get a full endorsement, but I think neutrality is a real
possibility,'' Pennsylvania Labor Secretary Johnny J. Butler said.
</P>
<P>
   Unions still give most of their money to Democrats. And while
there are 42 Republican members of the NEA who are delegates to the
convention here -- up from 15 in 1992 -- that number pales in
comparison with the 350 NEA members who will be delegates at the
Democratic National Convention in Los Angeles later this month.
</P>
<P>
   Still, organized labor is making an effort to cross party lines
at a time when the Republicans continue to control both houses of
Congress.
</P>
<P>
   ''Our members didn't want us to be lap dogs for any political
party,'' said Andrew Stern, president of the 1.4-million member
Service Employees International Union, the health care workers'
union that is the largest in the AFL-CIO. ''They wanted us to be
watchdogs for their issues.''
</P>
<P>
   It's an effort cheered by Republican lawmakers who have opposed
their leadership's anti-union tilt.
</P>
<P>
   ''Hard-working people should be a base for us,'' said Rep. Peter
King, R-N.Y. ''And yet we've been driving them away.''
</P>
<P>
   Republican union members welcome the move across party lines.
</P>
<P>
   ''The Democratic Party has taken unions for granted,'' said
Geraldine Sam of Texas, a kindergarten teacher and NEA member who
is here as a Bush delegate. ''If unions are willing to come to the
party, we're willing to work with the unions.''
</P>
<P>
   To build bridges to the GOP, Stern called upon former Republican
National Chairman Richard Bond.
</P>
<P>
   ''There is nothing Republican or Democratic about a health care
worker being stuck by a dirty needle,'' Bond said.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Marge Roukema of New Jersey, one of the GOP lawmakers
honored by SEIU on Monday night, has introduced legislation
requiring hospitals to use safer needles that protect health care
workers from accidental pricks.
</P>
<P>
   Others honored Monday were Sen. Charles Grassley of Iowa, for
his support of nursing home legislation; and Rep. Mark Foley of
Florida, for championing a bill that would protect health care
worker whistleblowers from retaliation.
</P>
<P>
   On Wednesday, the SEIU and 15 other unions, many of them
representing transportation workers, plan to honor Quinn, along
with Reps. Frank LoBiondo of New Jersey and Ray LaHood of Illinois.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-08-01-00 0231 </TRAILER>
