<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000801.0058 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-01 02:34 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> BC-NY--Upstate Air,0472  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	   ROCHESTER, N.Y.(AP) - The state Department of Environmental
Conservation is urging the federal Environmental Protection Agency
not to mark western New York as out of compliance for air quality.
</P>
<P>
   Even small excesses of ozone may mean the EPA can require
stiffer emissions standards for automobiles and industry - a move
some Rochester-area critics say would harm an already shaky upstate
economy.
</P>
<P>
   ''Simply put, such a designation will only make it that much
more difficult for our area to prosper,'' said Marvin E. Decker,
chairman of the Rochester-based Genesee Transportation Council.
</P>
<P>
   During measurements the DEC took from 1997 to 1999, four western
New York counties - Wayne, Niagara, Erie and Chautauqua - showed
levels of ozone in the air slightly higher than federal standards
allow.
</P>
<P>
   Some experts say exceeding ozone standards even a little is
harmful to public health. But according to others, the excess in
western New York is not enough to cause harm.
</P>
<P>
   At ground level, ozone is a pollutant and one of the chief
components of smog. It can trigger asthma and other respiratory
ailments and levels of ozone above .08 parts per million in an
eight-hour period, exceed the federal standard.
</P>
<P>
   Locally, some levels are fractionally higher. In Wayne County,
ozone levels - measured at an air monitoring station in Williamson
- are .086 parts per million - 6 thousandths above the standard.
</P>
<P>
   In western New York, Erie County exceeds the ozone standard by
the smallest amount, at .085 parts per million. Chautauqua exceeds
it the most, at .089 parts per million.
</P>
<P>
   The Wayne County measurement, Decker told the Rochester Democrat
and Chronicle, could cause the entire Metropolitan Statistical Area
to be in violation of standards. That area includes Wayne, Monroe,
Ontario, Livingston, Genesee and Orleans counties.
</P>
<P>
   In upstate New York, slightly higher levels of ozone are too
small to harm health, said DEC spokeswoman Jennifer K. Post.
</P>
<P>
   One expert disagreed.
</P>
<P>
   ''Once you get above those (permitted) levels of ozone, you're
putting people at risk,'' said Peter Iwanowicz, director of
environmental health for the American Lung Association in Albany.
''We take these (higher levels) very seriously. A public health
response always dictates the most protective measures.''
</P>
<P>
   But according to Post, the boost in upstate levels of ozone are
in part the result of pollution transported from power plants in
the midwest and Canada - a factor western New York businesses and
motorists can do nothing about, said Post.
</P>
<P>
   The Nanticoke facility in Ontario, Canada, 63 miles west of
Buffalo, is one of the largest sources of ozone emissions in North
America.
</P>
<P>
   ''But you can't ignore the fact that some ozone is homegrown,''
the result of emissions from car tailpipes and factory
smokestacks,'' said Iwanowicz. ''The finger-pointing game only gets
you so far.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-08-01-00 0234 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
