<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-01 02:44 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> NBA Trades, Signings To Resume  </HEADLINE>
By CHRIS SHERIDAN
<TEXT>
<P>
   Of the top four NBA free agents, three are headed to Florida.
The latest is Eddie Jones, who is on the verge of going to Miami in
a nine-player blockbuster trade.
</P>
<P>
   July began with Tim Duncan turning down Orlando, while Grant
Hill and Tracy McGrady decided to join the Magic. Now that it's
August, trades and free-agent signings can resume.
</P>
<P>
   While trades involving Allen Iverson, Patrick Ewing and Shawn
Kemp were still in the rumor stage, the word is already out on the
deal between the Hornets and Heat.
</P>
<P>
   Charlotte was set to send Jones, Anthony Mason, Ricky Davis and
Dale Ellis to Miami for P.J. Brown, Jamal Mashburn, Otis Thorpe,
Tim James and Rodney Buford.
</P>
<P>
   Jones was the latest player to decide against signing with the
Bulls, whose grand plan to stockpile salary cap room for this
summer has turned into a grand failure. Chicago, which thought it
could at least get McGrady and Jones, might end up with no more
than Ron Mercer and Brad Miller.
</P>
<P>
   Jones was considering the Bulls until Monday morning, but
decided it would be better to wait and see.
</P>
<P>
   ''About 9:30 this morning Eddie told me, 'Mama, I may have to go
to Chicago because Charlotte and Miami can't come up with a
deal,''' Jones' mother, Frances Thigpen, told the Miami Herald. ''I
said, 'We have to start sending up some timber -- we have to pray.'
He said, 'Yeah, Mama, pray for me.'''
</P>
<P>
   Orlando is expected to wait until Thursday to announce the
signings of Hill and McGrady, which will give the Magic 48 hours to
find a rebounder, perhaps Maurice Taylor, to replace Ben Wallace.
</P>
<P>
   Wallace and Orlando reserve guard Chucky Atkins are both headed
to Detroit, which is using Hill's salary cap space on the two Magic
defectors.
</P>
<P>
   The Toronto Raptors were hoping to land Indiana's Austin
Croshere, but that can only happen if the Pacers allow themselves
to be outbid. The Raptors also liked Houston's Cuttino Mobley, but
he has decided to stay with the Rockets.
</P>
<P>
   The Spurs are trying to convince the Clippers' Derek Anderson to
join them, while the Boston Celtics are exploring numerous
sign-and-trade options involving their free-agent power forward,
Danny Fortson, who is coveted by the Golden State Warriors and New
York Knicks.
</P>
<P>
   Portland forward Brian Grant opted out of the final four years
and $41 million of his contract to become a free agent, and he
could sign an even more lucrative deal as part of a sign-and-trade
agreement.
</P>
<P>
   The Blazers are reportedly interested in a sign-and-trade
sending Grant and another player to Cleveland for Kemp.
</P>
<P>
   ''Shawn would look forward to going to Portland and winning a
championship, which has always been his goal,'' said Kemp's agent,
Tony Dutt.
</P>
<P>
   Other big-name rumors being reported in various media outlets
included Iverson to the Pistons in a three-way deal (with Jerry
Stackhouse, Jerome Williams and Glen Rice to the 76ers; Matt Geiger
to the Pistons and Christian Laettner to the Lakers) and Ewing to
Portland for Grant and Jermaine O'Neal.
</P>
<P>
   There also was speculation that Charlotte, after acquiring Brown
from Miami, would reroute him to the Lakers for Rice.
</P>
<P>
   As for Chicago, no one is quite certain what will happen.
</P>
<P>
   Duncan and Hill showed no interest in going there despite the
Bulls' ability to pay them maximum salaries. McGrady went to
Chicago for a recruiting trip, only to spurn the Bulls in favor of
a warm climate.
</P>
<P>
   Tim Thomas listened to Chicago, too, but turned the Bulls'
interest into lucrative leverage that will keep him in Milwaukee
with the Bucks.
</P>
<P>
   Having been turned down by most of the marquee names, Chicago
may choose to pursue several B-list free agents -- from Mercer to
Derek Anderson to Jahidi White to Miller -- or decide to pack it in
for another year and wait for the salary cap to jump, perhaps by as
much as $8 million, heading into the 2001-02 season.
</P>
<P>
   Mercer drew interest from the Nets, but New Jersey has
insufficient salary-cap room to sign him after being denied an
injury exception of $3.8 million by the league office on Monday.
The Nets asked for the exception because Jayson Williams can no
longer play, but the league turned it down -- along with a request
for an injury exception for Kerry Kittles -- because the Nets waited
more than six months from the day of Williams' injury to apply.
</P>
<P>
   Several players, most notably Duncan, will stick with their own
teams.
</P>
<P>
   The Eastern Conference champion Indiana Pacers, with the
possible exception of Croshere, should remain intact despite having
four free-agent starters -- Jalen Rose, Reggie Miller, Rik Smits and
Mark Jackson. All are expected to re-sign, with Rose reportedly
getting the maximum allowable salary -- about $9.2 to $9.6 million
for next season -- under terms of the collective bargaining
agreement.
</P>
<P>
   Antonio Daniels, a close friend of Duncan's, will stay with the
Spurs.
</P>
<P>
   Rashard Lewis, who entered the NBA straight out of high school
three years ago, will remain in Seattle.
</P>
<P>
   Howard Eisley should remain in Utah as the heir apparent to John
Stockton at point guard, Joe Smith will stay in Minnesota, and Tim
Hardaway should do the same in Miami. Toni Kukoc could re-sign with
Philadelphia, although the sides were said to be far apart on
money.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
