<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-01 02:47 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Satellites Beam US Into Convention  </HEADLINE>
By LAURA MECKLER
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHILADELPHIA (AP) -- George W. Bush arrived at his convention
early, beamed to cheering delegates via satellite, though he may
have been upstaged by another satellite import -- a gospel-preaching
local minister who rocked the crowd.
</P>
<P>
   With images filling giant screens, delegates to the Republican
National Convention loved the show.
</P>
<P>
   Embracing new technology, convention organizers are using more
remote satellite feeds than ever before to bring coast-to-coast
symbols of America right into their arena.
</P>
<P>
   Later this week, satellite hookups will fill the hall with a war
hero aboard a battleship, a New Jersey senior talking about Social
Security and a tour of the Simon Wiesenthal Center in Los Angeles,
a monument to the victims of the Holocaust.
</P>
<P>
   ''We wanted to show this is a coast-to-coast convention,'' said
Andy Card, the convention's co-chairman. ''We're reaching out
beyond our hall and beyond our party.''
</P>
<P>
   The outreach includes a series of videos on social programs
around the country that work without the benefit of government. On
Wednesday, video tributes will honor former Republican presidents,
and on Thursday, a biographical film will tell the Texas governor's
story.
</P>
<P>
   Political conventions, already made-for-TV productions, are now
having TV productions made for them.
</P>
<P>
   The videos fill the First Union Center,projected onto a 25-by-16
foot center screen and a pair of 9&AMP;frac12; by 12 foot screens on either
side.
</P>
<P>
   ''They're very slick,'' said Keith Martin, senior anchor at
WBRE-TV in Wilkes-Barre, Pa. ''They have a huge budget. I'm
jealous.''
</P>
<P>
   Satellites have long been used to show the presidential nominee
making his way from his hotel to the convention floor. In 1996,
Democrats expanded on the concept, beaming President Clinton into
his convention each day as he rode a campaign train to Chicago.
</P>
<P>
   Now Republicans are taking the next step. Bush will appear each
day, but he's not the only one.
</P>
<P>
   On Tuesday night, retired Gen. Norman Schwarzkopf will talk
tough from the deck of the USS New Jersey in Camden, N.J. On
Wednesday, Los Angeles Mayor Richard Riordan will lead a tour of
the Weisenthal Center.
</P>
<P>
   Convention spokeswoman Leslie Goodman said there are concerns,
particularly about the Schwarzkopf feed.
</P>
<P>
   ''You have to worry about weather and worry about line of
sight,'' she said. ''It's a much less controlled environment,
especially when you're going into a live show. These are things
that haven't been done before.''
</P>
<P>
   On Monday, House Speaker Dennis Hastert formally opened the
convention via satellite from historic Carpenter Hall. Later,
delegates heard the Rev. Herbert Lusk of Philadelphia's Greater
Exodus Baptist Community Revitalization Church preach the gospel of
Bush.
</P>
<P>
   ''We are supporting Governor Bush because we know he gives faith
a chance,'' Lusk thundered to a cheering congregation, revival
style. ''Mr. Bush, we are praying for you. Keep the faith. We love
you!''
</P>
<P>
   The delegates loved Lusk.
</P>
<P>
   ''It's almost like it came into the building,'' said Ann Bock of
Indiana, Pa. ''It seemed to take us with it.''
</P>
<P>
   And they got more excited when Bush appeared on the big screens
from the campaign trail in Ohio.
</P>
<P>
   But, as even his partisans noticed, Bush looked a little stiff
as he spoke to the camera from a classroom. Behind him were
motionless students seated and straight-faced.
</P>
<P>
   ''He felt a little nervous in front of the camera, don't you
think?'' said Dick Alderson of Westchester, Ohio.
</P>
<P>
   Brian Wilson of Macon, Miss., figured it's probably difficult to
speak in a silent room into a camera that's being projected for a
cheering convention crowd. But he figures most of his fellow
delegates were pleased.
</P>
<P>
   ''Delegates certainly love the nominee,'' he said, ''so the more
they see of him the happier they are.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-08-01-00 0247 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
