<HEADLINE> Baseball Today  </HEADLINE>
By The Associated PressSCOREBOARD:
Tuesday, August 1:
<TEXT>
<P>
   Chicago White Sox at Texas (8:35 p.m. EDT). The AL
Central-leading White Sox send All-Star James Baldwin to the mound
against Rafael Palmeiro and the Rangers.
STARS:
Monday:
</P>
<P>
   -- Darryl Kile, Cardinals, pitched his first shutout in more than
two years, giving up six hits as St. Louis blanked Montreal 4-0.
</P>
<P>
   -- Ellis Burks, Giants, had three RBIs, including a solo homer in
the 11th inning that lifted San Francisco to a 4-3 win over
Milwaukee.
</P>
<P>
   -- Woody Williams, Padres, allowed four hits and came within one
out of his second career shutout as San Diego defeated Philadelphia
4-1.
</P>
<P>
   -- Tim Hudson, Athletics, allowed one run on three hits in eight
innings as Oakland beat Toronto 6-1.
</P>
<P>
   -- Scott Spiezio, Angels, had a three-run pinch-hit homer with
two outs in the bottom of the ninth to beat Detroit 5-4.
SHAKE UP:
</P>
<P>
   Baltimore continued trading veterans Monday, sending Will Clark
to St. Louis for third baseman Jose Leon, and outfielder B.J.
Surhoff and reliever Gabe Molina to Atlanta for outfielder Trenidad
Hubbard and two minor leaguers.
SWAPS:
</P>
<P>
   On Monday, Seattle acquired outfielder Al Martin from San Diego
for outfielder John Mabry and RHP Tom Davey. ... The Padres traded
RHP Brian Meadows to Kansas City for right-hander Jay Witasick, and
also sent catcher Carlos Hernandez and a minor leaguer to St. Louis
for reliever Heathcliff Slocumb. ... The Chicago Cubs shipped Henry
Rodriguez to Florida for two minor leaguers.
SOLIDIFIED STAFF:
</P>
<P>
   Toronto bolstered its pitching Monday by acquiring right-hander
Steve Trachsel and left-hander Mark Guthrie from Tampa Bay for
minor league second baseman Brent Abernathy and a player to be
named.
STRONG START:
</P>
<P>
   Cubs right-hander Kevin Tapani allowed four hits over 6 2-3
innings in a 2-0 win over Colorado on Monday night.
SAVES:
</P>
<P>
   San Francisco's Robb Nen recorded his 26th save in a 4-3,
11-inning win over Milwaukee on Monday night, setting a major
league record for saves in July with 14, one shy of the record for
any month.
SMALL CROWDS:
</P>
<P>
   Only 8,044 fans were in Miami to see Florida's 4-2 loss to
Houston on Monday night.
STRANGE OCCURANCE:
</P>
<P>
   Boston's Hipolito Pichardo picked up his first save of the
season with two scoreless innings as the Red Sox beat Seattle 8-5
Monday night. He also struck out in a rare American League
pitcher's at-bat.
SHUT DOWN:
</P>
<P>
   Cincinnati snapped the New York Mets' six-game winning streak
with a 6-0 victory Monday night.
SPEED ACQUIRED:
</P>
<P>
   Outfielder Tom Goodwin, second in the NL in stolen bases, was
traded to Los Angeles by Colorado for outfielder Todd Hollandsworth
and two minor leaguers on Monday.
SEEKING CONTROL:
</P>
<P>
   Cincinnati's Scott Williamson threw two wild pitches in a 6-0
win over the New York Mets on Monday night, tying Jim Maloney's
team record of 19 wild pitches in a season.
SIGNED:
</P>
<P>
   The Chicago Cubs signed Rondell White to a one-year contract
extension Monday after acquiring the outfielder from Montreal for
left-handed pitcher Scott Downs.
STILL SORE AT SHEA:
</P>
<P>
   Cincinnati's Barry Larkin, who rejected a trade to New York on
July 23, was booed loudly every time his name was announced at Shea
Stadium on Monday night. The shortstop went 1-for-4 as the Reds
beat the Mets 6-0.
SORELY MISSED:
</P>
<P>
   St. Louis is 8-13 since Mark McGwire went out of the lineup with
right knee tendinitis, despite a 4-0 win in Montreal on Monday
night.
STYMIED:
</P>
<P>
   Cincinnati's Scott Williamson improved to 3-0 with an 0.51 ERA
in eight appearances against the New York Mets, including six
shutout innings in the Reds' 6-0 victory Monday night.
SNAPPED:
</P>
<P>
   Baltimore's Albert Belle ended the longest homerless drought of
his career, a string of 27 games and 109 at-bats, by hitting a
two-run shot in the first inning of the Orioles' 6-5 win over
Minnesota on Monday night. ... David Wells lost on the road for the
first time this season as Toronto was beaten by Oakland, 6-1.
STRUGGLING:
</P>
<P>
   Colorado has lost 21 of 26 games following a 2-0 loss to the
Chicago Cubs on Monday night, and the Rockies have been shut out
eight times this season -- all on the road.
SWINGS:
</P>
<P>
   Houston's Jose Lima, who started the season 1-13, won his third
straight decision with a 4-2 victory over Florida on Monday night.
SPEAKING:
</P>
<P>
   ''It was loud. But I think that's one of the reasons I've always
liked playing here. There always seems to be a lot of energy here
and I feed off that.'' -- Cincinnati's Barry Larkin on getting booed
loudly every time his name was announced in the Reds' 6-0 win at
Shea Stadium. Larkin rejected a trade to the Mets on July 23.
SEASONS:
Aug. 1:
</P>
<P>
   1906 -- Harry McIntire of Brooklyn Dodgers pitched 10 2-3 innings
of no-hit ball before Claude Ritchey of Pittsburgh singled.
McIntire weakened in the 13th and lost 1-0 to the Pirates on an
unearned run, finishing with a four-hitter.
</P>
<P>
   1941 -- New York Yankees pitcher Lefty Gomez walked 11 St. Louis
batters in a 9-0 victory to set a major league record for walks in
a shutout.
</P>
<P>
   1962 -- Bill Monbouquette of the Boston Red Sox pitched a
no-hitter to beat the White Sox 1-0 at Chicago.
</P>
<P>
   1970 -- Willie Stargell of Pittsburgh hit three doubles and two
home runs to power the Pirates to a 20-10 rout of the Braves in
Atlanta.
</P>
<P>
   1972 -- Nate Colbert of the Padres drove in 13 runs in a
doubleheader with five home runs and two singles. San Diego beat
the Atlanta Braves in both games, 9-0 and 11-7.
</P>
<P>
   1977 -- Willie McCovey of the San Francisco Giants hit his 18th
career grand slam -- a total that still leads the NL.
</P>
<P>
   1978 -- Pete Rose went 0-for-4 against Atlanta pitchers Larry
McWilliams and Gene Garber to end his 44-game hitting streak as the
Braves defeated the Cincinnati Reds 16-4.
</P>
<P>
   1986 -- Bert Blyleven threw a two-hitter and became the 10th
major league pitcher with 3,000 career strikeouts, leading the
Minnesota Twins to a 10-1 victory over the Oakland A's.
</P>
<P>
   1994 -- Baltimore's Cal Ripken became only the second major
leaguer to play 2,000 straight games as the Orioles beat Minnesota
1-0.
</P>
<P>
   1998 -- Switch-hitter Tony Clark set an AL record by homering
from both sides of the plate for the third time this year as the
Detroit Tigers defeated Tampa Bay 8-0.
</P>
<P>
   Today's birthdays: Shigetoshi Hasegawa, 32; Brian Bohanon, 32;
Gregg Jefferies, 32.
</P>
