<HEADLINE> Kodak and Minarik musters red-shirted regiment  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	   ROCHESTER, N.Y. (AP) - The Eastman Kodak Co. was in full effect
at the Republican National Convention.
</P>
<P>
   More than 30 delegates and their friends from Monroe County wore
bright red sport shirts at a pre-convention reception sponsored by
Kodak at the Pennsylvania Academy of Fine Arts.
</P>
<P>
   The shirts bore a county logo on the left breast and a slogan on
the left sleeve: ''We're leading New York.'' The garments were paid
for by Monroe County Republican Chairman Stephen J. Minarik III.
</P>
<P>
   For Kodak executives the wine and hors d'oeuvres in a fine art
gallery also amounted to a kind of marketing tool. Hundreds of New
Yorkers drifted in and out during the event.
</P>
<P>
   ''We're the largest manufacturing employer in New York state,''
said Kodak Chief Executive Officer Daniel Carp. ''These people have
to get to know me as a human being. It's my responsibility to my
employees.''
</P>
<P>
   Kodak officials did not say exactly how much they spent on the
affair. Carp brushed aside questions about Kodak buying influence
with political big shots.
</P>
<P>
   ''We compete on a world stage with the Japanese, with the
Europeans, all who have their mechanism of working with
government,'' he said. ''This gives me the chance to talk with
people I otherwise wouldn't meet.''
</P>
</TEXT>
