<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-01 10:00 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Dow Gains 5 but Nasdaq Falls 40  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP)-- Stocks opened mixed Tuesday as investors tried to
interpret conflicting signals about the U.S. economy.
</P>
<P>
   In the first half hour of trading, the Dow Jones industrial
average was up 5.63 at 10,529.33.
</P>
<P>
   The Nasdaq composite index fell 40.86 to 3,726.66. The Standard
&AMP; Poor's 500 index was down 1.82 at 1,429,19.
</P>
<P>
   In another sign that the economy is still growing rapidly,
consumer spending posted a strong rebound in June after two months
of lackluster growth, the government said Tuesday. The Commerce
Department said spending rose by 0.5 percent in June, a slightly
better-than-expected gain.
</P>
<P>
   The rebound in spending outstripped American workers' gain in
incomes, which rose up 0.4 percent in June. That was in line with
analysts' expectations.
</P>
<P>
   The uptick in spending is good news for corporations that rely
on consumer demand but it could also intensify worries about
inflation and another possible interest rate hike by the Federal
Reserve.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, investors Tuesday were also reviewing another key
report-- the National Association of Purchasing Management
manufacturing index. The manufacturing report found growth in the
nation's industrial sector remained flat in July at 51.8 percent.
Analysts had expected a small increase.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
