<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-01 12:22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> At the Movies: 'Hollow Man'  </HEADLINE>
By DAVID GERMAIN
<TEXT>
<P>
   The screenplay is almost as transparent as star Kevin Bacon, but
let's not kid ourselves. You're not going to see ''Hollow Man'' to
hear this invisible guy speak.
</P>
<P>
   You're going for the full dose of the remarkable visual wizardry
in the movie's ads, chillingly showing Bacon vanish from skin to
bone.
</P>
<P>
   ''Hollow Man,'' the latest sci-fi blood bath from director Paul
Verhoeven (''Starship Troopers,'' ''RoboCop''), is driven purely by
its visceral special effects.
</P>
<P>
   The plot is your basic
invisibility-sends-narcissist-scientist-into-ego-overdrive story,
with the cliched ex-lover (Elisabeth Shue) working alongside him
despite their rocky romantic history.
</P>
<P>
   The dialogue and characters are largely incidental, except for
the Invisible Mr. Bacon, represented for much of the movie by a
digitized stand-in depicting the actor as a smoky phantom or a
gruesome, skinless ghoul.
</P>
<P>
   Bacon plays Sebastian Caine, a brilliant, vainglorious
researcher who has discovered the secret of invisibility for a
military project and makes himself the first human guinea pig.
Trouble is, while Caine has found an antidote that restores
invisible lab animals, the counteragent doesn't work on people.
</P>
<P>
   So he's stuck in limbo, confined to an underground research
bunker except for a couple of nasty voyeuristic jaunts around
Washington, D.C.
</P>
<P>
   Delusions of godhood overwhelm him. Caine mutinies against his
fellow researchers, waging a war of attrition to eradicate anyone
with knowledge of the invisible man. Then he'll be free to do as he
pleases, rampaging through a world ignorant of his presence.
</P>
<P>
   In one of the script's few perceptive lines, Caine proclaims,
''It's amazing what you can do when you don't have to look at
yourself in the mirror.''
</P>
<P>
   Everything else is pretty much doggerel. There are vapid
exchanges among the scientists, bland repartee between Caine and
former lover Linda McKay (Shue), and a cookie-cutter romantic
triangle involving her new boyfriend (Josh Brolin).
</P>
<P>
   ''You want to know what it's like to make love to an invisible
man?'' Caine asks his ex.
</P>
<P>
   ''It would be like old times,'' McKay responds. ''You were never
there.''
</P>
<P>
   Strange they couldn't make a go of it, with wit like that to
prop up their relationship.
</P>
<P>
   The mad-scientist story line is essentially the same as H.G.
Wells' ''The Invisible Man'' and the 1933 Claude Rains classic,
adapted from the novel by director James Whale. But oh, how far
Hollywood has come from objects floating in the air and Rains
swathed in bandages.
</P>
<P>
   Bacon spent much of his time on set painted green, blue or black
so he could be matted out later, with phantom glimpses of the
invisible Caine inserted digitally, based on computer imaging of
the actor.
</P>
<P>
   Visions of Caine covered in water, mist and blood are striking.
The images of Caine vanishing and partly reappearing -- along with
the similar rematerialization of an invisible gorilla -- absolutely
dazzle.
</P>
<P>
   ''Hollow Man'' plays out much like a haunted-house story, with
all the requisite oversights by the victims. The supposedly
brilliant researchers prove themselves as dumb as fence posts when
it comes to practical matters, such as wandering the labyrinthine
bunker alone while their invisible foe stalks them, or repeatedly
failing to make sure Caine is dead when they manage to get the
better of him.
</P>
<P>
   At one point, McKay says, ''The concept of Sebastian is much
more appealing than Sebastian himself.''
</P>
<P>
   Ditto with ''Hollow Man.'' The invisibility idea was ripe for a
retread, but the movie ambles shallowly in Whale's wake, bringing
little new to the concept other than visual fireworks.
</P>
<P>
   But again, no one's going to ''Hollow Man'' for its brains.
They're going to see an invisible maniac on the prowl. In that
regard, Verhoeven and company deliver with bombastic aplomb.
</P>
<P>
   ''Hollow Man,'' distributed by Sony's Columbia Pictures, runs
114 minutes and is rated R, with loads of very visible violence.
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   Motion Picture Association of America rating definitions:
</P>
<P>
   G -- General audiences. All ages admitted.
</P>
<P>
   PG -- Parental guidance suggested. Some material may not be
suitable for children.
</P>
<P>
   PG-13 -- Special parental guidance strongly suggested for
children under 13. Some material may be inappropriate for young
children.
</P>
<P>
   R -- Restricted. Under 17 requires accompanying parent or adult
guardian.
</P>
<P>
   NC-17 -- No one under 17 admitted.
</P>
