<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-01 15:25 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> New Focus on Iraq's Standing  </HEADLINE>
By LEON BARKHO
<TEXT>
<P>
   BAGHDAD, Iraq (AP) -- Its invasion of Kuwait touched off a war
that left Iraq defeated and devastated and reduced a decade later
to a nation of children begging on street corners and families
relying on rations.
</P>
<P>
   The arrival of a senior U.N. official Tuesday focused new
attention on where this once-rich oil dynamo stands on the 10th
anniversary of its invasion and the imposition of U.N. sanctions to
punish it for the aggression
</P>
<P>
   The U.N. sanctions, which forbid trade with Iraq, are to remain
in place until U.N. weapons inspectors certify that Iraq's
biological, chemical and nuclear weapons and the missiles used to
deliver them have been destroyed.
</P>
<P>
   Without trade, the Iraqi economy has been crippled. But
President Saddam Hussein, the architect of the Kuwaiti invasion,
remains firmly in charge.
</P>
<P>
   Increasingly, attention is focusing not on what he did 10 years
ago, but on how ordinary Iraqis are suffering today.
</P>
<P>
   Tuesday's arrival of Benon Sevan, executive director of the U.N.
Office for the Iraq Program, comes at a critical stage for Iraq,
still locked in a standoff with the U.N. Security Council over
weapons inspections.
</P>
<P>
   U.N. weapons inspectors left Iraq shortly before the United
States and Britain began airstrikes in December 1998 meant to
punish Iraq for a lack of cooperation with the inspectors. The
Iraqi government has barred U.N. inspectors from returning.
</P>
<P>
   Iraq does not hide its resentment of the oil-for-food program
Sevan oversees, which places all Baghdad's dealings with the
outside world under strict scrutiny. Proceeds from oil sales under
the program, which are expected to top $10 billion in the current
six-month phase, go directly to a U.N. escrow account and are only
spent to pay for approved purchases to offset the impact of
sanctions on ordinary Iraqis.
</P>
<P>
   Cabinet ministers have frequently charged that the Iraqi people
are the last to benefit from the program, while U.N. agencies
involved in running it are the first to take advantage of it.
</P>
<P>
   More than 600 international staff work under Sevan, whose
expenses Iraq claims consume up to 4 percent of oil revenues
expected to hit $18 billion this year if oil prices hold. Some 30
percent goes to a U.N. fund to compensate victims of Iraq's 1990
invasion of Kuwait.
</P>
<P>
   But in a statement on Monday, Sevan lauded the program, saying
it has made the ''situation for many (in Iraq) significantly
better.''
</P>
<P>
   He called the U.N.-monitored oil deal ''by far the largest
humanitarian program ever administered by the United Nation.''
</P>
<P>
   U.N. Secretary-General Kofi Annan recently approved $7.1 billion
in spending under the program's present leg, which runs from June
to December.
</P>
<P>
   Neither Sevan nor his aides in Baghdad would disclose the agenda
of the current visit. But besides Iraqi complaints, Sevan is
expected to raise issues about the security of his staff.
</P>
<P>
   In late June, two U.N. staffers were killed when a gunman
stormed the headquarters of the U.N. Food and Agriculture
Organization in Baghdad. The authorities did not even condemn the
killing. Instead they seized on it, allowing the gunman to address
a news conference during which he said he acted because of concern
about the plight of his country under sanctions.
</P>
<P>
   Concerns about the safety of staff led to the suspension of U.N.
activities in the south for two weeks last month.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-08-01-00 1525 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000801.0106 </DOCNO>
