<HEADLINE> Dow Adds 52; Nasdaq Drops 60  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- Stocks were mixed Tuesday as investors mulled
conflicting signals about the U.S. economy. Technology stocks fell
on profit-taking.
</P>
<P>
   In late afternoon on Wall Street, the Dow Jones industrial
average was up 51.72 at 10,573.34.
</P>
<P>
   The Nasdaq composite index was down 60.33 at 3,706.69, giving
back nearly two-thirds of its 103.99-point advance on Monday. The
Standard &AMP; Poor's 500 index was up 6.75 at 1,437.58.
</P>
<P>
   In another sign that the economy is continuing its rapid growth,
consumer spending posted a strong rebound in June after two
lackluster months, the government said Tuesday. The Commerce
Department said spending rose by 0.5 percent in June, a slightly
better than expected gain.
</P>
<P>
   The rebound in spending outstripped American workers' gain in
incomes, which rose 0.4 percent in June. That was in line with
analysts' expectations.
</P>
<P>
   The uptick in spending is good news for corporations that rely
on consumer demand but it could also intensify worries about
inflation and another possible interest rate hike by the Federal
Reserve.
</P>
<P>
   But in another sign of an economic slowdown, construction
spending fell 1.7 percent in June, the Commerce Department said.
Analysts expected a small increase.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, investors Tuesday were also reviewing a report from
the National Association of Purchasing Management that activity in
the nation's industrial sector was unchanged in July. Analysts had
expected a small increase.
</P>
<P>
   ''The Dow with its economy-sensitive stocks is getting
encouragement from the purchasing management report that shows the
economy is slowing to healthy levels,'' said Alfred E. Goldman,
director of market analysis, A.G. Edwards &AMP; Sons Inc., St. Louis.
</P>
<P>
   Pushing the Dow higher was Disney, up $1.50 to $40.125 and
Coca-Cola, bubbling up 2.688 to $64.
</P>
<P>
   Shares of utilies, pharmaceuticals and petroleum equipment
makers were generally up.
</P>
<P>
   Internet and telecommunications stocks pulled the Nasdaq lower.
Among them were Cisco, off $1.50 at $63.25, and Worldcom, down $1
at $38.06.
</P>
<P>
   Advancing issues outnumbered decliners by a 7-to-5 margin on the
New York Stock Exchange, where volume came to 707.56 million
shares, up from Monday's pace.
</P>
<P>
   The Russell 2000 index was down 1.25 to 499.39.
</P>
