<HEADLINE> Penn Traffic to open nine supermarkets in Vermont and New Hampshire </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	   SYRACUSE, N.Y. (AP) - A decade after it pulled out of New
England, Penn Traffic Co. is going back.
</P>
<P>
   The company announced Tuesday that it had regained operating
control of six supermarkets in Vermont and three others in New
Hampshire and will have all of them open in the next two weeks. The
stores have been leased to The Grand Union Co. since 1990.
</P>
<P>
   ''We are excited about doing business again in Vermont and New
Hampshire,'' said Joseph V. Fisher, president and chief executive
officer of the struggling supermarket chain. ''Our associates are
working hard to restock the shelves and spruce up the stores as
soon as possible.''
</P>
<P>
   Grand opening ceremonies for the stores in Vermont and New
Hampshire are set for Aug. 13.
</P>
<P>
   Penn Traffic owns and operates 220 supermarkets in upstate New
York, Ohio, West Virginia, Pennsylvania, Vermont and New Hampshire
under the Big Bear, Big Bear Plus, Bi-Lo, Quality, and P&AMP;C names.
</P>
<P>
   Penn Traffic reported a loss of $26.7 million, or $1.33 per
share, for the first quarter that ended April 29. It has now lost
nearly $87 million since emerging from bankruptcy reorganization
last June.
</P>
</TEXT>
