<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-01 16:13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> France Keeps Concordes Grounded  </HEADLINE>
By JOCELYN GECKER
<TEXT>
<P>
   PARIS (AP) -- French authorities decided Tuesday to keep Air
France's Concordes grounded, saying the supersonic jetliners won't
fly again until investigators can recreate the events that sparked
last week's raging fire and deadly crash.
</P>
<P>
   Investigators have not pinpointed what led to the Concorde's
dive into a hotel in the town of Gonesse, killing 113 people. A
panel of experts will convene Thursday to try to nail down what
happened, French Transport Minister Jean-Claude Gayssot said
Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   ''Until we pull together all these elements to establish a chain
of events, Air France flights will not be resumed,'' Gayssot said
after a Cabinet meeting. He said ''absolutely no one,'' including
Air France, had pressured authorities to resume flights.
</P>
<P>
   British and French aviation experts, meeting separately from
crash investigators in Paris, have failed so far to decide which
extra safety measures should be put into place -- another mandatory
step before the Air France Concorde flights can resume, the General
Direction for Civil Aviation said.
</P>
<P>
   France's pilots applauded the move.
</P>
<P>
   ''We believe this decision is very wise,'' said Patrick Auguin,
vice president of France's National Union of Air Pilots. ''It is
very important for Concorde pilots to have confidence in their
planes.''
</P>
<P>
   An Air France charter flight from Paris to New York crashed in a
ball of flames shortly after takeoff on July 25 just outside Paris,
killing all 109 people on board and four on the ground. Bodies of
the majority of those killed had not yet been identified or
released to families.
</P>
<P>
   Air France grounded its remaining five Concordes immediately
after the crash. The world's other seven Concordes, owned by
British Airways, resumed most flights after a day's pause.
</P>
<P>
   Investigators said Monday that it could take 18 months before
they could determine the cause of the accident.
</P>
<P>
   The Transport Ministry's Accident and Inquiry Office said seven
work groups had been formed to focus on key elements of the
investigation, including the wreckage, the aircraft's systems and
engines, preparation for flight and eyewitness accounts.
Investigators said Tuesday they had not found evidence of problems
prior to takeoff.
</P>
<P>
   So far, there is evidence that one or two of the Concorde's
tires exploded and one of the plane's engines shut down, followed
by the partial shutdown of another engine. In addition, the
undercarriage did not pull up and the jet had difficulty climbing
into the sky, never achieving sufficient speed, investigators said.
</P>
<P>
   The Accident and Inquiry Office has said the flames spewing from
the side of the aircraft before it crashed most likely came from a
''major fuel leak'' and that part of a fuel tank was discovered on
the runway. Investigators said Tuesday that they have not found any
engine fragments on the runway.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, British Airways grounded one of its Concordes for
repairs Tuesday, delaying its morning flight to New York by more
than two hours.
</P>
<P>
   The plane scheduled to take the flight had just had an engine
changed, and technicians felt more adjustments needed to be made,
British Airways reported. Another Concorde was assigned to the
flight.
</P>
<P>
   Two days earlier, a British Airways Concorde flying from London
to New York had to make an emergency stop in eastern Canada after
the plane's captain smelled fuel in the cabin. Despite that and two
other weekend incidents, British Airways said it expected to
continue operating regular service out of London and New York.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
