<HEADLINE> New York's popular game species lucrative for hunters  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	   ALBANY, N.Y. (AP) - Hunters had a successful season with wild
turkeys, despite the number going down slightly from last year's
take.
</P>
<P>
   Wild turkeys, indigenous to the area but absent from New York
for almost 100 years, have returned in large numbers, according to
John Cahill, commissioner of the state Department of Environmental
Conservation.
</P>
<P>
   Cahill said wild turkey is the second most popular game to hunt,
with 250,000 hunters annually. This year hunters took 8,766
turkeys, down about 200 from last year, according to the DEC.
</P>
<P>
   They speculated the unusually cool and rainy summer may have
influenced numbers.
</P>
