<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-01 16:18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Comptroller projects $516.2 million surplus  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	   HARTFORD, Conn. (AP) - The state comptroller on Tuesday
projected that Connecticut will end the 2000 fiscal year with a
budget surplus of $516.2 million.
</P>
<P>
   Comptroller Nancy Wyman's estimate is about $46 million higher
than last month's. Wyman said higher-than-expected consumer
spending drove up tax revenues.
</P>
<P>
   Combined, the income and sales taxes will produce more than $7.3
billion, or nearly $347 million over original estimates.
</P>
<P>
   About $196 million of the surplus has already been allocated by
the Legislature. Another $35 million must go to the state's
emergency rainy day fund.
</P>
<P>
   The remainder of the nearly $285 million surplus will fund
various school construction projects.
</P>
<P>
   The final surplus figure for the fiscal year will be released
Aug. 31.
</P>
</TEXT>
