<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-01 16:19 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Indian Movie Star Is Kidnapped  </HEADLINE>
By K.N. ARUN
<TEXT>
<P>
   MADRAS, India (AP) -- For 30 years, Veerappan and his gang have
prowled the jungles of southern India, gunning down at least 130
policemen and slaughtering elephants, felling thousands of
sandalwood trees and kidnapping people, according to police.
</P>
<P>
   Among his latest victims is a 72-year-old movie star, Rajkumar,
abducted from his vacation home in the forests of Tamu Nidal state
on Sunday night along with three others.
</P>
<P>
   Veerappan, 56, has eluded police for 18 years but is believed to
be tired of running from the law and weakened by asthma. He has
offered to surrender in exchange for amnesty. He left an audio
cassette with the wife of the actor as he led his new hostages
away.
</P>
<P>
   Rajkumar's son, Ambareesh, told United News of India on Tuesday
that the eight-minute tape contained no ransom demand. In it
Veerappan warned that no Tamils should be hurt and demanded the
release of a man being held without trial.
</P>
<P>
   Veerappan -- who like many resident of southern India uses one
name -- has granted three interviews in the past, all of them to the
news magazine Nakeeran.
</P>
<P>
   He recounted in one videotaped interview how he killed his foes,
cutting up their bodies and floating them down the river or tying
up policemen and throwing them into anthills to die a slow, painful
death.
</P>
<P>
   Veerappan cupped his hands and trumpeted like an elephant or
imitated birds, deer and wild animals. He said elephants often
responded to his call, only to be shot dead.
</P>
<P>
   Veerappan said he shot his first elephant at age 10. He took to
regular ivory poaching and sandalwood smuggling in the early 1960s
and was first arrested in 1965 by Karnataka forest officials. But
he escaped, reportedly after smearing oil on his hands to slip out
of the handcuffs.
</P>
<P>
   The elusive gang leader uses his knowledge of the terrain and
animals, or the support of hunters and farmers, who regard him as a
saint. He is generous with gifts and money and has helped local
hunters over the years, in return for shelter or information about
police and forest guards.
</P>
<P>
   In a videotaped interview three years ago, Veerappan sported
olive-green fatigues and carried a gun in his hand. He is tall and
skinny, with a huge handlebar mustache and a prominent Adam's
apple.
</P>
<P>
   He became notorious in the 1980s, operating in the forests
contiguous to Karnataka and Tamil Nadu. His second arrest was in
1986 in Bangalore, but he escaped again and has not been captured
since. He once admitted to smothering his newborn daughter so her
crying wouldn't give away his hiding place.
</P>
<P>
   The 1991 killing of P. Srinivas, Karnataka Deputy Conservator of
Forests, was among his most brutal, police have said. Srinivas was
lured into the jungle on the pretext that Veerappan and his gang
were willing to surrender. A few days later, the beheaded body was
found at the edge of the forest.
</P>
<P>
   A special police and commando force reduced Veerappan's gang,
estimated at 150, to about a dozen in two years. Many died in
shootouts; others surrendered or were captured, including
Veerappan's brother, Arjunan.
</P>
<P>
   After Arjunan's arrest, Veerappan began kidnapping. Arjunan and
three other gang members died in police custody. They were said to
have committed suicide by taking poison, but Veerappan claimed they
were tortured and killed.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-08-01-00 1619 </TRAILER>
