<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Federal grant for drug and alcohol prevention programs  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	   MIDDLE ISLAND, N.Y. (AP) - A new federally funded program
designed to give local schools the flexibility to shape their own
drug and alcohol prevention programs will begin at four schools in
eastern Suffolk County.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Michael Forbes and U.S. Secretary of Education Richard
Riley announced Tuesday that four middle schools - Central Islip,
Longwood Central and South County Central school districts - would
receive a federal grant totaling $839,000.
</P>
<P>
   The money will be used to fund the hiring and training of three
new full-time coordinators for the Safe and Drug Free Schools
program. The coordinators will work with students and parents in
designing and implementing drug and alcohol prevention programs
tailored to their needs.
</P>
<P>
   ''Feeling safe in school is directly related to increased
learning,'' said Forbes. ''This new program is a step in the right
direction because it gives the schools flexibility.''
</P>
</TEXT>
