<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Colombian Attacks Trigger Response  </HEADLINE>
By WILL WEISSERT
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOGOTA, Colombia (AP) -- Colombian rebels have adopted the tactic
of hurling hundreds of combatants against small police outposts in
remote areas, and apparently taking no prisoners.
</P>
<P>
   But as the police body count rises, so is the storm of protest
against the rebels, who last weekend demolished most of a remote
mountain village in their assault.
</P>
<P>
   ''The world should be watching these attacks, they are
international atrocities,'' Monsignor Alberto Gilbert, head of the
Roman Catholic Church's conference of bishops in Colombia, told The
Associated Press on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   The weekend attack on the village of Arboleda, 90 miles
northwest of the capital Bogota, by hundreds of rebels of the
Revolutionary Armed Forces of Colombia, or FARC, killed at least 14
police officers and four civilians. Security forces were searching
on Tuesday for more victims.
</P>
<P>
   The rebels first used two car bombs to blow up the Arboleda
police station and three other buildings, crushing about a dozen
people inside. The guerrillas hurled dynamite wrapped in burning
cloth into the remains of the police station while others detonated
smaller explosives they had planted around the area.
</P>
<P>
   A church, a bank and a health clinic were among the buildings
that were demolished in the attack.
</P>
<P>
   In Washington, a spokesman for the U.S. State Department called
the rebels' action ''bloody and irresponsible.''
</P>
<P>
   Increasingly the 15,000-strong FARC has taken to attacking rural
hamlets without warning, pitting hundreds of rebels against usually
no more than a dozen or two police officers. Civilians are left to
fend for themselves in the crossfire.
</P>
<P>
   On July 15, the FARC attacked the police station in the
southwestern Colombian town of Roncesvalles. After their ammunition
ran out, 13 policemen surrendered to the rebels. The guerrillas
then systematically executed the policemen.
</P>
<P>
   Jose Miguel Vivanco, executive director of the Human Rights
Watch-Americas, noted that not all policemen and security forces
are involved in the fight with the rebels.
</P>
<P>
   ''When we see these kind of extra-judicial killings it's clear
that Colombia's violence has reached massive and extraordinary
levels,'' Vivanco said in a phone interview from Washington.
</P>
<P>
   ''There are no words to sufficiently condemn the terrible acts
of barbarism committed by these guerrillas,'' Colombian President
Andres Pastrana told a crowd Tuesday during a public ceremony in
the southwestern city of Neiva.
</P>
<P>
   Pastrana said the rebels this year have killed 73 police
officers, destroyed 51 villages and killed more than 42 civilians.
</P>
<P>
   It is not known why the rebels adopted their latest strategy,
but it is clear why it has been successful so far. Government
forces cannot protect every town, and with the villages so isolated
a large force of rebels can overwhelm a police station and escape
while reinforcements are struggling to arrive.
</P>
<P>
   ''We are astonished that those who carry out (these attacks)
pretend to be fighting for their people,'' Pastrana said.
</P>
<P>
   However, human rights observers have also criticized government
security forces and their de facto allies, right-wing paramilitary
groups, of numerous human rights violations.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-08-01-00 1636 </TRAILER>
