<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Report: Viagra May Aid Diabetics  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   BALTIMORE (AP) -- Viagra, the popular impotence drug for men,
could give relief to millions of diabetics who suffer from a
stomach condition that impedes digestion, according to new
research.
</P>
<P>
   The condition, called gastroparesis, affects as many as 12
million diabetics, and can trigger vomiting, dehydration and loss
of appetite.
</P>
<P>
   Viagra may ease the condition by helping stomach muscles to
relax, aiding in the passage of food, lead author Christopher
Ferris said Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   As an impotency drug, Viagra works much the same way, causing
certain muscles in the penis to relax and allowing improved blood
flow.
</P>
<P>
   So far, researchers have only tested their findings on mice, but
a human clinical trial could begin as early as September, Ferris
said.
</P>
<P>
   ''I'm quite optimistic,'' Ferris said, a professor at Vanderbilt
University Medical Center in Nashville, Tenn. ''I suspect what
we're seeing in the mice will be very similar to what we see in
people.''
</P>
<P>
   Viagra's manufacturer, Pfizer Inc., did not participate in the
study, Ferris said. The study appears in the August issue of
Journal of Clinical Investigation.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Marc Rendell, who has studied the effects of Viagra on
diabetics as director of the Creighton Diabetes Center in Omaha,
Neb., said he was intrigued by the research, but questioned how
successful the drug will be in treating gastroparesis.
</P>
<P>
   ''I must say I haven't seen any particular effects in diabetic
patients that seem favorable,'' said Rendell, who was not involved
in the study. ''Some patients (who use Viagra) will actually
complain of stomach upset.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
