<HEADLINE> Arms Dealer To Face German Trial  </HEADLINE>
By STEPHEN GRAHAM
<TEXT>
<P>
   BERLIN (AP) -- The German-Canadian arms-industry lobbyist at the
heart of a corruption scandal that has engulfed former German
leader Helmut Kohl and his party will have to stand trial in
Germany, a judge ruled Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   Karlheinz Schreiber, who is currently fighting efforts to
extradite him from Canada, will face charges including bribery and
tax evasion in connection with the 1991 delivery of German-built
tanks to Saudi Arabia, said Maximilian Hofmeister, a judge in the
southern town of Augsburg.
</P>
<P>
   Schreiber is suspected of being the go-between for secret
contributions to associates of Kohl that came to light last year,
triggering a wave of revelations about illegal donations to the
Christian Democratic party, which Kohl once headed.
</P>
<P>
   Kohl has been called before a parliamentary probe into whether
government decisions were influenced by the donations. The former
chancellor, while admitting that he accepted $1 million in
undeclared gifts from party supporters, has denied his government
was bought but refuses to name the party's benefactors.
</P>
<P>
   In the Augsburg case, Schreiber is accused of paying $1.8
million to Holger Pfahls, then a top official in the German defense
ministry, to ensure that 36 tanks were passed from the German army
to Saudi Arabia in 1991 after the German company Thyssen-Henschel
failed to deliver new units to the Saudi forces on time during the
Gulf War.
</P>
<P>
   Former Thyssen managers Juergen Massmann and Winifried Haastert
will also stand trial. they and Schreiber are also accused of
skimming off $12 million in undeclared commissions from the tank
deal.
</P>
<P>
   However, the judge decided not to pursue charges against former
party treasurer Walther Leisler Kiep for abetting tax evasion.
State prosecutors had argued that Kiep must have known that a
$500,000 cash donation from Schreiber to the Christian Democrats in
1991 hadn't been taxed.
</P>
<P>
   Hofmeister said it was impossible to say whether Schreiber would
be extradited in time for the trial, which is expected to start in
the first half of 2001.
</P>
<P>
   Pfahls was not charged to stand trial as the court has no
address for the former official, who is believed to be somewhere in
Asia.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-08-01-00 1705 </TRAILER>
