<HEADLINE> Polling firm sues Internet service providers over 'spamming' blacklist </HEADLINE>
By BEN DOBBIN
<TEXT>
<P>
   ROCHESTER, N.Y. (AP) - A leading Internet-based polling company
is suing America Online and a dozen other Internet service
providers for blocking correspondence with some 2.7 million of its
6.6 million online members.
</P>
<P>
   Harris Interactive Inc., which publishes the Harris poll, filed
suit in federal court late Monday seeking unspecified damages from
AOL, HotMail, Netscape and other providers that subscribe to the
''Realtime Blackhole List'' maintained by Mail Abuse Prevention
System (MAPS).
</P>
<P>
   The nonprofit California company was established to fight e-mail
abuse. Harris Interactive was added to the list for purportedly
sending unsolicited bulk e-mail or ''spam'' - an accusation the
market research company heatedly denies.
</P>
<P>
   The listing prompted service providers to block Harris
Interactive from corresponding with some 41 percent of members
served by those providers, the lawsuit alleges. The Rochester-based
company is also suing MAPS, based in Redwood City, Calif., and a
market research competitor, Incon Research of Norwalk, Conn.
</P>
<P>
   ''Harris Interactive was sending mail to people who didn't want
it,'' said Kelly Thompson, the MAPS list's project manager, ''and
they refused to change their procedures so that that could not
happen.'' She declined to comment on the lawsuit.
</P>
<P>
   Last week, Yesmail.com, a Chicago-based online marketer, won a
temporary restraining order preventing MAPS from placing Yesmail on
its list of spammers. The order was suspended after the two sides
agreed to try to negotiate a settlement.
</P>
<P>
   Harris Interactive was initially listed in December, then placed
on probation and listed again in mid-July, Thompson said. ''Anybody
is free to send us a nomination, and once we receive it, we
investigate it ... as to whether that site should be listed,'' she
said.
</P>
<P>
   Harris Interactive's chief executive, Gordon S. Black, alleged
that MAPS had acted on a complaint from Incon, a competitor ''whose
motivation to defame us appears to be based on our leadership in
the marketplace.''
</P>
<P>
   Harris Interactive is not only a pioneer in market research on
the Internet but helped develop many of the polling industry's
privacy policies, Black said. ''Nobody in our business has more
stringent standards of conduct,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The company said it sought restitution only after attempting in
vain to resolve the dispute through negotiations. The lawsuit
accuses the service providers of antitrust violations, commercial
disparagement and curtailing its ability to conduct business.
</P>
<P>
   Black called AOL's decision to block e-mails ''a particularly
egregious example of market abuse by an Internet giant,'' noting
that AOL owns Digital Marketing Systems, a research firm that is an
active competitor.
</P>
<P>
   Neither America Online nor any of its interactive brands use the
MAPS list, countered AOL spokesman Rich D'Amato. ''We are confident
that our spam-fighting techniques are entirely appropriate and that
this lawsuit against American Online has no merit,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Denying that it sends unsolicited e-mail to attract new members
to its online panel, Harris Interactive maintains instead that
members can join the panel only after registering at the company's
site and 26 other recruiting sites.
</P>
<P>
   Harris Interactive said its 6.6 million registered parties are
surveyed on diverse issues ranging from online buying habits to
public policy. Rather than being quizzed over the telephone, people
now can call up a Web page e-mail message and fill out a
questionnaire.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
