<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Amnesty International checks alleged abuse at women's prison  </HEADLINE>
By JOHN CHRISTOFFERSEN
<TEXT>
<P>
   HARTFORD, Conn. (AP) - Amnesty International said Tuesday it
plans to ask its members around the world to call for a probe of
alleged abuses at Connecticut's only prison for women.
</P>
<P>
   The human rights group wants an investigation into allegations
of sexual abuse of inmates and other misconduct by prison staff at
York Correctional Institution in Niantic, said Christine Doyle,
research director of Amnesty International U.S.A. in New York.
</P>
<P>
   The group also says prisoners have complained that male guards
do pat-down searches of the female inmates and are present when
those inmates undress or shower.
</P>
<P>
   ''We're going to do a specific action targeting York,'' Doyle
said. ''For us to target a specific institution is always
serious.''
</P>
<P>
   Amnesty has received the allegations of sexual abuse in the past
week, Doyle said.
</P>
<P>
   ''We received a few startling cases,'' Doyle said. ''Now we're
just trying to do research into it to see if they're credible.''
</P>
<P>
   Correction Department spokeswoman Christina Polce said the
agency is not aware of any recent claims of sexual abuse at York,
but would investigate. ''We take all allegations seriously,'' she
said.
</P>
<P>
   Amnesty also has received ''dozens'' of complaints of male
officers conducting pat-downs or watching nude prisoners.
</P>
<P>
   ''When you can have male officers in the same room with naked
female inmates we consider that a serious human rights abuse,''
Doyle said. ''We outright condemn it and call for an end to that
practice.''
</P>
<P>
   Polce said the department cannot assign correctional officers to
a prison based on gender.
</P>
<P>
   ''The responsibilities of a correctional employee are not gender
specific,'' Polce said. ''We should not discriminate against an
employee based on gender.''
</P>
<P>
   Daniel Kelley, a union steward at York, said correctional
officers do not stand guard while inmates shower or undress. He
said there are no open showers at the prison.
</P>
<P>
   Male officers do not strip-search female prisoners, except in an
emergency, and pat searches are done in the open, he said.
</P>
<P>
   And sexual misconduct can occur no matter who's guarding whom,
he said.
</P>
<P>
   ''The gender of the officer and the gender of the inmate doesn't
come into play,'' Kelley said.
</P>
<P>
   But Mark Ryan, an activist in Hamden, said an officer
aggressively searched his wife, who is an inmate at York.
</P>
<P>
   ''He said to her, 'I can do this all day because I'm a
corrections officer,''' Ryan said. ''To her it's very upsetting.''
</P>
<P>
   Some of the abuse reports are older, but Amnesty wants to see
how they were handled, Doyle said.
</P>
<P>
   In April, prison worker John E. Palladino, 43, was convicted of
sexually assaulting a female inmate at York. It is illegal for
staff to have sex with inmates, even if it is consensual.
</P>
<P>
   Connecticut is one of only six states that allows male guards to
conduct physical searches of female prisoners, Doyle said.
</P>
<P>
   Prison officials say the use of male guards at women's prisons
is common around the country.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
