<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-01 17:39 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> US: Progress Made on Free Trade  </HEADLINE>
By MARTIN CRUTSINGER
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- Negotiators from the United States and Jordan
made ''very substantial progress'' toward a free trade agreement
and will meet again in the fall to try and close a deal, U.S. Trade
Representative Charlene Barshefsky said Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   A free trade agreement would eliminate trade barriers between
the two countries over a period of years. The United States has
such agreements with Canada and Mexico, its partners in the North
American Free Trade Agreement, and with Israel, an agreement it
reached in 1985.
</P>
<P>
   Barshefsky said from Amman that in meetings with Jordan's King
Abdullah II and his economic advisers, both sides narrowed
differences in a number of areas.
</P>
<P>
   ''The progress is sufficiently strong that I don't believe it
will require substantial new negotiations,'' she said in a video
conference with reporters in Washington after a luncheon meeting in
Amman with Abdullah.
</P>
<P>
   She said the two sides will meet in early fall, probably in
Washington. While she refused to predict whether a deal could be
closed then, she said: ''The president and the king would both like
to get this done as quickly as possible.''
</P>
<P>
   President Clinton announced during the king's visit to
Washington in June that the two countries had agreed to negotiate a
free trade agreement to boost economic contacts. The Clinton
administration considers Jordan critical to achieving an overall
Middle East peace settlement.
</P>
<P>
   ''A strong, stable Jordan is very important for peace in the
Middle East,'' Barshefsky told reporters Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   Barshefsky said the negotiations with Jordan were based on the
outline of the deal reached with Israel, but it must be updated in
such areas as electronic commerce, which did not exist 15 years
ago.
</P>
<P>
   Jordan's official Petra news agency said Abdullah expressed hope
that a free trade agreement with the United States would boost
foreign investment in Jordan.
</P>
<P>
   ''We hope that this agreement will give a big opportunity for
international firms to invest in Jordan and to benefit from its
human resources and economic and geographic advantages,'' Abdullah
said, according to Petra.
</P>
<P>
   Deputy Prime Minister Mohammad Halayqah predicted a free trade
agreement will be reached in September.
</P>
<P>
   Since ascending to the throne in 1999 after the death of his
father, King Hussein, Abdullah has been pushing various reforms to
Jordan's economy in an effort to attract foreign investment
including seeking membership in the World Trade Organization.
</P>
<P>
   A free trade agreement with Jordan would have to be approved by
Congress. Administration officials said key Republicans and
Democrats in Congress are being kept informed on the progress of
negotiations to ensure strong support for any final agreement.
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   On the Net: http://www.ustr.gov.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
