<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-01 17:50 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> No death penalty for 19-year-old accused of killing his grandmother </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	   FREEHOLD, N.J. (AP) - Citing the family's wishes, prosecutors
won't seek the death penalty against a teen-ager accused of killing
his own grandmother.
</P>
<P>
   Brandon Cowser, 19, of Ocean Township, is accused of murder,
felony murder, robbery, conspiracy and other charges in the Nov. 30
slaying of Mattie Belle Chapman, 77, of Neptune.
</P>
<P>
   Telling her he needed a ride, Cowser allegedly lured Chapman
from her apartment, strangled her and submerged her in a creek to
make sure she was dead.
</P>
<P>
   Then, with the help of Nathaniel Burkard, he stole $3,300 from
her bank account and went on a spending spree, prosecutors say.
</P>
<P>
   Burkard, 19, of Asbury Park pleaded innocent Monday during brief
arraignments before Superior Court Judge James A. Kennedy.
</P>
<P>
   Monmouth County Prosecutor John Kaye met with members of the
family ''as a supplement to our internal review of the case by the
(prosecutor's) Homicide Review Committee and the family position
was clearly opposed to the death penalty,'' said Second Assistant
Prosecutor Robert Honecker.
</P>
<P>
   Chapman loved her grandson and supported him even when he got
into trouble. Members of her church, Good Hope Baptist Church in
Asbury Park, have urged Kaye not to seek the death penalty because
she would not have wanted it, according to Theodore V. Fishman, a
public defender.
</P>
</TEXT>
