<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Judge blocks use of uncertified teachers at troubled schools  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	   NEW YORK (AP) - A state Supreme Court justice barred the Board
of Education Tuesday from hiring or assigning uncertified teachers
in the city's poorly performing schools for the upcoming school
year.
</P>
<P>
   Justice Gloria C. Aronin issued the temporary restraining order
after Education Commissioner Richard Mills sued the city board,
alleging it had violated his order to comply with a new rules
requiring that after September 1999, new teachers at the troubled
schools had to be certified. A hearing was set for Aug. 15.
</P>
<P>
   The lawsuit, filed in Brooklyn, follows months of negotiations
between Mills and New York City Schools Chancellor Harold Levy, who
has said he was having difficulty staffing those schools with
certified teachers as required by the Board of Regents.
</P>
<P>
   An estimated 600 uncertified teachers were hired to work last
year at 99 city schools on the state's ''registration review'' list
of poorly performing schools. Mills warned Monday that the state
would take legal steps to ensure that ''students that have some of
the greatest educational needs in the city and state have highly
qualified, certified teachers.''
</P>
<P>
   School officials argued Tuesday that Mills should give them more
time to either reassign uncertified teachers or certify them
through an accelerated certification program approved by the Board
of Regents last month. Deputy Chancellor David Klasfeld called the
suit ''premature.''
</P>
<P>
   ''We don't take issue with the commissioner's order,'' Klasfeld
said. ''I think we do take issue with him going to court.''
</P>
<P>
   In an April letter to Mills, Levy said one problem he faces is
that the city board ''pays less than the market wage rate that is
necessary in this part of the state to attract an adequate pool of
certified candidates.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
