<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-01 18:21 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Dow Ends Up 85; Nasdaq Slips 81  </HEADLINE>
By PHIL GALEWITZ
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- New economic reports calmed Wall Street's
inflation fears Tuesday, sending blue chip stocks higher. But
technology stocks dropped amid profit-taking from Monday's rally.
</P>
<P>
   Stocks of health care and utility companies -- issues investors
usually turn to during economic uncertainty-- enjoyed broad gains.
</P>
<P>
   The Dow Jones industrial average rose 84.97 to 10,606.95.
</P>
<P>
   The Nasdaq composite index fell 81.47 to 3,685.52, giving back
most of its 103.99-point advance on Monday. The Standard &AMP; Poor's
500 index rose 7.27 to 1,438.10.
</P>
<P>
   Investors found comfort in three economic reports released
Tuesday -- all eased inflation worries and fears that the Federal
Reserve will raise interest rates when its policy-making Open
Market Committee meets Aug. 22. The inflation-wary Fed has already
pushed rates higher six times over the past 13 months.
</P>
<P>
   ''We got some salutary news,'' said David Orr, chief economist
at First Union Capital Markets Group in Charlotte, N.C., ''It
showed the economy was not too hot, nor too cold.''
</P>
<P>
   In the first report, the National Association of Purchasing
Management said activity in the nation's industrial sector was
unchanged in July. Analysts had expected a small increase.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, the Commerce Department reported construction
spending fell 1.7 percent in June. Analysts had also forecast a
small increase in that figure.
</P>
<P>
   A third report found stronger-than-expected consumer spending
during June, and that the gain outstripped American workers' income
gains. But investors looked past that sign of economic strength
because the Commerce Department report also found that the prices
Americans pay for goods overall were unchanged.
</P>
<P>
   ''The fact that personal spending rose faster than personal
incomes did not bother the market,'' said Alfred E. Goldman,
director of market analysts at A.G. Edwards &AMP; Sons in St. Louis.
''Spending is good as long as we are not seeing an increase in
prices nor outspending supply,'' Goldman said.
</P>
<P>
   He said the Dow with its economy-sensitive stocks got some
encouragement from the purchasing management report, which showed
the economy is slowing to healthy levels.
</P>
<P>
   Big gainers on the Dow included The Walt Disney Co., up $1.312
at $40, and Coca-Cola, up $1.562 at $62.875. Analysts upgraded
Disney partly on the strength of its ABC television show ''Who
Wants To Be A Millionaire.''
</P>
<P>
   Every major pharmaceutical company got healthier, including
Bristol-Myers Squibb, up $2.75 at $52.25 and Pfizer, up $2.625 at
$45.75.
</P>
<P>
   HMO stocks rallied, led by Cigna up $1.375 at $101.25, and
WellPoint Health Networks, up $2.50 at $89.688. Cigna's
second-quarter earnings, released after the market closed, topped
Wall Street estimates.
</P>
<P>
   Duke Energy, up $1.625 at $63.313, was one of the big gainers
among utilities.
</P>
<P>
   Internet and telecommunications stocks pulled the Nasdaq lower.
Among them were Cisco, off $2.25 at $63.188, and Worldcom, down $1
at $38.063.
</P>
<P>
   ''This is a nervous moody market that is approaching new growth
stocks in a tentative fashion-- up one day, down the next,'' Goldman
said.
</P>
<P>
   Advancing issues outnumbered decliners by a 7-to-5 margin on the
New York Stock Exchange, where composite volume came to 1.11
billion shares, down from Monday's pace.
</P>
<P>
   The Russell 2000 index was down 2.87 to 497.77.
</P>
<P>
   Overseas, Japan's Nikkei stock average rose 2.37 percent. In
afternoon trading, Germany's DAX index was down 0.70 percent,
Britain's FT-SE 100 was up 0.32 percent, and France's CAC-40 was
down 0.06 percent.
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   On the Net:
</P>
<P>
   New York Stock Exchange: http://www.nyse.com
</P>
<P>
