<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-01 18:37 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Engine Makers Accused on Pollution  </HEADLINE>
By H. JOSEF HEBERT
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- State officials and environmentalists are
complaining that truck engine manufacturers are trying to renege on
part of a much ballyhooed 1998 consent agreement with the Justice
Department to curtail pollution from large trucks.
</P>
<P>
   The complaints came as the Environmental Protection Agency
issued a formal regulation Tuesday on the first phase of a
two-stage program announced last year to cut truck pollution.
</P>
<P>
   The final EPA rule gives engine manufacturers until 2007, an
additional three years, to comply with a provision that would
require them to test truck engines under actual driving conditions
when determining if they comply with emission standards.
</P>
<P>
   Separately, six truck manufacturers, which together account for
nearly 95 percent of all diesel truck engines sold, promised in
1998 as part of a $1 billion consent agreement to design pre-sale
emissions test procedures to take into account actual highway
driving conditions.
</P>
<P>
   Attempts were unsuccessful Tuesday to reach officials at any of
the six engine manufacturing companies.
</P>
<P>
   The consent agreement stemmed from EPA findings that the
manufacturers for years had installed devices that allowed trucks
to pass the pre-sale tests, but then exceed pollution requirements
during actual highway driving.
</P>
<P>
   The manufacturers as part of the agreement said they would
remove the devices during overhaul and that is being done.
</P>
<P>
   But the manufacturers also promised to have the more realistic
pre-sale emissions testing procedures in place by 2002 under the
consent agreement. A proposed EPA rule announced last fall called
for all manufacturers to have the new test procedures in place by
2004.
</P>
<P>
   But the final rule issued Tuesday extends the deadline until
2007. While the rule does not affect the consent agreement, the
extension could give manufacturers ammunition to argue for a change
in the agreement as well, some environmentalists fear.
</P>
<P>
   ''Now the companies are pressing their case at the Justice
Department'' to get a similar extension as part of the consent
agreement, said Frank O'Donnell, who has followed the issue for
Clean Air Trust, an environmental advocacy group.
</P>
<P>
   Robert Perciasepe, head of the EPA's air pollution office, said
that the decision to give manufacturers until 2007 to put in place
the new test procedures won't affect emission reductions.
</P>
<P>
   ''The bottom line is, the rule is a 40 percent reduction in
nitrogen oxide emissions from diesel engines,'' said Perciasepe in
an interview. He said the tougher emission standards the EPA is
proposing for 2007 will require companies to conduct more stringent
pre-sale engine tests.
</P>
<P>
   The manufacturers have complained to the EPA and Justice
Department that they can't meet the requirement for the more
stringent testing procedures by 2002 and 2004, especially under
driving conditions in hot or cold weather or at higher altitudes.
</P>
<P>
   State air pollution control officials also have complained about
the manufacturers' attempt to relax the requirements under the 1998
consent decree, which at the time was hailed by EPA and Justice
officials as one of the most important environmental enforcement
victories achieved by the Clinton administration.
</P>
<P>
   ''We're worried if manufacturers once again break their consent
decrees and emit far more (pollution) than allowed, it could
acerbate our ability to meet federal health based (air quality)
standards,'' said Bill Becker, executive director of the
Association of State and Territorial Air Pollution Administrators.
</P>
<P>
   Becker wrote to Justice and EPA officials this week urging that
the manufacturers' requests for extensions on the test procedure
requirements be rejected.
</P>
<P>
   ''We absolutely cannot afford any backsliding,'' wrote Becker.
</P>
<P>
   A day later, the EPA issued its final rule giving the
manufacturers an additional three years to comply with the new
testing requirements. Justice has yet to make a decision on whether
to agree to changes in the consent agreement.
</P>
<P>
   The companies that signed the 1998 consent agreement were Mack
Trucks Inc., Cummins Engine Co., Detroit Diesel Corp., Navistar
International Transportation Co., Caterpillar Inc., Renault and
Volvo Truck Corp. Renault and Volvo truck companies have since
merged.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-08-01-00 1837 </TRAILER>
