<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-01 18:41 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> USDA To Give Farmers Sugar  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- Hoping to boost depressed sugar prices, the
Agriculture Department announced plans Tuesday to give
government-held sugar to farmers who agree to plow under some of
this year's crop.
</P>
<P>
   The program also is intended to discourage farmers from
forfeiting to the government some 1.4 million tons of sugar that
are being held under federal marketing loans.
</P>
<P>
   The Agriculture Department currently holds about 174,000 tons of
sugar left over from the 1999 crop -- the equivalent of 2 percent of
this year's projected production. The amount of sugar available for
USDA to give to farmers is expected to increase as farmers forfeit
some of the stocks that are now under loan.
</P>
<P>
   Giving the surplus to farmers to entice them to destroy part of
this year's crop will save the government on monthly storage costs,
currently about $2 a ton, USDA officials said.
</P>
<P>
   ''We're optimistic that it will get a significant amount of
acreage out of production and restore balance to the U.S. market,''
said Jack Roney, an economist for the American Sugar Alliance, a
growers' group.
</P>
<P>
   USDA is unsure what the impact will be on production and prices,
said Mary Beth Schultheis, a spokeswoman for Agriculture Secretary
Dan Glickman.
</P>
<P>
   ''This will depend on producers' interest in enrolling in the
program,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Farmers would not take possession of the sugar itself but would
instead receive a ''payment-in-kind'' certificate that they could
redeem for cash.
</P>
<P>
   By law, no producer can receive more than $20,000 each, the
equivalent of 15 acres of sugar beets, which is about 7 percent of
the average farmer's production.
</P>
<P>
   Wholesale sugar prices are down 23 percent this year because of
heavy domestic production and a surge in imports. Some farmers
switched to sugar beets in recent years when prices for corn and
other crops dropped sharply.
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   On the Net: USDA's Farm Service Agency: http://www.fsa.usda.gov
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
