<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-01 18:52 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Democrats say if Torricelli can't stop McGreevey, no one can  </HEADLINE>
By JOHN P. McALPIN
<TEXT>
<P>
   TRENTON, N.J. (AP) - U.S. Sen. Robert Torricelli has a national
reputation as his party's money man and Clinton defender. Jim
McGreevey is the local glad-hander whose network of union leaders,
party operatives and other supporters scared away the senator from
making a run for governor.
</P>
<P>
   If McGreevey's candidacy is so strong it blocked Torricelli,
Democrats say others don't have a chance.
</P>
<P>
   ''If Bob Torricelli's candidacy can't take off, Bob Torricelli
who some people were calling the 800-pound gorilla, how do the
other 125-pound gorillas take off? It's just not going to happen,''
state chairman Tom Giblin said Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   McGreevey has worked to build his campaign for governor since
his narrow loss to Republican Gov. Christie Whitman in 1997.
Whitman is barred from seeking a third term.
</P>
<P>
   The Woodbridge Township mayor appeared to be the party's
presumptive nominee until Torricelli started soliciting support.
</P>
<P>
   Two weeks ago Torricelli admitted his ambitions to leave
Washington for Trenton.
</P>
<P>
   On Monday he withdrew, citing in part McGreevey's support.
Torricelli's announcement came hours after McGreevey garnered
public endorsements from 30 elected Democrats, including Newark
Mayor Sharpe James.
</P>
<P>
   On Tuesday afternoon McGreevey was in Jersey City where he
collected endorsements from U.S. Rep. Bob Menendez and several
Hudson County officials.
</P>
<P>
   McGreevey has a Statehouse news conference scheduled for
Wednesday where he plans to announce more endorsements from county
Democratic organizations.
</P>
<P>
   ''For the past six years we have been working real hard, in fact
daily, to build a broad-based coalition,'' McGreevey said. ''On an
ongoing basis, I have worked to forge relationships, in fact
friendships.''
</P>
<P>
   Those relationships now show in the form of support from across
the state, McGreevey said.
</P>
<P>
   No one else is as good at building those relationships, what
politicians call ''retail politics'', Giblin said.
</P>
<P>
   ''He went to their weddings, their wakes, their parties,''
Giblin said.
</P>
<P>
   And right now no other candidate is doing that, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ''I just don't see it. Everybody knows Bob Torricelli is one of
the top three or four fund-raisers in the country and all he brings
to the party. And still the support is there for McGreevey,''
Giblin said.
</P>
<P>
   But not all Democrats are buying that party line.
</P>
<P>
   ''I don't think the electoral process was meant to be a
coronation,'' said Walter Fields, a Democratic consultant. ''If we
are simply going to have this process of anointment, then we might
as well eliminate the primaries. They're meaningless.''
</P>
<P>
   Fields, who once headed the state chapter of the NAACP, said
Democrats should be worrying about more than just collecting
support from party bosses.
</P>
<P>
   Residents, voters and rank-and-file party members need to be
included and their concerns addressed by a candidate, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ''That's the critical question we should be asking: What is this
candidate saying?'' Fields said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-08-01-00 1852 </TRAILER>
