<BODY>
<HEADLINE> 51 Injured in Japan Factory Blast  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   TOKYO (AP) -- A powerful explosion tore through a gunpowder
factory in western Japan Tuesday, injuring at least 51 area
residents and shattering windows in buildings up to a mile away.
</P>
<P>
   Most of those injured in the blast at Nihon Yushi Co.'s
gunpowder-making plant were hit by flying glass or other objects,
said Seiichi Tsuchida, a spokesman for the town of Taketoyo. None
of the injuries was life-threatening.
</P>
<P>
   The casualty toll in the 10:30 p.m. blast could have been higher
but the factory was not operating because of a summer holiday.
</P>
<P>
   Witnesses said 150-foot flames shot up from a fire that engulfed
the factory, destroying several of its buildings, according to
Tsuchida. The factory was located in Aichi prefecture (state),
about 155 miles west of Tokyo.
</P>
<P>
   ''At first I thought it was a big earthquake,'' Tsuchida said of
the 10:30 p.m. blast. He said glass was shattered at a shop about
one mile away. Kyodo News agency reported that 161 homes were
damaged.
</P>
<P>
   Officials said police were trying to determine the cause of the
blast.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
