<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-01 20:22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Cinnaminson man pleads guilty to Medicaid fraud  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	   TRENTON, N.J. (AP) - A Cinnaminson man pleaded guilty Tuesday to
charges that he defrauded the Medicaid Program by billing it for
substance abuse programs he never held.
</P>
<P>
   Tommie Murry, 41, pleaded guilty to conspiracy, theft by
deception and corporate misconduct, as well as two counts of
Medicaid fraud.
</P>
<P>
   He was charged with defrauding Medicaid of about $600,000.
</P>
<P>
   Murry had been employed as the executive director of The Excel
Center, a now defunct outpatient drug and alcohol treatment center
formerly located in Vineland. It provided services to many Medicaid
patients.
</P>
<P>
   Murry and The Excel Center submitted bills to Medicaid for
multiple sessions of group alcohol and drug therapy for Medicaid
patients. But the groups never took place, said John Smith, acting
insurance fraud prosecutor.
</P>
<P>
   Under the terms of the guilty plea, The Excel Center will be
fined $10,000 and will forfeit about $1.7 million in Medicaid
claims, Smith said.
</P>
<P>
   Murry faces up to five years in prison when he is sentenced Oct.
13.
</P>
<P>
   Murry has an unlisted phone number and could not be reached for
comment.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
