<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-01 20:25 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Media Empire Denies Talk of Sale  </HEADLINE>
By JIM HEINTZ
<TEXT>
<P>
   MOSCOW (AP) -- The media holding company of beleaguered tycoon
Vladimir Gusinsky on Tuesday denied reports that the company may be
sold to the state-controlled natural gas monopoly Gazprom.
</P>
<P>
   The company, Media-Most, also accused the Kremlin of doing
''everything'' it could to create financial problems for the
company, which includes broadcast and print outlets that have been
critical of President Vladimir Putin.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, another mogul, Boris Berezovsky, said Tuesday he has
begun talks with the government on selling back his stock in
Russia's premier television network, ORT. Berezovsky controls a 49
percent stake in ORT; the state has a controlling interest.
</P>
<P>
   Observers said such deals could threaten media freedom by giving
the government greater control over the influential outlets.
</P>
<P>
   Gusinsky was jailed for four days in June after being arrested
on charges of cheating the state of some dlrs 10 million in a
privatization deal. Gusinsky and many observers saw the arrest as a
Kremlin attempt to crack down on independent-minded media. But the
case was abruptly dropped last month for lack of evidence.
</P>
<P>
   The newspaper Kommersant -- which is owned by Berezovsky, a
Gusinsky rival -- reported Tuesday that Media-Most and
Gazprom-Media, an arm of the gas company, held a meeting Monday
about selling Media-Most to the gas monopoly.
</P>
<P>
   ''All that is said in the story does not conform to reality,''
said a statement released by Media-Most.
</P>
<P>
   Gazprom already owns about 30 percent of Media-Most's NTV
television channel and holds 17-20 percent more of NTV's stock as
collateral for a loan. Gazprom, which also owns media outlets that
compete with Media-Most's, has been stepping up pressure on NTV in
recent months to settle its debts.
</P>
<P>
   The Media-Most statement lashed out at the Kremlin, which its
said ''has done everything in the past year to create additional
financial problems for the holding.''
</P>
<P>
   ''The main goal ... is to establish control over NTV and change
the leadership of the company and with them, it is understood, the
editorial politics,'' the statement said.''
</P>
<P>
   Gazprom-Media chief Alfred Kokh said talks were under way on
Media-Most's debts to the gas company, but said sale of the media
holding as a whole was not under discussion, the Interfax news
agency reported.
</P>
<P>
   But analysts say such a deal has long been under consideration.
</P>
<P>
   Berezovsky announced plans recently to merge his media outlets
into a single holding that would help protect his political
interests. He said Tuesday that the holding could include his stake
in ORT if talks on selling his stock to the government fail,
Interfax reported.
</P>
<P>
   ORT administrators could not be immediately reached for comment,
and the Kremlin press service said it had no information on the
talks.
</P>
<P>
   Media-Most's flagship NTV television network is seen as
important to Russian democracy, as the only one of the country's
three major networks that is not state-controlled. ORT's coverage
of the government has been largely favorable.
</P>
<P>
   Gusinsky has been in Spain with his family since last week, and
has not commented publicly on the end of the probe against him.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-08-01-00 2025 </TRAILER>
