<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-01 20:34 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Protests Break Out Over Chavez  </HEADLINE>
By TIMOTHY WARREN
<TEXT>
<P>
   CARACAS, Venezuela (AP) -- Supporters of President Hugo Chavez
and opposition backers exchanged blows and threw rocks and bottles
at each other Tuesday in clashes over results from last weekend's
elections.
</P>
<P>
   Chavez ordered in federal troops to southwestern Merida state to
quell the violence that left nine people injured after results
showed an incumbent governor from an opposition party there losing
to a pro-Chavez candidate.
</P>
<P>
   ''We had to send troops ... because the governor tells us he's
not going to give up his government to the revolutionary
candidate,'' Chavez, who says he is leading a ''social revolution''
for Venezuela, told reporters in the capital, Caracas.
</P>
<P>
   New election results Tuesday gave the opposition fewer
governorships than previously announced, stirring disputes between
Chavez supporters and the opposition.
</P>
<P>
   In Sunday's elections, Venezuelans voted for the president, the
legislature, governors, mayors and other officers to
''re-legitimize'' the overhauled political system created in a new
constitution pushed through by Chavez last year.
</P>
<P>
   Chavez won re-election handily with a 21-point lead over his
nearest challenger, former Zulia state Gov. Francisco Arias. His
coalition also won about 60 percent of the new 165-member
legislature.
</P>
<P>
   The revised results published Tuesday gave Chavez's leftist
Patriotic Pole coalition at least 14 of Venezuela's 23
governorships. Earlier results had given the opposition a slim
majority but the final count gave them only seven. The allegiance
of the remaining two governorship was unclear.
</P>
<P>
   Some of the governorships were still in limbo Tuesday, however,
because candidates were disputing the results.
</P>
<P>
   The dispute in southwestern Merida state turned violent when
supporters of the incumbent governor, William Davila, clashed with
Chavez backers. The violence injured nine people and forced local
businesses to close, the state government said.
</P>
<P>
   Davila, who was way ahead in pre-election polls, held a close
lead over Chavez ally Florencio Porras as initial balloting came
in. But results released Tuesday showed Porras up by some 1,750
votes.
</P>
<P>
   Davila called the count ''a fraud,'' questioning why more than
9,500 votes have been declared invalid.
</P>
<P>
   The secretary-general of Davila's Action Democratic Party,
Timoteo Zambrano, pleaded with international election monitors to
stay in the country, saying ''it's not true that these elections
have been transparent.''
</P>
<P>
   Officials of the Organization of American States, which sent an
observer team to Venezuela, said they did not detect any
irregularities but added they would withhold final judgment until
more information is available.
</P>
<P>
   Attorney general Javier Elechiguerra announced Tuesday his
office was investigating complaints of voting irregularities in
seven states.
</P>
<P>
   Chavez said Tuesday his coalition would continue fighting for
its candidates in disputed elections. ''We're consolidating our
revolution, and like any battle, we have to care for it up to the
last bit of territory,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Despite his landslide victory, Chavez now faces a viable
opposition for the first time since he took office last year and
plowed through his ''social revolution.''
</P>
<P>
   Chavez will have to negotiate and make deals to get his most
radical changes approved, since many require a two-thirds majority
in Congress.
</P>
<P>
   In his victory speech, Chavez appealed to the Roman Catholic
Church, business leaders and the political opposition -- all of whom
he derided in his first 18 months in office -- to help get Venezuela
back on its feet.
</P>
<P>
   ''A balance of power has been restored. Now we have to see how
Chavez responds,'' newspaper editor Teodoro Petkoff said Monday on
a local radio show.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-08-01-00 2034 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
