<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-01 20:40 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Autopsy Done On Kansas State Player  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   MANHATTAN, Kan. (AP) -- An autopsy was performed Tuesday to
determine the cause of death of Kansas State tackle Anthony Bates,
a university spokesman said.
</P>
<P>
   Doug Dull, the university's sports information director, said
Tuesday he had no further information about the death of the
20-year-old from Tempe, Ariz. It wasn't known when autopsy results
would be available.
</P>
<P>
   Bates was driving near campus Monday when he suffered a
''medical condition,'' the university said without providing
details.
</P>
<P>
   His pickup truck crossed into the opposite lane and struck a
car, then continued south about 800 feet before hitting two parked
cars and coming to a stop, according to a Riley County police
report.
</P>
<P>
   The report said Bates was unconscious and taken to Mercy Health
Center, where he died at 3:18 p.m. A hospital spokesman said he
could provide no information, deferring to Kansas State.
</P>
<P>
   Bates, a 6-foot, 280-pound redshirt junior, was due to report
for practice on Thursday with other veteran players.
</P>
<P>
   ''I know that I speak for each and every member of this program
in expressing our pain, our compassion and our deep, deep sympathy
for Anthony's parents, relatives and friends who also are suffering
tremendously over the tragic passing of this very special young
man,'' Kansas State coach Bill Snyder said in a statement.
</P>
<P>
   ''Anthony, simply and honestly put, was a wonderful person;
caring, giving, unselfish and friendly. He was a man of character
and values. To say we hurt, to say we miss him, to say we love him
is dramatically understated. I ask all Wildcat fans to include
Anthony, his family and his teammates in their prayers during this
period of mourning.''
</P>
<P>
   Bates transferred to Kansas State from Phoenix Junior College
and was a redshirt last season.
</P>
<P>
   ''He was just perfect in every since of the word,'' Phoenix JC
assistant head coach Loren Dawson said. ''He was never in trouble
and was not only in class, but excelled in class. He wasn't
recruited hard by the bigger schools out of high school because of
his height, but when we got him, he was a difference-maker for us.
He was one of the best players we ever had. Nobody ever worked
harder.''
</P>
<P>
   The accident happened on the day newcomers reported to preseason
camp for the Wildcats, who are starting practice early to prepare
for their Aug. 26 opener against Iowa in the Eddie Robinson Classic
at Arrowhead Stadium.
</P>
<P>
   A management information systems major, Bates earned academic
honors on the Big 12 Conference Commissioner's Honor Roll in three
semesters.
</P>
<P>
   He was an all-state player at Mountain Pointe High School in
Phoenix, graduating in 1997.
</P>
<P>
   Bates was an Eagle Scout and a member of the National Honor
Society and Fellowship of Christian Athletes. He is survived by his
parents, Allen and Sharon.
</P>
<P>
   Plans for a memorial service were pending.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-08-01-00 2040 </TRAILER>
