<HEADLINE> Bus crash on West 34th Street leaves at least three seriously injured </HEADLINE>
By LUKAS I. ALPERT
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) - A city bus struck and seriously injured an NYPD
traffic agent Tuesday evening, then jumped a curb and crashed into
a Solomon Smith Barney building.
</P>
<P>
   Two other people were seriously hurt, and at least 34 injured in
all. Many were treated at the scene by dozens of medical
technicians, according to a Fire Department spokesman and eye
witnesses.
</P>
<P>
   The wreck happened on 34th Street between Eighth and Ninth
avenues in Manhattan and temporarily halted traffic on the block.
The eastbound bus was left standing on end in the middle of the
street, its front section in the doorway of the 10-story building
it struck.
</P>
<P>
   Jean Bolcy, 34, works around the corner from the accident and
said he saw the bus driver slumped over the wheel before the bus
came to rest.
</P>
<P>
   ''I saw the bus jump up on the sidewalk and through the trees.
He didn't even slow down,'' Bolcy said. ''If he hadn't hit that
wall, he'd still be going.''
</P>
<P>
   The bus hit the traffic agent as the agent leaned into the
window of a parked car, Bolcy said. Another witness reported seeing
the bus driver thrown out a window when he hit the building.
</P>
<P>
   Others ''were jumping out of the windows of the bus and
running,'' Bolcy said.
</P>
<P>
   It wasn't immediately clear whether any pedestrians other than
the traffic agent were hurt.
</P>
<P>
   Two of those seriously hurt were taken to St. Vincent's
Hospital. The third went to Bellevue.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
