<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-01 20:46 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Lazio makes cameo appearance at GOP convention  </HEADLINE>
By JESSE J. HOLLAND
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHILADELPHIA (AP) - New York U.S. Senate candidate Rick Lazio
used his brief appearance Tuesday at the Republican National
Convention to slam first lady Hillary Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   ''I don't know about you, but I don't want to be lectured for
the next six years by Hillary Rodham Clinton,'' Lazio told a
cheering New York GOP delegation.
</P>
<P>
   Lazio, running in a state where Democrats hold a 5-to-3 voting
advantage, sought to keep his distance from the more conservative
national GOP platform, including its anti-abortion plank. He
carefully managed all of his public appearance so that beyond doing
media interviews, he appeared only with moderate New York
politicians like Gov. George Pataki and New York City Mayor Rudolph
Giuliani.
</P>
<P>
   He also publicly rejected the national platform, especially the
recently reaffirmed anti-abortion platform. ''I don't support the
anti-abortion plank,'' Lazio said. ''I think the platform, frankly,
has become largely obsolete.''
</P>
<P>
   He said GOP presidential nominee George W. Bush's more
mainstream ideas were the real party platform. ''Governor Bush is
running on the ideas that he believes in and that's what's
important,'' he said. ''I'm running on the ideas that I believe in.
I'll be running on my record.''
</P>
<P>
   A Zogby International poll Sunday had Lazio holding a slight
lead over Clinton, 50 percent to 42 percent with a 4 percentage
point margin of error. Several of the most recent previous polls
had shown the two in a dead heat.
</P>
<P>
   Lazio stepped into the race for the seat of retiring Democratic
Sen. Daniel Patrick Moynihan when Giuliani dropped out in May after
being diagnosed with prostate cancer.
</P>
<P>
   Lazio reminded supporters that support for him against Clinton
could help Bush against Vice President Al Gore in New York, which
usually votes Democratic in presidential elections. ''We are
effectively running against the White House and all that entails,''
he said. ''The better we do, the worse it is for them.''
</P>
<P>
   Pataki also jumped on Clinton, telling a cheering breakfast
crowd that Clinton didn't know the difference between Erie County,
N.Y., and Erie, Pa. - a reference to her calling a Pennsylvania
radio station last week thinking she was calling one in New York -
and that when Bush wins: ''We will finally have a first lady we can
be proud of.''
</P>
<P>
   Hoping to spoil Lazio's day, New York Democratic Party
Chairwoman Judith Hope appeared at the New York GOP's hotel to call
on Lazio to release his income tax records. ''We just decided to
follow him here to Philadelphia ... to tell him we're not going
away, we really think he should do the right thing,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Former New York U.S. Sen. Alfonse D'Amato defended Lazio and
pointed out all of the financial controversies the first lady has
been part of. ''The last person in the world to be attacking anyone
is Judith Hope,'' D'Amato said. ''If she wants to talk about
someone's tax record, she should look at their own candidate,
Hillary Clinton.''
</P>
<P>
   Lazio said he would release his tax record by the end of summer.
</P>
<P>
   Meantime, Lazio supporters said his low profile in Philadelphia
illustrates how different he is from Mrs. Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   ''Rick's focus has to be on New York and not on national
politics,'' Pataki said.
</P>
<P>
   On the other side, New York GOP consultant and television
commentator Jay Severin said Lazio's image could be harmed by
spending a lot of time at a convention that just reaffirmed the
party's anti-abortion and other conservative planks.
</P>
<P>
   ''He doesn't need to give Hillary Clinton big fat targets to
shoot at,'' he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-08-01-00 2046 </TRAILER>
