<HEADLINE> Syracuse division to build systems for $8 million contract  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	   BETHESDA, Md. (AP) - A division of Bethesda-based Lockheed
Martin has received an $8 million contract to supply radar
technology to the Hellenic Merchant Marine Ministry in Greece.
</P>
<P>
   Lockheed's Naval Electronics and Surveillance Systems-Radar
Systems division, based in Syracuse, will build at least 10 radar
systems for the Greek government. They will be installed at a
number of stations and service centers guiding vessels through the
Ionian and Aegean Sea.
</P>
<P>
   ''The Greek government selected our team based on our reputation
and technology to provide safe navigation for one of the major
maritime nations in the world,'' said Mike Smith, president of the
Naval Electronics and Surveillance Systems division.
</P>
<P>
   Similar Lockheed technology is used by the U.S. Coast Guard and
maritime agencies in 14 countries around the world.
</P>
</TEXT>
