<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-01 21:03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Pataki gets increased role in convention  </HEADLINE>
By JESSE J. HOLLAND
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHILADELPHIA (AP) - Gov. George Pataki, who started the National
Republican Convention hosting intimate breakfast meetings, assumed
a higher profile Tuesday when tapped to replace actor Bruce Willis
for a tribute to the surviving GOP presidents.
</P>
<P>
   Pataki, a diehard supporter of Texas Gov. George W. Bush,
provided the narration while video clips of the Ronald Reagan,
Gerald Ford and George Bush presidencies played on large screens
for delegates.
</P>
<P>
   Ford, 87, and Bush, 76, were on hand for the event. Former first
lady Nancy Reagan attended in behalf of her 89-year-old husband,
who has Alzheimer's disease.
</P>
<P>
   Pataki's name came up Monday when schedulers found out that
Willis could not keep his commitment.
</P>
<P>
   Not a bad consolation prize for someone who had been on Bush's
short-list of potential running mates.
</P>
<P>
   ''It was March of '99 when I endorsed Governor Bush and since
that time I've been trying to be supportive,'' Pataki said.
</P>
<P>
   Pataki will meet Bush when the presumed nominee arrives at the
Philadelphia airport Wednesday, and introduce him at a rally there.
</P>
<P>
   Bush seems willing to have the New York governor closely
involved. Pataki is one of a group of Republican governors here in
Philadelphia entrusted by Bush to rev up the delegates.
</P>
<P>
   ''They pick people they think have the creditability to go out
and talk to delegations about the issues on which Governor Bush is
basing his campaign,'' Pataki spokeswoman Zenia Mucha said.
</P>
<P>
   Pataki led the cheerleading - on a different subject every day
but always along the Republican convention theme - to delegates
from Idaho, Nevada, Delaware, Michigan, North Carolina, Virginia,
Massachusetts and California.
</P>
<P>
   Pataki continued to deflect questions about his willingness to
accept a job in a Bush cabinet.
</P>
<P>
   ''I love being governor, I've always loved being governor,'' he
said. ''I'm going to continue to do everything I can to continue to
make New York, our great state, a better state and I'm going to try
from now until November 7 to help Governor Bush in any way I can
but I love being governor.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
