<HEADLINE> Pirates Sign Benjamin To Extension  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   PITTSBURGH (AP) -- The Pittsburgh Pirates signed reserve
infielder Mike Benjamin to a $1.85 million, two-year contract
extension Tuesday, one day after utilityman John Vander Wal agreed
to a two-year deal.
</P>
<P>
   Benjamin has played second base, shortstop and third base since
signing with the Pirates as a free agent before the 1999 season,
batting .247 in 110 games last year.
</P>
<P>
   ''Without question, he's been a real good player for us,''
general manager Cam Bonifay said. ''He's probably as good as there
is at what he does.''
</P>
<P>
   Benjamin, 34, is hitting .277 with two homers and 15 RBIs this
season. He has made only 10 errors in his two Pirates seasons. He
is a .234 career hitter in 12 seasons with the Giants, Phillies,
Red Sox and Pirates.
</P>
<P>
   Benjamin, who has a $700,000 salary this season, will make
$925,000 per year in 2000 and 2001. He could make an additional
$300,000 per year in incentives based on plate appearances.
</P>
