<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-01 21:43 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Unifrax announces plans to merge with Carborundum  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	   NIAGARA FALLS, N.Y. (AP) - Ceramic fibers maker Unifrax Corp. on
Monday moved to double its size with the acquisition of Carborundum
Insulation Technologies.
</P>
<P>
   Unifrax officials said the deal potentially pushes Unifrax's
sales above $160 million while making the company a major
international player in the high-temperature insulating products
market.
</P>
<P>
   ''We, for the most part, have been a North American-focused
business,'' said Paul J. Viola, Unifrax's vice president of
acquisitions and strategic development. ''That kept us out of about
two-thirds of the worldwide ceramic fiber market.''
</P>
<P>
   Viola said the acquisition is not expected to have any direct
impact on the company's Western New York operations, which include
plants in Tonawanda, Amherst, and Sanborn, as well as its
headquarters and research laboratory in Niagara Falls.
</P>
<P>
   The deal reunites Unifrax - the U.S. ceramics fiber business
that St. Gobain SA did not acquire when it purchased most of
Carborundum's operations in 1995 - with what had been its foreign
sister business, at once providing the company visibility to the
worldwide ceramic fiber market, Viola said.
</P>
<P>
   The acquisition is expected to help Unifrax sell its new Isofrax
thermal insulation, which the company is marketing as a new type of
insulation that meets European health and safety regulations.
Isofrax, which is made of bio-soluble fiber, can be used to
insulate turbines, furnaces, kilns and flues, as well as other high
temperature uses.
</P>
<P>
   The terms of the deal were not disclosed. Unifrax said it will
finance the acquisition with a combination of bank debt and seller
financing. The purchase is expected to close by the end of
September.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-08-01-00 2143 </TRAILER>
