<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000801.0198 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-01 21:43 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Diamond Trade Targeted in Africa  </HEADLINE>
By EDITH M. LEDERER
<TEXT>
<P>
   UNITED NATIONS (AP) -- Accused of fueling Sierra Leone's civil
war, Liberia and Burkina Faso promised Tuesday to cooperate with
investigations and asked for aid to end the illegal trade in
diamonds and arms in their countries.
</P>
<P>
   The United States and Britain charged Monday that the presidents
of the two West African countries were helping Sierra Leone's
notorious rebels sell diamonds and buy increasingly sophisticated
weapons that have kept the nine-year war going.
</P>
<P>
   The two-day open hearing on the role of ''blood diamonds'' in
the war, organized by the U.N. Security Council committee
monitoring sanctions against Sierra Leone, put the spotlight on
Liberia and Burkina Faso as conduits for the illegal trade in
diamonds and weapons.
</P>
<P>
   Bangladesh's U.N. Ambassador Anwarul Chowdhury, who chairs the
committee, said it will examine the allegations against the two
countries. ''Before the Security Council takes a decision, it has
to look into these more closely and more thoroughly,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   In early July, the Security Council imposed a ban on the
purchase of Sierra Leone diamonds that don't have a government
certificate. The move was aimed at strangling the ability of the
rebel Revolutionary United Front to finance the civil war, which
has killed and maimed tens of thousands.
</P>
<P>
   U.S. Ambassador Richard Holbrooke warned Monday that Washington
would support measures against Burkina Faso and Liberia unless they
stop facilitating rebel diamond sales. U.S. officials said the
measures could include freezing the countries' foreign assets and
visa restrictions on senior officials.
</P>
<P>
   Liberian Foreign Minister Monie Captan and Burkina Faso's U.N.
Ambassador Michel Kafando demanded proof of the allegations.
</P>
<P>
   At Tuesday's concluding session, Captan noted that Sierra Leone
recently reported an increase in its diamond revenue and asked
whether the government there might be selling rebel diamonds since
the RUF still controls about 90 percent of the diamond mines.
</P>
<P>
   He said Liberia will ''actively participate'' in a regional
investigation of the illegal diamond trade, which includes RUF
representatives.
</P>
<P>
   ''Liberia remains committed to working with the international
community in finding ways and means of bringing to an end the
illegal trade in arms and diamonds,'' Captan said.
</P>
<P>
   The Liberian minister urged the international community and U.N.
Secretary-General Kofi Annan to provide technical assistance to
help Liberia ''monitor and control illicit trading within its
territory.'' Liberia also wants U.N. peacekeeping troops deployed
on its side of the Sierra Leone border to improve monitoring, he
said.
</P>
<P>
   Kafando said Burkina Faso is ''ready and willing'' to receive
investigators from the United Nations or any other source.
</P>
<P>
   Burkina Faso also needs international expertise to address the
problem of diamond trafficking and has asked for radar to better
monitor its airports, he said.
</P>
<P>
   But closing the diamond traffic through other nations is just
part of the overall solution to severing the link between diamonds
and war, representatives from governments, the diamond industry and
private organizations told Tuesday's session.
</P>
<P>
   U.S. Deputy Assistant Secretary of State for African Affairs
Howard Jeter said Sierra Leone must also deal with official
corruption, and the international diamond markets must address
''the larger issue of the lack of transparency and
accountability.''
</P>
<P>
   Britain's U.N. Ambassador Jeremy Greenstock questioned whether a
system to certify Sierra Leone diamonds could work without a global
system to certify the origin of every diamond in the world -- a
system that until now does not exist.
</P>
<P>
   Still, Jeter said closing the illegal routes was a priority.
</P>
<P>
   ''Rough diamonds from Sierra Leone will continue to seek the
most profitable route to market,'' he said. ''Illicit routes -- and
in particular those that facilitate the diamonds-for-arms trade --
must be shut down.''
</P>
<P>
   Annan announced appointments Tuesday to a five-member panel to
collect information on possible violations of the arms embargo and
the link between the diamond trade and arms. It will be chaired by
Martin Chungong Ayafor of Cameroon.
</P>
<P>
   Calling the situation in Sierra Leone ''dangerous and
volatile,'' the secretary-general said achieving a durable peace in
Sierra Leone will require a politicial solution ''based on a robust
and credible international military presence.''
</P>
<P>
   The United States opposes any increase in the U.N. peacekeeping
force in Sierra Leone, which is nearing its 13,000-strong ceiling.
But Annan said in a report to the Security Council Tuesday that he
remains convinced the force should be beefed up and would make a
recommendation shortly.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-08-01-00 2143 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000801.0199 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-01 21:45 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Japan Test Flight Arrives in Cuba  </HEADLINE>
By VIVIAN SEQUERA
<TEXT>
<P>
   HAVANA (AP) -- Dozens of travel agents, journalists and tourists
arrived in Cuba Tuesday evening on the first of four Japanese
flights aimed at discovering whether this Caribbean island could
become a major tourism destination for Asian travelers.
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, the flights will help expose the Cuban people
to people and customs from another part of the world, said Kenya
Uno, chief political and economic officer for the Japanese Embassy
in Havana.
</P>
<P>
   Each of the four charter flights of Boeing 747 jets owned by
Japan Airlines will carry up to 350 passengers. The first flight
carried 286 travelers.
</P>
<P>
   The visits are the result of an agreement between the airline
and the state-operated Cuban tourism company Cubanacan. For the
visits to continue after the initial flights, there will have to be
enough Japanese interested to make the trips worth the cost, Uno
said.
</P>
<P>
   The four trial trips call for five days on the island, with
visits to the beach resort of Varadero and the colonial city of
Trinidad, as well as the capital Havana.
</P>
<P>
   Traveling on the first flight were members of the board of
directors of Japan Airlines, as well as Masatake Kusamichi, member
of the board of directors of the Nissho-Iwai corporation, which is
among the 10 largest commercial firms in Japan. Nissho-Iwai is also
the principal commercial creditor of Cuba.
</P>
<P>
   About 4,000 Japanese visited Cuba last year, and that number
could surpass 5,000 this year, according to Japanese Embassy
estimates. Japanese officials add that much will depend on the kind
of attention received by the Japanese visitors, who are accustomed
to first-class service.
</P>
<P>
   So far the service in Cuba, Uno said, ''does not reach that
level.''
</P>
<P>
   To prepare for the first wave of Japanese visitors, the chef
from the Japanese ambassador's residence in Havana gave a three-day
course in sushi preparation to the chefs at one of the capital's
best hotels, the Melia Cohiba.
</P>
<P>
   As for the Cubans chefs' first efforts at sushi, said Uno, ''We
tasted it ... and frankly, it turned out very well.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-08-01-00 2145 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000801.0200 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-01 21:49 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Witness: Teitelbaum, Doherty have hotel confrontation  </HEADLINE>
By JESSE J. HOLLAND
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHILADELPHIA (AP) - While the talk is of compassion and unity at
the Republican National Convention, things aren't running quite so
smoothly among New York's attendees.
</P>
<P>
   According to two witnesses, tempers flared in the New York GOP's
convention hotel lobby Monday night as one of Gov. George Pataki's
top aides had a verbal confrontation with the manager of New York
City Mayor Rudy Giuliani's aborted U.S. Senate campaign.
</P>
<P>
   The confrontation between Bruce Teitelbaum, the Giuliani
official, and Thomas Doherty, Pataki's chief patronage dispenser,
occurred in the lobby of the Warwick Hotel shortly before midnight,
according to Leonard Guttman, a vice president with the New York
City Health and Hospitals Corporation.
</P>
<P>
   Teitelbaum refused to comment Tuesday on the incident. A
spokeswoman for Pataki denied there had been any confrontation.
</P>
<P>
   Guttman said he was talking with Teitelbaum in the Warwick
lobby.
</P>
<P>
   ''Governor Pataki had walked in and was going up the elevator
and then a moment later this guy comes up and starts shouting at
Bruce, shouting in a very agitated way - verbally abusive,'' the
Giuliani administration aide said.
</P>
<P>
   Guttman said he was told after the incident by Teitelbaum and
another person that the man doing the shouting was Doherty.
</P>
<P>
   ''I never met him in my life,'' Guttman said.
</P>
<P>
   Guttman said the encounter lasted ''a few minutes, or at least
it felt that way.''
</P>
<P>
   He added, ''Bruce held his cool ... . At the end, they just
walked away'' from each other, Guttman said.
</P>
<P>
   Another source familiar with the incident and speaking only on
condition of anonymity said Doherty accused the ''Giuliani camp''
of being responsible for a story in Monday's New York Post saying
Pataki was working behind the scenes to replace state GOP Chairman
William Powers with Doherty.
</P>
<P>
   Pataki, Powers and other Republicans have denied the story.
</P>
<P>
   Pataki spokeswoman Zenia Mucha denied there had been any
confrontation.
</P>
<P>
   ''This is such an out-and-out lie,'' Mucha said. ''He and Tom
had a 15-second conversation and Tom kept going.''
</P>
<P>
   She refused to make Doherty available for comment.
</P>
<P>
   Last year, the state settled a lawsuit against Doherty and
others for more than $150,000 stemming from an argument he got into
in 1996 with a state worker in an Albany bar.
</P>
<P>
   The employee, who was subsequently fired, said Doherty had vowed
during their argument that she would lose her job. The employee, as
part of the settlement, was given a new state job.
</P>
<P>
   Relations between the Pataki and Giuliani camps have been
strained ever since 1994, when the Republican mayor crossed party
lines to endorse then-Gov. Mario Cuomo in his bid for a fourth
term.
</P>
<P>
   Pataki beat Cuomo, a Democrat, in that race to become governor.
---
</P>
<P>
   Eds: Associated Press Political Writer Marc Humbert contributed
to this story.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
