<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-01 21:55 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Israel Inagurates New President  </HEADLINE>
By RON KAMPEAS
<TEXT>
<P>
   JERUSALEM (AP) -- Israel's new president was inaugurated Tuesday
and pledged to maintain peace at home while Israel's government
pursues peace with its neighbors.
</P>
<P>
   ''I believe you chose me to bring peace among us,'' Moshe Katsav
told legislators, adding that making peace with the Arabs was best
left to parliament and the Cabinet.
</P>
<P>
   That was a veiled reference to former Prime Minister and Nobel
peace laureate Shimon Peres, whom Katsav defeated Monday in a poll
of the Knesset's 120 legislators.
</P>
<P>
   Peres was the nominee of Prime Minister Ehud Barak's government,
and was expected to promote Barak's far-reaching proposals to
finalize peace with the Palestinians and the Syrians. Katsav's
Likud party said that was inappropriate for the largely ceremonial
presidency.
</P>
<P>
   The peace process has riven Israelis, and Katsav has said he
would put aside his own hard-line beliefs and work to mend the
wounds.
</P>
<P>
   He mentioned the 1995 assassination of peace architect Prime
Minister Yitzhak Rabin by an ultranationalist Jew, and he suggested
that his countrymen -- still mired in shrill debate -- had learned
nothing from that tragedy.
</P>
<P>
   ''Have we learned the lesson of this abominable murder?'' he
asked.
</P>
<P>
   One reason for Katsav's victory was his appeal -- as an observant
Jew -- to the Knesset's 22 ultra-Orthodox lawmakers.
</P>
<P>
   He wore a skullcap during the swearing-in, even though it is not
a religious ceremony, and told legislators that he believed the
Jews had survived centuries in exile ''only because our ancestors
kept the commandments.''
</P>
<P>
   He said one of his goals would be to reinforce Israel's ties to
Diaspora Jews.
</P>
<P>
   ''We must act to increase their attachment to Israel and
Judaism, each year thousands abandon Judaism and become alienated
from it,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Katsav, 54, was born in Iran, and is the first president to come
from among the Jews who immigrated from Muslim countries and who
suffered discrimination at the hands of the European Jewish
establishment in the first years of the state.
</P>
<P>
   Ezer Weizman, who was president until last month, congratulated
Katsav and said his election was a sign that Israel had overcome
such social distinctions.
</P>
<P>
   ''Once Israel was divided into 'ours' and 'others','' said
Weizman, himself a scion of the establishment. ''No longer: the
definition of 'others' is not worthy.''
</P>
<P>
   Weizman's term was cut short by three years after he admitted to
taking hundreds of thousands of dollars in cash gifts from a
millionaire French friend. A police report recommended against
prosecution, but suggested he should step down.
</P>
<P>
   ''Try not to get into trouble,'' Weizman cracked to Katsav.
''It's not easy''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
