<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Councilman charged with drunken driving  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	   DUMONT, N.J. (AP) - A Dumont councilman was charged with drunken
driving on Tuesday after Bergen County prosecutors began an
investigation into whether the borough's mayor and police chief
tried to squash his arrest.
</P>
<P>
   Philip Fredericks, who serves as the council's liaison to the
police department, was charged with driving while intoxicated,
careless driving, failure to keep right and failure to wear a seat
belt for allegedly driving drunk on July 22.
</P>
<P>
   Prosecutors directed police to issue the charges as a result of
the investigation into the incident, Assistant Bergen County
Prosecutor Lucia Van Wetering said.
</P>
<P>
   The office has questioned Mayor Donald Winant and Police Chief
Michael Affrunti after learning that Fredericks was taken into
custody, then released.
</P>
<P>
   Law enforcement sources have told The Record of Hackensack that
Affrunti ordered police to release Fredericks while officers were
processing charges against him.
</P>
<P>
   Fredericks didn't return a message left at his office Tuesday.
His home telephone rang unanswered. Winant and Affrunti also didn't
return telephone messages Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   Sources who spoke on condition of anonymity told The Record that
officers found Fredericks sleeping at the wheel of his sports
utility vehicle outside a Knights of Columbus lodge, drove him
home, then later spotted him weaving along the road in his car.
Fredericks failed a roadside sobriety test, the sources said.
</P>
<P>
   After Fredericks was arrested, Affrunti came from home into the
station and ordered police to release him, the sources said. Winant
arrived to drive Fredericks home, the sources said.
</P>
<P>
   Affrunti told a reporter last week that Fredericks was never
pulled over, The Record said.
</P>
<P>
   Fredericks faces a Sept. 13 appearance in municipal court on the
charges. Penalties for the most serious offense, driving while
intoxicated, range from 30 days to six months in jail and the loss
of a driver's license for six months to 10 years.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
