<HEADLINE> Brazilian Oil Giant Fined $94M  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   RIO DE JANEIRO, Brazil (AP) -- The government has fined federal
oil giant Petrobras $94 million for causing the country's worst oil
spill in 25 years, a news agency reported Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   The federal Environmental Protection Agency ordered Petrobras to
pay the amount over three years for a spill earlier this month that
damaged some 370 acres of a preserved area along the Iguacu River,
in southern Brazil, and killed some of the river's fauna, Estado
news agency reported.
</P>
<P>
   It took workers several days to contain the more than 1 million
gallons of crude oil that spewed from a burst Petrobras pipeline at
the Getulio Vargas refinery in Araucaria, about 435 miles southwest
of Rio.
</P>
<P>
   The government fined Petrobras $28 million in January, when an
underwater oil pipe broke and spewed at least 340,000 gallons of
crude into Rio's famous Guanabara Bay and through protected
mangrove swamps.
</P>
<P>
   Brazil's worst oil disaster was in 1975, when an oil tanker from
Iraq dumped nearly 8 million gallons of crude into the bay and
forced the closure of Rio's famous beaches for nearly three weeks.
</P>
</TEXT>
