<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-01 22:14 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> DEC says zebra mussels are declining  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	   WATERTOWN, N.Y. (AP) - They still number in the billions, but
zebra mussel populations around New York are declining, state
environmental officials say.
</P>
<P>
   Although New York State Department of Environmental officials
stopped counting the quarter-inch, black-and-white-striped zebra
mussels in 1995 because there simply were too many, Steve R. LaPan,
Lake Ontario unit leader for the DEC, said their numbers have
stopped increasing.
</P>
<P>
   The reason? Not enough to eat.
</P>
<P>
   And, according to information obtained from recent dives in the
lake, the mussels also are up to 11 millimeters smaller.
</P>
<P>
   Power and water plants have spent $100 million a year to install
filtration and chemical systems to eliminate zebra mussel problems
in their water systems. Still, the pesky creatures have
irreversibly altered the aquatic ecosystem, concentrating toxins in
algae and eliminating native clams.
</P>
<P>
   ''Our system will never go back to what it was,'' said Edward L.
Mills, director of a Cornell University field station on Oneida
Lake. ''Native species are being lost and contaminants are
concentrated. We have 20 percent of the world's fresh water in this
area. We need to do everything we can to protect those systems
because they ultimately affect our health and well-being.''
</P>
<P>
   Scientists say that the scarcity of food is causing quagga
mussels to replace zebra mussels. Quagga mussels are similar in
size but are round on the bottom, instead of flat, and feed on a
greater variety of zooplankton, which makes lake waters clearer.
</P>
<P>
   ''They are vaccum cleaners taking food to a lower level,'' Mills
said.
</P>
<P>
   In Oneida Lake, bass populations are increasing because the
clearer water encourages aquatic plant growth, Mills said.
</P>
<P>
   However, clearer water doesn't mean cleaner water. Airborne and
groundwater toxins, including PCB and mercury, are becoming
concentrated at the bottoms of lakes in the remaining algae plants.
It's possible that an increase in contamination in algae plants
eventually will lead to an increase in contamination in the fish
that feed on those plants.
</P>
<P>
   Clearer water also may contribute to increased mortality in fish
larvae because they are more vulnerable to being found and eaten by
other fish. A decrease in large clams also is evident in Lake
Ontario.
</P>
<P>
   ''Some clam beds are full of empty shells,'' LaPan said.
''(Zebra mussels attach to clams and) literally steal food out of
their mouth.''
</P>
<P>
   Impact of the loss of clams has not been determined, but LaPan
said he doesn't believe it will have a direct impact on the fish
system. However, parasites and grubs that clams harbor, and
muskrats that feed on clams may be affected, he said.
</P>
<P>
   With the introduction of such exotics as the zebra mussel, the
Great Lakes are becoming more like the Black, Caspian and Baltic
seas of Europe. Changing ballast in the Atlantic Ocean before
entering the Great Lakes system has improved since the policy
became mandatory, said Charles R. O'Neil, senior extension
associate with Sea Grant. But the system is not foolproof. Some
exotics still remain in the sludge at the bottoms of boats.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-08-01-00 2214 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
