<DOCNO> APW20000801.0211 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-01 22:38 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Teddy Roosevelt's great-grandson speaks to GOP convention  </HEADLINE>
By JESSE J. HOLLAND
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHILADELPHIA (AP) - President Theodore Roosevelt was a national
icon, and as a former New York governor, a source of pride for the
entire state.
</P>
<P>
   His great-grandson, Theodore Roosevelt IV, entered the national
political arena Tuesday night by giving a prime-time speech about
protecting the environment, a cause closely linked to President
Roosevelt.
</P>
<P>
   ''It is encouraging that the Republican Party is granting
prime-time attention to issues concerning environmental protection
and conservation of our natural resources,'' said Roosevelt, an
investment banker and chairman of the League of Conservation
Voters. ''Few issues so closely affect our quality of life.''
</P>
<P>
   Roosevelt's 2-minute speech focused on environmental concerns.
</P>
<P>
   ''Some of the world's best scientists give us 20, maybe 30,
years to turn back the tide on ecological devastation,'' Roosevelt
said.
</P>
<P>
   ''But, I daresay, most conservation advocates are not driven
simply by a desire to see our species survive a few more years. No.
Humankind as the great exterminator is simply not a role with which
we can live.''
</P>
<P>
   Roosevelt also is a New York delegate to the convention.
</P>
<P>
   President Roosevelt led America into foreign affairs with a
motto of ''speak softly and carry a big stick,'' and domestically
became a ''trust buster,'' breaking up railroad and other
monopolies. He won the Nobel Peace Prize in 1906 for mediating a
peace to the Russo-Japanese War. He is also known in New York state
as a conservationist after adding greatly to national park land and
western forests and preserving New York's wilderness in the 6
million acre Adirondack Park.
</P>
<P>
   The Roosevelts aren't the only New Yorkers with a family
connection at the convention.
</P>
<P>
   One of the featured speakers Thursday night is U.S. Rep. Vito
Fossella, who will talk about Social Security. His
great-grandfather, former U.S. Rep. James O'Leary, cast a vote in
the House of Representatives to help create Social Security.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
