<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-01 22:45 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Bus crash on West 34th Street leaves 34 injured  </HEADLINE>
By LUKAS I. ALPERT
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) - A city bus careened onto the sidewalk and into a
building Tuesday evening injuring 34 people, one critically,
including a NYPD traffic agent.
</P>
<P>
   Witnesses described seeing the eastbound M-34 bus lose control
shortly after crossing Ninth Avenue on 34th Street. The bus
careened into a parked car, hitting the traffic agent who witnesses
said was leaning into the window of the car talking with the
driver.
</P>
<P>
   The bus then jumped the curb, crashed through a fifteen-foot
tree and then a planter, smashing into the entrance of a Solomon
Smith Barney building, and finally coming to rest in front of a
garage.
</P>
<P>
   The traffic agent fell away from the bus and was not run over,
said Richard Sheirer, director of the city's Office of Emergency
Management.
</P>
<P>
   The traffic agent was brought to Bellevue Hospital and was
listed in serious but stable condition, authorities said. The bus
driver was brought to St. Vincent's, where he was listed in
critical condition.
</P>
<P>
   Twenty-six others were taken to area hospitals, none with
life-threatening injuries. Six people refused medical treatment,
authorities said.
</P>
<P>
   Other than the driver and traffic agent - who was on the street
- the other 32 injured were all passenger on the bus, authorities
said.
</P>
<P>
   ''I saw the bus jump up on the sidewalk and through the trees.
He didn't even slow down,'' said Jean Bolcy, 34, who works around
the corner from where the accident happened.
</P>
<P>
   ''If he hadn't hit that wall, he'd still be going,'' Bolcy
added, saying he thought he saw the bus driver slumped over the
wheel before the bus came to rest.
</P>
<P>
   Afterward, passengers ''were jumping out of the windows of the
bus and running,'' Bolcy said.
</P>
<P>
   The wreck happened just after 7 p.m. and halted traffic on the
block for over two hours while dozens of Emergency Medical Service
workers tended to the injured in the shadow of the bus' crumpled
remains.
</P>
<P>
   ''If there's one thing you can say about this it's that this may
be a true miracle on 34th street, that you could have a city bus go
up on the sidewalk at 7 o'clock on a warm summer night and have
only one person get hit,'' Sheirer said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-08-01-00 2245 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000801.0213 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-01 22:54 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> 4th OSU Player Arrested in Beating  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   CORVALLIS, Ore. (AP) -- A fourth Oregon State football player was
arrested Tuesday in the beating of another student.
</P>
<P>
   Corvallis police said Dennis Weathersby, 20, turned himself in
to police Tuesday and is charged with third-degree assault.
</P>
<P>
   Weathersby was a freshman cornerback for the Beavers last
season. He broke up 17 passes -- two shy of the school record.
</P>
<P>
   Three Oregon State receivers -- Robert Prescott, Alton ''Junior''
Adams and James Newson -- were charged with third-degree assault in
the case last month.
</P>
<P>
   Third-degree assault is a Class C felony that carries a maximum
prison term of five years.
</P>
<P>
   The players are accused of beating Victor Becerra, 21, at a
Corvallis house party on July 22. He was treated at a hospital for
injuries to the face.
</P>
<P>
   Coach Dennis Erickson announced last week that Prescott and
Adams have been suspended indefinitely from competition. He did not
suspend Newson.
</P>
<P>
   Oregon State athletic officials did not return calls Tuesday
night about Weathersby's status with the team.
</P>
</TEXT>
