<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-01 22:54 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Ohio St. To Retire Player's Numbers  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   COLUMBUS, Ohio (AP) -- Heisman Trophy winners Howard ''Hopalong''
Cassady and Vic Janowicz will become the second and third Ohio
State football players to have their numbers officially retired.
</P>
<P>
   The school said Tuesday that Janowicz's No. 31 will be retired
during halftime of a game against Penn State on Sept. 23.
</P>
<P>
   On Nov. 18, Cassady's No. 40 will be retired during halftime
ceremonies of Ohio State's regular season finale against Michigan.
</P>
<P>
   The only Ohio State football player to have his number retired
is Archie Griffin, the 1974 and 1975 Heisman Trophy winner. The
only two-time winner of the Heisman, Griffin wore No. 45.
</P>
<P>
   Janowicz won the Heisman Trophy in 1950. In that season, he
scored 16 touchdowns and accounted for 875 yards in total offense.
In an 83-21 victory over Iowa, he scored two touchdowns, passed for
four and set a Big Ten record with 10 extra points.
</P>
<P>
   Janowicz, a member of the Ohio State Athletic Hall of Fame and
the National Football Foundation Hall of Fame, died in February
1996.
</P>
<P>
   In 1954, Cassady rushed for 701 yards and eight touchdowns and
averaged 5.7 yards per carry, earning him unanimous All-America
honors.
</P>
<P>
   The following year, Cassady again was an All-America after
rushing for 964 yards and 15 touchdowns and won the Heisman Trophy.
</P>
<P>
   Cassady currently lives in Tampa, Fla., but returns to Columbus
in the summer to serve as a coach for the Columbus Clippers, the
top farm team of the New York Yankees.
</P>
<P>
   Ohio State has had two other Heisman Trophy winners: Les Horvath
in 1944 and Eddie George in 1995.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
