<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-01 23:01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.S. Embassy To Move to Jerusalem  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   JERUSALEM (AP) -- The United States plans to move its embassy
from Tel Aviv to Jerusalem by Jan. 20, the day President Clinton
leaves office, Prime Minister Ehud Barak said Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   Barak told Israel television he understood the United States
''will rent offices by Jan. 20, and they will build an embassy.''
</P>
<P>
   When asked about Barak's statement, State Department spokeswoman
Victoria DeLong and White House spokesman P.J. Crowley both said
they had no information that a final decision had been made on such
a move.
</P>
<P>
   The two officials referred back to Clinton's statement Friday
that he intends to review moving the embassy and that he will make
a decision by the end of the year.
</P>
<P>
   Barak mentioned the embassy move as among the positive results
of the failed U.S.-mediated summit at Camp David with the
Palestinians.
</P>
<P>
   In the wake of the summit, Clinton said Friday he was putting
the embassy move ''under review and I'll make a decision sometime
between now and the end of the year on that.'' The statement
apparently aimed to support Barak, embattled by hard-liners at home
who say he offered too many concessions at Camp David.
</P>
<P>
   The embassy move would lend support to Israeli claims to the
city -- and would infuriate many in the Muslim world. Protests broke
out in some Palestinian cities after Clinton's statement and some
militant groups have threatened to target U.S. diplomats if the
United States moved its embassy.
</P>
<P>
   After the Camp David talks fell apart, Clinton also warned the
Palestinians not to follow through with their pledge to declare
statehood unilaterally on Sept. 13, if there is no agreement by
that deadline for a final peace deal. Clinton said the move would
be a ''big mistake'' and said the ''entire relationship'' with the
Palestinians would be reviewed.
</P>
<P>
   He also suggested the Palestinians were more to blame for the
failure of Camp David, by not moving as Israel had on the sensitive
issue of Jerusalem. Both sides softened positions on other core
issues, including refugees and borders.
</P>
<P>
   Barak agreed to extend limited sovereignty to the Palestinians
in some of the city's Arab neighborhoods. Palestinian leader Yasser
Arafat insisted on full sovereignty throughout east Jerusalem,
including the ultrasensitive walled Old City, home to sites holy to
Muslims, Christians and Jews. Arafat has blamed Israel for the
summit's failure, saying he refused to go far enough on Jerusalem.
</P>
<P>
   Barak said that the Muslim quarter of the Old City, and Sheik
Jarrah -- an Arab area abutting the walls of the Old City -- were not
on the table ''at this point.''
</P>
<P>
   Not ruling out discussion of those areas was a large step by
Barak from the stance of earlier governments -- which long
considered those areas the sacred core of their commitment to
Jerusalem. Some in the Israeli opposition say Barak has gone too
far and are calling for early elections.
</P>
<P>
   Barak also said that a multibillion dollar fund set up by the
United States and European nations to compensate Palestinian made
refugees by Israel's 1948 independence war would also compensate
Jews driven out of Arab countries after the war.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-08-01-00 2301 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000801.0220 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-01 23:04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Dole Pays Tribute to War Heroes  </HEADLINE>
By MIKE FEINSILBER
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHILADELPHIA (AP) -- Eyes glistening, Bob Dole spoke to the
Republican Party Tuesday on behalf of hundreds of thousands of
''voiceless heroes'' who never came home from wars. He said that
wearing this nation's uniform in battle was a greater honor than
winning his party's presidential nomination.
</P>
<P>
   In paying tribute to his comrades in arms, Dole, 77, also hailed
young Americans, ''heroes in waiting.''
</P>
<P>
   ''Don't be fooled by their wardrobe or their music,'' he
advised. ''They are as great a generation as this nation has ever
produced.''
</P>
<P>
   ''Even as we meet, they are fighting quiet wars of their own,
combating poverty, prejudice, isolation and indulgence. My fondest
hope is that all their challenges are posed in community service,
in classrooms and research labs, not on foreign battlefields.''
</P>
<P>
   The moment could only have been emotional for both Dole and his
wife, Elizabeth. He was swamped by Bill Clinton in the presidential
election of 1996; she tried to win the GOP's presidential
nomination last year, but quit the race in October.
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. Dole was seated with former Presidents Ford and Bush. She
seemed to be wistful.
</P>
<P>
   In her own moment at the podium, Mrs. Dole saluted George W.
Bush, this convention's sure nominee, as one who will ''put an end
to the smash-mouth politics of recent years and to the name-calling
that tarnishes our trust.''
</P>
<P>
   Later, Dole admitted having his voice catch toward the end of
his address as he talked about veterans. ''You try not to look at
people you know in the audience,'' he said in an interview.
</P>
<P>
   Dole was one of 671,846 U.S. servicemen wounded in combat in
World War II -- another 292,132 were killed -- and he said he was
''honored to speak for these voiceless heroes, and for their
comrades who survived the deadliest war ever inflicted on the human
family.''
</P>
<P>
   Dole virtually lost use of an arm in combat in Italy. His spine
was crushed, and his shoulder, arm and collarbone were broken. He
was unable to move and nearly bled to death.
</P>
<P>
   Dole expressed his determination to see the construction of a
memorial to World War II veterans on the Mall in Washington, near
the Lincoln Memorial, a controversial site.
</P>
<P>
   But he said the real memorial to servicemen was not made of
pillars or arches.
</P>
<P>
   ''It is to be found everywhere: at this convention and in the
upcoming one in Los Angeles, and in the November election, and
every time free men and women assemble to determine their
destiny.''
</P>
<P>
   Dole summed up why he remains -- as he proclaimed himself in 1996
-- ''the most optimistic man in America.''
</P>
<P>
   ''I have seen Americans split the atom, abolish Jim Crow,
eliminate the scourge of polio, win the Cold War, plant our flag on
the surface of the moon, belatedly recognize the talents of women
and others once relegated to the shadows, develop the Internet,
lead The Information Age, and map the human genome.''
</P>
<P>
   Dole started with a quip about his failed 1996 campaign:
''There's still time for a recount.''
</P>
<P>
   Then the band played the Army, Navy, Marine and Air Force
service anthems while veterans of those services stood. Dole got a
standing ovation. He finished, ''My fellow Americans, this proud
veteran salutes you.'' He gave the audience a crisp military salute
and marched off.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-08-01-00 2304 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000801.0221 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-01 23:09 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Obituaries in the News  </HEADLINE>
By The Associated PressWilliam Maxwell:
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- William Maxwell, the revered editor of such New
Yorker writers as J.D. Salinger and John Cheever and himself an
accomplished man of letters, died Monday. He was 91.
</P>
<P>
   Maxwell's death came eight days after the death of his wife,
Emily, to whom he was married for 55 years.
</P>
<P>
   Hired in 1937 by The New Yorker's Katharine White, a founding
editor and the wife of E.B. White, Maxwell was on staff for 40
years and worked with some of the magazine's most celebrated
authors, including Salinger, Cheever, John O'Hara, John Updike and
Harold Brodkey.
</P>
<P>
   In ''About Town,'' a history of The New Yorker published this
year, author Ben Yagoda noted that Maxwell's correspondence with
writers ''exudes a palpable empathy.'' For many, Maxwell was the
ideal editor, a man of civilized temperament and compassionate
rigor.
</P>
<P>
   Cheever and Brodkey were among those who dedicated books to
Maxwell.
</P>
<P>
   Maxwell's career as an author preceded his time at The New
Yorker. His first novel, ''Bright Center of Heaven,'' was published
in 1934. Subsequent books included the story collections ''Billie
Dyer'' and ''Over by the River,'' and the 1980 novel, ''So Long,
See You Tomorrow,'' which won the American Book Award.
Derek Hill:
</P>
<P>
   LONDON (AP) -- Derek Hill, an English artist who did costume
designs for several well-known plays and painted portraits of
Prince Charles, died Sunday. He was 83.
</P>
<P>
   Hill's stage work includes costume designs for ''Castor and
Pollux'' at the Oxford University Opera Club in 1935, the ballet
''The Lord of Burleigh'' at Sadler's Wells in London in 1937 and
''Il Trovatore'' at Covent Garden in 1947.
</P>
<P>
   In 1956, he began to spend much of his time on Ireland's remote
Tory Island, based in a primitive hut, painting both the rugged
landscape and the people.
</P>
<P>
   Hill was made an honorary citizen of Ireland in 1999.
</P>
<P>
   He twice painted portraits of Prince Charles, and the two men
occasionally painted together.
</P>
<P>
   Other portrait subjects included Earl Mountbatten, Bernard
Berenson, Yehudi Menuhin, Michael Tippett, John Betjeman and
Frederick Ashton.
Leah Welch:
</P>
<P>
   MINNEAPOLIS (AP) -- Leah Welch, who was paralyzed by polio in
1949 and later dedicated herself to making life better for people
with disabilities, died Friday. She was 76.
</P>
<P>
   Welch lobbied legislators and members of Congress on behalf of
the disabled and was invited to the White House to witness
President Bush sign the Americans With Disabilities Act in 1990.
</P>
<P>
   Despite being paralyzed from the neck down and spending her last
16 years on a ventilator, Welch was active and spoke frequently to
groups about the needs of disabled people.
</P>
<P>
   She founded Independence Crossroads, which helped find personal
care attendants for disabled people. The business now does mostly
in-home counseling and advocacy for the disabled.
John Wells:
</P>
<P>
   LONDON (AP) -- John Wells, a doctor and member of the established
St. Ives artists' community in England, died July 27. He was 92.
</P>
<P>
   Wells was raised in an artists' colony and went on to study
medicine while taking evening classes in life drawing. After
qualifying as a doctor, he set up a practice on the remote Scilly
Isles, off the southwest tip of England, continuing to paint part
time.
</P>
<P>
   Wells' work drew on the area's rugged landscape of sea and rock,
and was influenced by the Russian Constructivists, with their lines
and geometrical shapes.
</P>
<P>
   After World War II, in which he served as a Royal Navy medial
officer, he took up painting full time.
</P>
<P>
   In 1946, he founded the Crypt Group, a collection of modernists
within the community of St. Ives in Cornwall. He had his first
London show in 1946, and gained recognition in Britain and abroad
throughout the 1950s.
Pinkie Wilkerson:
</P>
<P>
   BOSSIER CITY, La. (AP) -- Democratic state Rep. Pinkie Wilkerson,
a three-term lawmaker and former state attorney general, was killed
Tuesday when a truck slammed into the back of her car. She was 52.
</P>
<P>
   Wilkerson had been a House member since 1992, representing all
or parts of Claiborne, Bienville, Lincoln and Union parishes.
</P>
<P>
   She was vice chairman of the House Health and Welfare Committee
and a member of the civil law and judiciary committees. She pushed
legislation dealing with child abuse and neglect, foster children
and battered women.
</P>
<P>
   Wilkerson had been slated to be a delegate to the Democratic
National Convention in Los Angeles this month. She was a delegate
to the 1996 party convention in Chicago.
</P>
<P>
   At the time of her election to the House in 1991, Wilkerson was
an assistant district attorney and worked as an assistant state
attorney general during the 1980s.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-08-01-00 2309 </TRAILER>
