<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-01 23:10 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Dole Is Back and He's Loose  </HEADLINE>
By CALVIN WOODWARD
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHILADELPHIA (AP) -- Leave it to Bob Dole to break through all
that's scripted at the Republican convention and drop a few ad
libs.
</P>
<P>
   Taking the stage Tuesday night to pay tribute to the military,
the 1996 Republican presidential candidate spoke without the weight
of expectations, having ''no agenda and no greater ambition.''
</P>
<P>
   That seems to have loosened him up.
</P>
<P>
   ''There's still time for a recount,'' he cracked, referring to
his sound defeat at the hands of President Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   He said South Carolina Sen. Strom Thurmond, 97, ''took me to
Constitution Hall and showed me where he first met Ben Franklin.''
</P>
<P>
   Since the 1996 campaign, Dole has been busy raising money for a
World War II memorial on Washington's Mall, serving as an
intermediary in the Balkans, writing a book on political humor and
making commercials for a male impotence drug.
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   Minnesota: ''Land of 10,000 lakes and one goofy governor!''
</P>
<P>
   Nebraska: ''Only state never visited by Bill Clinton since he's
been president!''
</P>
<P>
   The roll call of the states, the way the nominee is officially
chosen, is different this year, spread out over three nights
instead of packed into one.
</P>
<P>
   But it's still a chance for delegates to make a plug for the
home state and take a swipe at the other party.
</P>
<P>
   ''Massachusetts: Bedrock of Republicanism,'' it was boldly
announced by a representative of that Democratic state.
</P>
<P>
   Maine was declared ''Governor Bush's beachhead.'' The convention
was told: ''As Maine goes, so goes the nation.''
</P>
<P>
   As for Clinton's no-show in Nebraska, the White House has said
he hopes to get there eventually.
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   Someone batted a red, white and blue beach ball up to Bush's
running mate, Dick Cheney, sitting with his family in the first row
above the floor.
</P>
<P>
   He caught it and didn't seem to know quite what to do with it.
He held it for a minute, then put it down, eventually passing it
along to one of his grandchildren.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
