<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Mass. Delegate Sticks With McCain  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHILADELPHIA (AP) -- Dr. Dwight Stowell Jr. knew it was a vote
wasted, but the Massachusetts delegate cast his ballot for Sen.
John McCain anyway at the Republican convention Tuesday, going
against McCain's own wishes.
</P>
<P>
   After two days of balloting, Stowell is the only delegate to
support McCain instead of Texas Gov. George W. Bush. Six votes have
been cast for Alan Keyes.
</P>
<P>
   ''I thought about it a lot and I've been hammered all day by
McCain's own people to vote for Bush, but in the end I took a page
out of John's book,'' said Stowell, a physician from Royalston,
Mass.
</P>
<P>
   ''He said that there are some issues that are greater than the
individual, and so I just decided to go ahead and do what I thought
was right.''
</P>
<P>
   Stowell said he wanted to send a message to Bush about the need
for campaign finance reform.
</P>
<P>
   ''We want him to be elected but we want him to be elected
talking about campaign finance reform,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   McCain defeated George W. Bush in Massachusetts' March primary.
Before the convention, McCain asked all his supporters to unite
behind Bush. Charles Shemchuk of Athol, another Massachusetts
delegate who had backed McCain, abstained.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
