<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-01 23:25 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Fire Blackens Mexico Baja Peninsula  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   TECATE, Mexico (AP) -- Mexican army and navy units have joined
firefighters in battling a blaze that has blackened 37,000 acres in
a remote mountainous area near the U.S. border, an official said
Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   The fire crews have the blaze in northern Baja California state
70 percent controlled and expect to have it under full control by
the end of the week, said Alfredo Escobedo, the director of the
Baja California Office of Civil Protection.
</P>
<P>
   The size of the fire makes it among the worst in the last 10
years in Baja California, but few people live in the area and it
does not pose a significant threat to any communities, Escobedo
said.
</P>
<P>
   Three firefighters suffered minor injuries in the fire, 30 miles
south of the U.S.-Mexico border in the Sierra de Juarez, the
mountain chain that runs down the center of the Baja peninsula.
</P>
<P>
   A man who may have caused the fire by allowing a campfire to get
out of control has been taken into custody by state authorities, he
said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
