<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Bronx serial rapist gets 155 years to life  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	   NEW YORK (AP) - The serial rapist who police were looking for
the night Amadou Diallo was shot in the Bronx was sentenced Tuesday
to 155 years to life in prison.
</P>
<P>
   Issac Jones, 39, denied being the rapist who terrorized women in
the Bronx, Manhattan and Mount Vernon during a crime spree that
started in 1994.
</P>
<P>
   Bronx District Attorney Robert Johnson said in a statement: ''By
denying the charges at the time of sentencing, in the face of DNA
evidence and his own confession, it is clear that this defendant
still thinks only of himself. His violent penchant for
self-gratification has caused tremendous damage to the lives of
others.''
</P>
<P>
   Police arrested Jones in April after DNA evidence linked him to
17 attacks on women. He was the suspect four Street Crime Unit
police officers were looking for when they shot and killed an
unarmed Diallo on Feb. 4, 1999.
</P>
<P>
   Jones was convicted on May 2 on several counts of rape, sexual
abuse, robbery and criminal possession of a weapon.
</P>
<P>
   State Supreme Court Justice Joseph Fisch heard sentencing
recommendations on Monday, including a statement from one of Jones'
victims asking ''that he receive the highest sentence applicable by
law.''
</P>
<P>
   Fisch rendered his decision Tuesday, saying he had ''removed
from society a cruel, merciless and dangerous predator who has
ruined many lives and terrorized the community and its honest,
law-abiding citizens for far too many years.''
</P>
<P>
   Jones is still awaiting trial on four other indictments
involving 16 victims in the Bronx, and cases are pending in
Manhattan and Westchester County involving five additional victims.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
